<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Pin-ups     06-06 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Pin-ups,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoners Riot Over Pin-Ups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prisoners ordered to remove pin-up posters from
newly painted walls damaged 28 buildings in an eight-hour riot in
western England and staged Britain's biggest breakout in five years,
officials said Monday.
   ``Nearly every part of the institution has been burned down,''
David Evans, general secretary of the Prison Officers Association,
said on British Broadcasting Corp. radio.
   Twenty-seven convicts escaped from low-security Haverigg Prison
during Sunday night's rioting and arson, but only three remained at
large Monday, said a spokesman for the Home Office, the government
department responsible for prisons and police.
   It was the biggest prison break since 38 convicted members of the
Irish Republican Army escaped from Maze Prison near Belfast,
Northern Ireland, in 1983.
   The Home Office said no guards were hurt at Haverigg, but one
prisoner was sent to the hospital with what looked like a broken jaw
and 10 others were treated for minor injuries at the prison, 280
miles west of London.
   ``There was a rampage by about 100 prisoners after they were told
to take down pin-ups,'' said a Home Office spokesman, speaking
anonymously in keeping with British custom.
   He said the prisoners smashed their rooms, pulled down sections
of the perimeter fence and started fires.
   Scores of police with dogs joined prison guards to encircle the
remote, seaside prison after the riots began about 8 p.m. Sunday and
raged until about 4 a.m. Monday. Firemen waited for hours before
entering the prison because of fears they would be attacked.
   Evans said on the BBC broadcast, ``The kitchen, the clothing
exchange stores, all the education departments, all the things that
the prisoners need for recreation have been burned down and many of
the wings, too, will not be able to house them today or for the very
near future.''
   John Jones, deputy north regional director for the Home Office
Prisons Department, said doors, windows, wash basins, toilets and
asbestos roofs were damaged by prisoners armed with stones and ``any
small implement which came to hand.''
   The prison houses 490 inmates. It is a former air force camp and
is classified as an open prison, a low-security facility used for
prisoners either nearing release or considered not dangerous by
parole boards.
   The 390 prisoners who gave themselves up were sheltered in a
workshop, Cumbria police said. Some were later bused to other
prisons while the damage at Haverigg was cleaned up.
</TEXT>
