<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0001EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FishPact     06-06 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fish Pact,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Crab Fishermen Eye USSR Fishing Grounds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search by American crab fishermen for new,
more productive seas combined with the Soviet Union's interest in
U.S. fishing technology has netted both sides a new fishing
agreement.
   Last week, President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
signed an agreement allowing for joint fishing, management and
conservation in the North Pacific.
   Members of the Alaska Crab Coalition and other American fisheries
groups had negotiated with the Soviet Union for more than a year in
an effort to get an agreement that would allow U.S. fishermen access
to the western Bering Sea.
   Ronald K. Peterson, Seattle-based owner of a crab boat and
president of the Alaska coalition, hopes U.S. crabbers will be able
to forge joint venture agreements with Soviet enterprises and fish
in Soviet water this year. Three Soviet ports would be opened to
American fishermen, he said.
   While U.S. bottomfish fishermen also hope eventually to cast nets
in Soviet waters for pollock, cod and other species, the agreement
with the Soviets is seen as especially beneficial for the crabbers.
   After a big fleet buildup to pursue huge stocks of crab in the
American sector of the Bering Sea in the 1970s, crab populations
dwindled around 1980 for a variety of reasons, including disease and
predators.
   ``In 1980, we took 130 million pounds of red king crab in the
Bering Sea, with 236 boats participating,'' Peterson said. ``Last
year, we had the same number of boats, and they took a little over
12 million pounds.''
   Crab boats cost $2.5 million new and owners need to pull up
$4,000 to $5,000 worth of crabs daily just to break even, said Arni
Thomson, executive director of the coalition, which represents 80
Bering Sea crab boats.
   Peterson said that, initially, 30 American crab boats would
probably be allowed in Soviet waters. Thomson said the Soviets
probably would process the catch.
   The Soviets, said Thomson, will benefit by having greater access
to under-utilized fish species in U.S. fishing areas and by the use
of superior American fishing technology.
   As an example, he said, American crabbers the past five years
have developed new methods of harvesting deep-dwelling snow crab.
Pots are strung together, perhaps 20 at a time, he said, and then
pulled up at once on a common marking buoy _ a departure from the
usual method of each pot being placed separately.
   ``The Soviets do not have that expertise and that is a very
important fishery now to us,'' Thomson said.
   Thomson said he expected that the benefits for American crews of
fishing off Siberia will be over the long term and will provide
stability to the Bering Sea crab fishery.
   The Bering Sea reportedly is the richest bottomfish ground in the
world. Two million metric tons are taken annually on the U.S. side
of the sea, and the Soviet side apparently has an equal-size
resource, said Ted Evans, executive director of the Alaska Factory
Trawler Association in Seattle.
   The loser in the new cooperative agreements could be Japan's
fishermen, who for decades had both Soviet and U.S. waters in the
North Pacific almost to themselves.
   ``The belief (by Americans and Soviets alike) is that Japan has
been a good trading partner, but the Soviets and Americans want
another trading partner in each other, for the competition,''
Peterson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
