<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-Millions     06-06 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Millions,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Find How Much A Million Is</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The magnitude of a trillion-dollar
deficit is a little more comprehensible to David Witte and his
sixth-grade classmates after they tried but failed to collect 1
million bottle caps and pull-tabs.
   Frank Heatwole's students finished the year-long project with
624,720 of the caps and tabs from drink containers.
   ``A million is a lot more than a person thinks,'' David said,
adding that the U.S. government ``is not a million dollars or a
billion but a trillion dollars in debt.''
   Classmate Jay Lippincott agreed.
   ``When I think about a trillion, I don't want to think of it. We
tried and we only got half a million,'' he said. ``I thought we
could do it.''
   The project produced overflowing boxes and barrels of caps and
tabs in the corner of the Lincoln Elementary School classroom.
   Students got friends and relatives to help by donating the caps
or tabs.
   Julie Higgenbothom said organization was the key to collecting so
many items.
   ``I've gotten lots of friends to help, and when you get
organized, it's a snap,'' she said.
   Angela Swartout got both her parents involved. Her mother brought
in a box containing 6,000 tabs and her father contributed a 40-pound
bag of them.
   Restaurants and taverns also helped.
   When collecting ended last week, the 400 pounds of caps and 602
pounds of tabs were taken to a recycling company, which paid the
class $315 for them.
   Part of the proceeds went for a class lunch of pizza. Students
were considering what they wanted to buy with the rest.
</TEXT>
