<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Kean-Veep     06-06 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kean-Veep,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Jersey Governor Offers `Inclusion' To Bush Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One in a series of occasional profiles of vice presidential
prospects</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In seeking the presidency, George Bush may
take a page from the new book by New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean.
   Kean's modern, moderate Republicanism _ as outlined in his
autobiographical book ``The Politics of Inclusion'' _ has caught
Bush's eye.
   That, along with the popular governor's growing national profile,
has put Kean on the so-called short list of potential Bush running
mates.
   The 51-year-old Kean, approaching the end of his second and last
gubernatorial term, is in many ways an automatic contender for the
national ticket.
   Bush, campaigning last month in New Jersey, said, ``Would he have
the qualifications for national office? The answer is clearly yes.''
   As the uncontested head of the Republican Party in his state,
Kean is in a position to deliver a hefty 16 electoral college votes
in November _ enough to get any presidential candidate's attention.
   In 1985, Kean was re-elected by the largest margin in state
history, with unprecedented support among blacks and other
minorities.
   He has headed the Republican Governors Association, and gained
national recognition for his programs. President Reagan, in the
State of the Union message this year, singled out Kean's education
reforms.
   Despite these credentials, many political observers believe the
governor is at best a long shot to round out the Bush ticket.
   Among those voicing the most doubt is Kean himself. He says he's
not campaigning for the job, and doesn't expect to be asked.
   ``I don't think that's going to happen. I'm not doing anything to
make it happen,'' he insisted in Washington last month.
   Obvious problems with a Kean candidacy are his similarities to
Bush. The two have similar patrician backgrounds.
   Bush went to Yale, while Kean attended Princeton. Bush is the
scion of a wealthy Connecticut family; Kean's family amassed a
fortune in real estate and utilities.
   Bush is the son of a U.S. senator; Kean's family tree includes
his congressman father, the late Robert Kean. A grandfather and
great-uncle served in the Senate. Further back, Kean's ancestors
include New Jersey's first constitutional governor and John Kean, a
contemporary of George Washington.
   The idea of Kean on the national ticket is unpopular with many
GOP conservatives. Kean is moderate, even liberal on some issues
held sacred by the right. He has frequently and openly broken with
President Reagan.
   Kean was first elected governor in 1981, beating Rep. James
Florio, D-N.J., by a margin of less than 1,800 votes. The contest
was so close that the winner remained uncertain for weeks.
   After a stormy first year, marked by a sagging economy and
uncertainty on the new governor's staff, Kean gradually built
support that has since earned him high approval ratings.
   The governor has an aggressive public-relations operation, topped
by his prominent presence in tourism commercials for the state of
New Jersey, which are broadcast nationally.
   Kean makes no secret about wanting to play a role at the GOP
convention, and in the fall campaign. He has already been called to
Bush's office for advice, and made it clear he would welcome an
invitation to deliver a speech at the convention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
