<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     06-06 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Differs With Administration On Offshore Drilling Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, facing a tough fight to carry
California in the fall presidential election, is bidding for support
from environmentalists by differing with the Reagan administration's
policy on offshore oil drilling.
   The vice president was in California today, on the eve of the
state's presidential primary. He already has more than enough
delegates for the Republican presidential nomination.
   A day earlier, the vice president stepped away from the
administration approach when he advocated a delay in a controversial
project off the Northern California coast.
   ``We must be assured that the national treasure of the California
coastline will not be harmed,'' he said.
   The administration is pushing to end the moratorium on drilling
off the coast, a position bitterly opposed by environmentalists.
   Opponents of ending the moratorium include many Republicans,
including Sen. Pete Wilson.
   The environment traditionally is a strong political issue in
California.
   In the past, Bush has said offshore drilling must adhere to
strict environmental standards, but he has not opposed the
administration plan to end the moratorium.
   Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff, told reporters on the flight
to California that the vice president was not advocating continuing
an absolute moratorium.
   Bush limited his difference on the question to Lease Sale 91, a
large area off the northern coast.
   ``It appears that drilling in this environmentally precious area
would not add substantially to our energy reserves,'' he said,
during remarks at the dedication of the nation's first commercial
methanol fuel pump at a gasoline station.
   Methanol is an alternative fuel derived from coal and natural
gas. Bush said methanol offers better, cleaner performance than
gasoline at no greater cost. However, cars must be adapted to use
the fuel.
   Bush said he would support legislation in Congress that would
give auto companies an incentive to produce cars that use
alternative fuels.
   The vice president spoke at an ARCO station at Wilshire and
Hobart boulevards. He pumped a couple of gallons of methanol into a
Chevrolet and then a Ford.
   Bush, who doesn't often have occasion to use self-service pumps,
then drove the Chevrolet around the back of the gas station to where
his limousine was parked.
   Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, the all-but-certain
Democratic presidential nominee, supports continuing the moratorium.
   A new California Poll, conducted by the Field Institute, said
last week that Dukakis is favored over Bush by California voters by
a margin of 53 percent to 40 percent. The survey of 926 California
voters was conducted May 16-22.
   ``George Bush recognizes the importance of environmental and
quality of life issues in California,'' said Fuller.
   He said Bush wants Lease Sale 91 ``deferred until next year,
giving his secretary of the interior an opportunity to study the
matter and determine whether or not to go further.''
   No specific request for a delay has been made of Interior
Secretary Donald P. Hodel, Fuller said.
   In his speech, Bush noted that he had been in the business of
supplying oil drilling equipment for wells in the Gulf of Mexico.
   ``I know it can be done safely,'' he said. ``But there are other
important considerations _ tourism, marine life, aesthetics _ and in
some extraordinarily sensitive areas, those considerations may
prevail until technology moves forward.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
