<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0041EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-LastPrimaryAds Bjt   06-06 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Last Primary Ads, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Underdog Jackson Is Making Biggest Ad Push In California Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 primaries began with a bang of
forceful and often negative television advertising. But they are
ending with a whimper in California, where the winners of Tuesday's
presidential contests are a foregone conclusion.
   Vice President George Bush, with a lock on the Republican
nomination, isn't running any TV commercials at all in the state
with the biggest bloc of delegates at stake.
   And Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, running far ahead on the
Democratic side, expects to spend no more than a paltry $200,000 on
advertising.
   The only candidate mounting a substantial media effort is
underdog Jesse Jackson, who is spending $700,000 on television
commercials all over the state, plus airing a half-hour show
tonight, on the eve of the primary.
   Dukakis, with a 20-point lead over Jackson in a poll last week,
is limiting his advertising to Los Angeles and San Francisco.
   ``For those Democrats who are already interested in the election
and planning to vote, we would hope that a (TV) buy even this modest
would catch their attention and provide some information,'' said
Dukakis strategist Tom Kiley. ``We don't have any illusions. We
don't pretend that advertising is playing a major role in the
campaign.''
   The Dukakis campaign is running a biography and two anti-drug ads
as well as radio spots, some in Spanish, aimed at the black and
Hispanic communities.
   One TV ad features Dukakis saying he wants to ``wage a real war,
not a phony war, against drug and alcohol dependence in this
country. ... The chief executive can make a difference in the war
against drugs. I've done it in my state and I want to do it for
every state in this country.''
   Dukakis is also using a companion ad in which an announcer
describes the Massachusetts program and quotes federal agents as
calling it ``a model for the nation. ... He did it with hard work.
Integrity. Leadership. We could use some of that in the White
House.''
   Despite the clear focus on November, both Kiley and Alixe Glen, a
spokeswoman for Bush, said the ads do not give Dukakis an early edge
over the vice president in a state that will be pivotal in the
general election.
   ``Our advertising is so modest that it would be unrealistic to
think it would have any measurable impact in terms of creating an
advantage over Bush, or even having a really significant impact on
the primary outcome,'' Kiley said.
   Glen said Bush would counter any minimal effect of the Dukakis
ads through personal appearances in the state.
   Bush has spent all but a fraction of the $27 million legally
permitted for primary contestants and cannot afford to campaign in
any substantial way until after his party's convention in August.
   But Glen said the financial crunch did not figure in Bush's
decision to forgo a television effort in California. That was ``in
large part due to the fact that we have not had an opponent for so
long in the Republican Party,'' she said.
   Jackson's initial hopes of a California upset have faded, but he
is making a major push with an eye toward holding a strong hand at
the Democratic convention next month.
   Jackson's ads are running on cable, independent and network
affiliate stations in Fresno, Los Angeles, El Centro, Sacramento,
Salinas, Redding, Santa Barbara, Bakersfield, Palm Springs, San
Jose, San Francisco, Eureka, Monterey, San Diego, and Reno, Nev.
   Campaign manager Gerald Austin said Jackson started a new TV ad
campaign Saturday to raise money to pay off bills and cover
convention expenses. The 30-second spot airing in California
features a still photo of Jackson and an 800-number that viewers can
call to pledge money or put a contribution on their credit card ``to
keep hope alive,'' Austin said.
   Other Jackson spots are familiar, including one touting Jackson's
success in winning the release of an American pilot shot down in the
Middle East. An ad called ``We Need Him'' features farmers and is
showing in rural areas. Actress Eileen Brennan praises Jackson's
stands on women's issues in another spot.
   Jackson caps his California push tonight with a half-hour show in
all 15 markets, a program variously described by Jackson aides as a
retrospective, a celebration and an update. It will feature campaign
footage and a celebrity interviewing Jackson, along with a pitch for
votes and money.
   ``It will give people an update on what the campaign has
achieved,'' said spokesman Eric Easter. ``We want people to vote for
him with knowledge beyond what the media says. It will give our
perspective on him and the campaign.''
</TEXT>
