<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SummitRevisited Bjt   06-06 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit Revisited, Bjt,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summit and Internal Politics Give Soviets a Week to Remember</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first visit to Moscow by a U.S. president in 14
years was overshadowed in the state-run media by a spirited
discussion of domestic politics, a debate that brought unprecedented
developments and raised issues not heard since the 1920s.
   The argument is over a nationwide Communist Party conference
starting June 28 that is shaping up as a battleground for supporters
of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms and the mid-level managers who
oppose them.
   Entrenched bureaucrats fear the Soviet leader's campaign to end
party oversight of the day-to-day details of governing and economic
planning and give the people a greater role, sociologist Tatyana
Zaslavskaya said in an interview printed Saturday by the newspaper
Izvestia.
   A senior Western diplomat said ``they have not debated issues as
basic as this since the 1920s,'' when the tyranny of Josef Stalin
began.
   Last week, Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,'' or greater
openness, was giving both the Soviet people and the West an
unprecedented look at the internal Soviet debate.
   In a week of firsts:
   _ On Saturday, May 28, Soviet television carried what is believed
to be the first live broadcast of the Presidium of the Supreme
Soviet, the nation's parliament, formally ratifying the treaty to
scrap intermediate-range nuclear missiles, which had been signed at
the December summit.
   _ President Reagan arrived the next day, becoming the first U.S.
president since Gerald Ford to visit the Soviet Union.
   _ Ousted Politburo member Boris N. Yeltsin, in unprecedented
interviews last Monday with U.S. and British broadcasters, attacked
Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev as the ``main person
responsible'' for slowing down the reforms.
   That was only the beginning.
   The Moscow News reported that same day that vandals had smashed a
Jewish cemetery west of the capital and Jewish residents said they
feared rising anti-Semitism, an unwelcome by-product of greater
openness.
   Throughout the week, reform advocates held news conferences for
Western journalists covering the summit, disclosing a fight over
delegate selection to the party conference.
   Reformers said they had been nominated by grass-roots party
organizations but were vetoed at next level, giving the Western
press an unprecedented look inside Soviet politics.
   On Tuesday, Reagan was asked whether he still thought the Soviet
Union was an evil empire, and responded: ``I was talking about
another time, another era.''
   Wednesday, Gorbachev became the first Soviet Communist Party
leader to give a news conference on Soviet soil. He used the
occasion to refute Yeltsin.
   Later Wednesday, several dozen members of a fledgling independent
political group, the Democratic Union, held a demonstration in
downtown Moscow to demand a multi-party system. One group member
said he thought it was ``the first time there was a political
meeting without repression ...'' since shortly after the 1917
Bolshevik Revolution.
   On Thursday, Reagan departed expressing deep personal regard and
political faith in Gorbachev.
   Friday morning, Ms. Zaslavskaya, a leading reformer, told Western
reporters ``the most pronounced advocates of perestroika were not
selected'' to the party conference. Perestroika is Gorbachev's
`restructuring' of Soviet life.
   At midday, Andrei D. Sakharov gave a news conference at the
Foreign Ministry press center, his first ever under government
auspices. Sakharov led the dissident movement in the Soviet Union
until he was banished to the closed city of Gorky in January 1980.
Gorbachev telephoned him in December 1986 to invite him back to
Moscow.
   On Friday afternoon, Gorbachev waded into the fight over
conference delegates, attending a meeting of the Moscow party
executive bureau that restored the names of some, but not all, of
the most outspoken reformers.
   On Saturday, party newspapers published a fairly detailed account
of the party meeting, along with a list of the 319 delegates chosen
from the city of Moscow. Ms. Zaslavskaya was not listed, but many of
her allies were.
   Later Saturday, Ligachev gave a speech dispelling reports of
splits in the party, proclaiming that ``all the members of the
leadership are deeply committed to the cause of perestroika.''
   ``Adversaries in the West, and some people in our country, too,
are making allegations about differences among the Soviet
leadership, in the Politburo ... Trying to drive a wedge in the
leadership is a notorious trick.''
   Also Saturday, Izvestia published a long interview with Ms.
Zaslavskaya in which she said the party conference _ the first since
1941 _ should find ways to make ``sharp cuts in the party
apparatus.''
   If the pace of change continues, the next U.S. president to visit
Moscow will find one quite different from the one Reagan left behind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
