<DOCNO> AP880606-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-JapanEconomy     06-06 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Japan Economy,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CIA Illustrates Japan's Superior Economic Performance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A set of figures compiled by the Central
Intelligence Agency illustrates how brilliantly the economy of Japan
has performed in the 1980s compared with those of the United States
and western Europe.
   In dealing with unemployment, inflation, production and foreign
trade, Japan outshines the others, even successful West Germany. The
yen's value has zoomed up at the same time that Japanese interest
rates have floated gently down.
   The CIA makes no comment on its information. Its directorate of
intelligence issues a thin pamphlet every two weeks called
``Economics and Energy Indicators.'' It contains only bland-looking
tables of figures and no analysis, but the latest issue summarizes
figures in the 1980s.
   ``Japanese success goes back to the end of World War II and it's
due to a combination of things,'' commented Jeffrey J. Schott of the
private Institute for International Economics.
   ``There's readiness to adjust to changing circumstances _ they're
shifting now from exports to production for home use. There's
cooperative labor and management practices. And there's just hard
work. They're all interrelated.''
   Japanese unemployment was a little above 2 percent at the start
of the decade. It has crept up a bit but never reached 3 percent.
   In this country unemployment was 9.6 percent in 1982, three times
Japan's. It was even higher for a while during that year's
recession, but has fallen since then.
   Still, the U.S. rate as given by the CIA _ 5.6 percent in
February _ is still more than twice as high as Japan's 2.7 percent.
   Unemployment in the four biggest countries of western Europe
varied widely, from West Germany's 7.7 percent in 1982 to Italy's
12.4 percent last year.
   CIA figures do not always agree with those issued by other U.S.
government agencies, and CIA officials say they come from several
sources. The Labor Department reported that U.S. consumer prices
rose 4.4 percent in 1987. The CIA put the number at 3.7 percent.
There are often many ways to calculate such statistics.
   On inflation, the CIA showed consumer prices in the United States
rising by 6.2 percent in 1982. Although the increase was only 3.7
percent last year, it is climbing again, according to the agency.
   Western Europe's record is similar, on average, although it
differs widely from country to country. Earlier in the decade these
rates averaged somewhat higher in Europe than in the United States.
By 1987 the average was nearly the same.
   But in Japan the inflation rate never reached 3 percent. Last
year Japanese consumers paid an average of only one-tenth of 1
percent over the level of 1986. In 1988 prices are falling fairly
sharply, with the drop in February at an annual rate of 2.4 percent.
   In 1982, the United States bought foreign goods worth $32 billion
more than what it could sell abroad. Though for a while that year
its trade was almost in balance, imports rose so fast in the rest of
the 1980s that in 1987 the U.S. international trade deficit amounted
to a record $153 billion.
   Japan started with a trade surplus of $19 billion in 1982 and
rocketed to a record of $96 billion in 1987. The level drooped a
little early last year, but rose again through February.
   ``The Japanese performance wouldn't look so brilliant if our own
had not been so un-brilliant,'' said Robert Solomon of the Brookings
Institution, a major Washington research group.
   ``Japan's big growth was based on exports. How big would it have
been except for the U.S. budget deficit?''
   Western Europe had a small but rising trade surplus since 1985
due largely to West Germany's record export sales. Britain, France
and Italy all had deficits in their world trade last year, as they
have steadily throughout the decade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MotelShootout     06-06 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Motel Shootout,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Officer, Suspect Killed In Shootout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer was slain Sunday night
during a shootout at a motel with a man who also was shot to death,
authorities said.
   Officer Brian Tunnell was pronounced dead at St. Francis Hospital
in Tulsa, with a gunshot wound to the head, police said in a
statement.
   The suspect, whose name was not released pending notification of
family, was killed when the officer with whom he was scuffling
grabbed Tunnell's gun and shot the suspect.
   Lt. Gary Anderson tried to arrest the suspect at the Elms Motel
on a felony warrant from Liberty County, Texas. The suspect struck
Anderson with an iron gate during the scuffle, police said.
   Tunnell arrived after Anderson told the motel manager to call for
help, and the suspect pulled Anderson's service revolver from him
and shot Tunnell in the head, according to the police statement.
   The motel manager then fired five shots at the suspect to
distract him, and Anderson was able to take Tunnell's gun, shooting
the suspect once, police said.
   ``It's been a real long night,'' said the wife of the motel
manager who spoke on condition of that her name not be used. ``We're
going to be so notorious. We're just a little motel in Miami,
Oklahoma.''
   The woman, who owns the 14-unit motel with her husband, said
Miami police told her not to release any information on the
shootings.
   Police Chief Bill Melton was unavailable for comment.
</TEXT>
