<HEAD>Man With Knife Arrested Before Jackson Appearance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Secret Service was trying to determine
whether a man who tried to carry a knife into a mosque knew Jesse
Jackson was due to appear at the site a short time later.
   The man, whose name has not been released, was arrested Saturday
evening when he refused to leave the weapon at the door of the
Islamic Center of Southern California. He was held on outstanding
traffic warrants, said Secret Service spokesman Richard Adams.
   ``He was advised not to enter with a knife. He said that he was
going to go in with the knife'' and then was detained by center
security guards, Adams said Sunday.
   A spokesman for the center, Dr. Maher Hathout, said the man
appeared at the center wearing a dagger in a sheath around his waist
and was refused entry. He said he did not know if any threat was
made against Jackson, who was not present at the time.
   Jackson spoke about an hour after the arrest, without incident.
   ``Right now, there's a question of whether he (the detained man)
even knew Jackson was going to be there,'' said Jane Vezeris, a
Secret Service spokeswoman in Washington.
   The Secret Service planned to discuss any possible charges
against the man Monday with the U.S. Attorney's office, Adams said.
</TEXT>
