<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Ortega     06-06 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Ortega,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Says U.S. To Blame If Peace Talks Fail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega says the key to
success of this week's peace talks with Nicaraguan rebels lies with
the Reagan administration.
   ``We hold the United States government responsible for what
happens in these meetings'' with the Contras, the president said
Sunday after meeting with labor leaders who support his leftist
Sandinista government.
   Government officials and leaders of the U.S.-supported Nicaraguan
Resistance, the Contra umbrella organization, are scheduled to meet
Tuesday through Thursday in Managua to attempt to forge a lasting
peace.
   It would mark the fourth occasion the combatants in the
7-year-old civil war have met in the Nicaraguan capital to discuss a
definitive truce.
   The Contra delegation planned to travel today to San Jose, Costa
Rica, to prepare for the talks, said a rebel spokesman in a
telephone interview from Miami on Sunday. He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Ortega said the Reagan administration would be to blame if the
Contras did not agree to end the war and ``lay down their arms.''
   In the event the talks fell through, he added, ``we will be
obliged to confront this terrorist policy with all the firmness and
force with which we have confronted it for all of these years.''
   The rebels, trained, funded and supplied by the United States,
began their war to overthrow the Sandinistas in 1981.
   Ortega said his government would offer ``no variations'' to its
peace proposal submitted during the last round of negotiations held
May 26-28.
   During that session, the government agreed to discuss Contra
demands for political changes they say would bring about
``democratization'' in Nicaragua. Those include freedom of the
press, an end to the ruling Sandinista National Liberation Front's
control over the armed forces and the government and electoral and
judicial reforms.
   The Contras rejected a government proposal for a 30-day extension
of the two-month truce that began April 1 and a plan for delivering
humanitarian aid to rebel units gathered inside truce zones.
   The cease-fire was set to lapse on May 31, but both sides agreed
to extend it at least until the end of this week's talks. Ortega has
already announced a unilateral 30-day truce extension.
   The rebel delegation was permitted to visit leaders of the
domestic opposition and Roman Catholic Church officials during the
last round of talks. Ortega said Sunday that they would be allowed
to do so again this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0040 </DOCNO>
