<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0860,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Reach Record High, Dollar Dips In Active Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs tp UPDATE with closing market figures.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, `An exchange ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices climbed across the board, driving the
Tokyo Stock Exchange's main barometer to a record closing high
Monday, while the dollar declined slightly against the Japanese yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues rose by 89.76 points, or 0.32 percent, from its
previous high of 27,906.48 points last Saturday to reach a record
27,996.24 points.
   In foreign exchange dealings, the dollar closed at 126.07 yen,
down 0.04 yen from last Friday's close. It opened at 126.32 yen and
was traded in range between 126.00 yen and 126.38 yen.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo said
trading was active. He said the dollar's strength against the yen
followed its recent rallies against the West German mark, Swiss
franc and British pound.
   ``Investor confidence in higher (stock) prices was further
boosted following last Friday's report on the U.S. monthly
unemployment rate,'' which helped ease concern over inflation in the
United States, said Katsuhiro Yagawara of Daiwa Securities.
   The U.S. government reported the nation's unemployment rate in
May rose to 5.6 percent of the labor force from 5.4 percent the
previous month, helping the U.S. bond market to rally last Friday.
</TEXT>
