<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     06-06 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to correct category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Asks Tuesday's Voters to Put Him Over the Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis made final appeals to California voters today, saying ``We
may be able to lock up this nomination early and go to Atlanta
united.''
   Dukakis was flying around the state today with stops in San
Diego, San Jose and Los Angeles, a trip aimed at gaining exposure in
each of the state's major television markets on the eve of Tuesday's
primary season finale.
   The Massachusetts governor returned to the state Sunday evening,
where he had a rally at a Greek Orthodox church, after completing
two days of campaigning in New Jersey, another of the four states
holding primaries on the final day of delegate-selection contests.
   Greeted warmly at the church, Dukakis danced a traditional Greek
dance and told supporters, ``With your help and the help of people
all across the country we're going to win a decisive victory here in
California, in New Jersey and Montana and New Mexico.''
   With a seemingly insurmountable lead over Jesse Jackson in the
delegate count, Dukakis aides were confident he will gain the
remaining delegates to assure his nomination by Tuesday's primaries
and the campaign can turn its attention to the important selection
of a running mate.
   Aboard his campaign plane on the flight west, Dukakis said he
would turn his focus to choosing a vice presidential candidate after
Tuesday. He said the search would be led by the top officials of his
campaign.
   Dukakis said his priority will be choosing someone who would be
qualified to be president if needed, and that only after that
qualification is met would he look at political considerations such
as the person's geographic region, expertise and other
considerations.
   Dukakis has more than 1,800 delegates toward the 2,081 needed for
a delegate majority at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
   With Jackson his only remaining rival and a Dukakis nomination
assumed, voter turnout remains his big concern, and Dukakis urged
voters at a series of stops in New Jersey not to forget to vote.
   ``Tuesday is very important, and please don't let anybody think
this is over,'' Dukakis said.
   He added that with wins in the two big states voting Tuesday, and
the smaller states of Montana and New Mexico, ``We may be able to
lock up this nomination early and go to Atlanta united.''
   Confident, the Dukakis campaign has aired no television ads in
New Jersey, and few in California.
   Already the Dukakis campaign is working on its fall campaign
against Republican George Bush, and Dukakis touched on themes aimed
at suburban swing voters, many of whom have gone with President
Reagan and the Republicans in the last two elections. In New Jersey,
he emphasized family values and economic policies that recognize the
changing needs of families with two working spouses and children who
need day care.
   In Paterson, an older industrial city, Dukakis called for federal
and state investment in urban revitalization, citing the example of
the economic rebirth of Lowell, Mass., in his state. Dukakis did
not, however, shed further light on how this investment would be
paid for, beyond his previous calls for providing modest sums of
money to encourage private development projects.
   In Jersey City, across the river from New York City, Dukakis
stressed the themes of affordable housing and blasted the Reagan
administration for what he said was a 90 percent cutback in federal
support for public housing assistance to low- and moderate-income
families. He said it's ``no wonder'' the nation faces a problem of
homelessness.
   Dukakis responded to indications from Jackson that he intends to
continue campaigning up to the convention, pressing his issues.
Dukakis said he saw no harm _ but added that he expects Jackson to
work for the ticket in the fall.
   ``It's not harmful at all,'' the Massachusetts governor said.
``He's a very strong person who's done an extraordinary job of
winning votes and winning support.
   ``I hope and believe we're going to have a good relationship. We
have in the past,'' he said. ``I suspect he's going to be out there
campaigning hard for the Democratic ticket this fall.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
