<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthKorea     06-06 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Korea,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Who Set Himself Ablaze In Protest Dies, More Street
Demontrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radical student leader who set
himself on fire to protest South Korea's relations with the United
States died today of injuries, prompting hundreds of his classmates
to stage another march.
   On Saturday, Park Rae-chun, a 24-year-old junior majoring in
Korean literature, shouted ``Overthrow military fascists,'' doused
his body with flammable liquid and set himself on fire on the roof
of Soongshil University's student center building.
   University officials reported his death today.
   Upon hearing of Park's death, about 1,000 students gathered in
the compound of the Hangang Sacred Heart Hospital and 500 of them
staged a street demonstration shouting ``Yankee go home,'' and
``Punish culprits in the Kwangju Massacre.''
   The alleged massacre refers to the bloody suprresion by
government troops of a 1980 civil uprising in the provincial
capital. At least 191 people were killed by official count.
   Some dissidents accuse President Roh Tae-woo and former President
Chun Doo-hwan, both generals at the time of the incident, of
masterminding the crackdown on the uprising.
   Today, police stood by without interfering as the protesters
marched about a mile to a busy intersection in the southern district
of Yongdungpo and then back to the hospital.
   The students from Soongshil and some other schools surrounded the
hospital and continued to shout anti-American and anti-government
slogans. No violence was immediately reported.
   Officials at Soongshil said funeral arrangements would be made
after consulting with Park's family. They said the school hoped to
bury him in a campus funeral, but that some of his classmates were
planning a ``democratic people's funeral.''
   Park left behind a suicide note that criticized the South Korean
government and the United States, which he blamed for the
partitition of the Korean peninsula.
   He said in the note that he was offering his body to ``the sacred
altar of democracy'' to advance national reunification.
   Ritual suicide is a traditional form of protest used by radical
students to dramatize their cause while trying to shame the
government. Two students killed themselves as part of
anti-government protests last month.
</TEXT>
