<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Fiji     06-06 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiji,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seize Huge Arms Cache, Round Up Indians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops today raided Indian businesses and
rounded up 40 people, including a former foreign minister, after
police seized a huge shipment of Soviet-made weapons apparently
smuggled from the Middle East.
   Krishna Datt, a Fijian of Indian descent in the ousted government
of Timoci Bavadra, was among those detained because he visited the
Soviet Union in 1985, the Ministry of Information said. It did not
elaborate.
   Government-controlled Radio Fiji said the arms haul included 93
automatic rifles, 10 light machine guns, 300 hand grenades, five
rocket-launchers, 72 bayonets, two large drums of live ammunition
and two pistols.
   It said the weapons were found at several locations near the city
of Nadi, on the western side of the main island of Viti Levu, a
stronghold for the coalition government that was overthrown in a
coup 13 months ago.
   In Suva, soldiers raided at least six buildings housing Indian
businesses, residents said.
   Police spokesman Senior Inspector Romanu Tikotikoca said
authorities had seized a ``substantial portion'' of a shipment of
weapons believed smuggled into the country in April. He gave no
further details.
   The weapons were similar to a shipment seized in Australia a week
ago that arrived from North Yemen and was destined for Fiji.
   Australian customs officers in Sydney, which is 2,000 miles to
the southwest, said the 16-ton shipment could have been used to
start a small war.
   Bavadra has denied any involvement in the gunrunning and his
wife, Kuini, said last week that the incident was part of a
deliberate campaign to discredit her husband, whom she said believes
in non-violence.
   Coup leader Sitiveni Rabuka has said the shipments were part of a
foreign plot to destablize the nation, but stopped short of accusing
a particular country or organization.
   Rabuka said he staged the two coups last year to protect the
political rights of ethnic Fijians, who are slightly outnumbered by
the Indian community among the 715,000 residents of this former
British colony.
   Radio Fiji also reported today that the arms and ammunition were
seized in raids on homes and warehouses owned by Indian businessmen.
   Meanwhile, residents said the army had increased its armed
patrols in the capital, with soldiers standing guard at all the
premises raided.
   Earlier, a 47-year-old truck driver of Indian descent was to have
appeared in court charged with conspiring to illegally import the
weapons shipment seized in Australia last week. But police postponed
the court appearance until Tuesday, saying they could not guarantee
the man's safety.
   The suspect was not identified.
</TEXT>
