<DOCNO> AP880606-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0536EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DissentingNuns     06-06 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dissenting Nuns,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Catholic Group Claims Victory In Decision Not To Expel
Nuns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By T.J. SIMONEAUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two nuns claimed ``a victory for all
women'' after Roman Catholic church officials backed down from their
threat to expel the nuns for publicly supporting the right to
abortions.
   However, the Vatican still could take action against Sisters
Barbara Ferraro and Patricia Hussey, who run a shelter for the
homeless in Charleston, according to Catholics For a Free Choice, a
dissident Catholic group.
   The nuns' order, the General Government Group of the Sisters of
Notre Dame deNamur, said Saturday in a statement from Rome that it
``will not proceed with the process to dismiss'' Ferraro and Hussey.
   ``Dismissal would not be in the best interest of the church or
the religious congregation at this time,'' the order said.
   ``This decision to halt the process of dismissal is not to be
interpreted as support for or agreement with the public statements
which have been made by Sisters Barbara and Patricia,'' according to
the statement read over the telephone to the nuns by officials of
the order in Rome.
   ``The Sisters of Notre Dame disclaim any public statetment on
abortion made by these two sisters.''
   The nuns have been under threat of dismissal since signing an
Oct. 7, 1984, advertisement in The New York Times that said ``a
diversity of opinion exists among committed Catholics'' on the issue
of abortion.
   The advertisement noted the church's view that abortion is always
wrong and added, ``there is a mistaken belief in American society
that this is the only legitimate Catholic position.''
   ``We are elated. This is an enormous victory for all women,'' the
two nuns said in a statement released through the Washington-based
dissent group.
   The nuns, who had said they expected to be expelled after being
given two warnings to disavow their support for abortion, could not
be reached for comment Sunday. They scheduled a news conference for
Thursday in Washington.
   Hussey has been a member of the order for 20 years, Ferraro for
25 years.
   Ferraro has claimed that ``the aim of the Vatican for years has
been to silence strong, independent women's communities and strong,
independent women.''
   ``There's no question. It's a very important victory for all
women,'' Frances Kissling, head of the dissident group, said Sunday.
   ``We felt it was very important that if anyone was going to act
against Barbara and Pat, it should be the Vatican, not the order. ...
   ``It should not be women expelling women.''
   Kissling said the Sisters of Notre Dame gave no other indication
why they decided not to expel the nuns.
   ``That is essentially what they have had to say,'' she said of
the statement released by the Vatican.
   Ferraro and Hussey were among 97 Catholics, including 22 other
nuns and four priests, who signed the advertisement, which was
written by Kissling's group.
   The other nuns and priests who signed it retracted their
statement and have had their cases closed by Rome ``without punitive
action against anyone,'' Kissling said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0546EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OldestPriest     06-06 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oldest Priest,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Great-Granddad Becomes Father Of Much Larger Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Reeda Schumacher's childhood dream was
delayed until his own children were grown, but now the oldest man to
become a Roman Catholic priest in America is ready to minister to a
much larger family.
   Schumacher, who has six children, 13 grandchildren and one
great-grandchild, was ordained Saturday, just 24 days short of his
80th birthday. He celebrated his first mass Sunday.
   ``What he's taught all of us is, there's nothing you can't do if
you really want to do it _ he believes that,'' said Fran Lipton,
Schumacher's 48-year-old daughter, who was among 300 people
attending the service with her five brothers and several of the new
priest's grandchildren.
   Wearing a simple white robe, the bespectacled white-haired
Schumacher was ordained into the priesthood by Bishop Thomas
Tschoepe of Dallas, who gave Schumacher a chance after he was
rejected by scores of other church leaders because of his age.
   Schumacher said he felt nothing special about making church
history.
   ``Being a priest is all that concerned me,'' he said after the
ceremony at his home parish, St. Tarcissus Roman Catholic Church on
the city's Northwest Side.
   Schumacher took steps to attend a seminary when he was 17, but
deferred his plans to care for his widowed mother. He later got
married and had a family of his own.
   A few weeks after his wife, Genevieve, died in 1984 after 52
years of marriage, Schumacher telephoned the Chicago archdiocese and
said he wanted to be a priest.
   ``The kids were all taking care of themselves,'' he explained.
``I was then free to do what I originally wanted to do.''
   But officials in Chicago turned him down, saying he was 35 years
beyond the cutoff age of 40 for archdiocesan sponsorship of a priest.
   After 49 dioceses either rejected or ignored his letters,
Tschoepe promised to give him an assignment.
   Tschoepe's backing allowed Schumacher to enter the seminary, and
in May, he graduated from Holy Apostles Seminary in Cromwell, Conn.
   ``Bill impresses me as a vigorous man of about 60 or so,'' said
the 72-year-old Tschoepe.
   A man almost 80 years old ``can be a good priest,'' the bishop
said. ``With the experience they have they can be very, very
effective, especially in counseling, and their understanding of what
other people are going through is one of `I've been there.'''
   Schumacher will begin his service in Dallas, but requested to be
ordained in his neighborhood church, where he had been a lay leader
for 31 years.
   As a priest, Schumacher's main responsibilities will be working
with the elderly and sick people.
   ``I think I have a rapport with people older like myself, and I
know I have a rapport with people who are ill,'' Schumacher said.
   Schumacher pursued various careers, including insurance broker,
politician, credit manager, and job counselor for the state of
Illinois.
   After retiring from his government job at age 68, Schumacher
became a travel agent, a career he continued until he applied for
seminary, Mrs. Lipton said.
   ``As I was watching the service I thought, my mother would have
been proud to be there; but of course if she was there he wouldn't
have been,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
