<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Politics     06-06 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Politics,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Socialists Defend Decision to Back Dissident Ruling Party Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The candidate representing Mexico's Socialist
Party has withdrawn from the presidential race and thrown his
support to a politician who heads a breakaway faction of the
governing party.
   Heberto Castillo stepped down as the Socialist candidate and
publicly endorsed Cuauhtemoc Cardenas in the July 6 presidential
elections.
   On Sunday, Gilberto Rincon Gallardo, secretary general of the
Socialist Party, said the government party reacted to the decision
with ``enormous disgust'' and was preparing ``to strike'' at the
leftist coalition now unified behind Cardenas.
   The Socialist party is Mexico's second largest opposition group.
   Cardenas, whose popularity has risen sharply among the left,
accepted Castillo's endorsement while campaigning in the gulf coast
state of Veracruz.
   ``It is a great honor and a high responsibility for me to be the
Mexican Socialist Party candidate,'' he told reporters Friday night.
He said he had accepted the Socialists' 12-plank platform.
   Rincon Gallardo denied on Sunday that the Socialists' decision
was opportunistic. ``If we were in circumstances of weakness, unity
would not be worth it,'' he told reporters in remarks carried by the
Excelsior news agency.
   The Socialists generally finish in third place in elections,
behind the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, and
the conservative National Action Party.
   But in this year's campaign, some polls indicate Cardenas is
trailing only Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the PRI candidate. The PRI
has not lost a presidential or gubernatorial election since it was
founded in 1929.
   Cardenas heads the National Democratic Front coalition, which
includes the Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution, originally a
PRI spinoff, two smaller leftist parties, and followers of the
Democratic Current reform movement he led within the PRI last year.
   He broke away from the PRI when the party refused to accept a
platform that called for open primaries to choose candidates for
elections. The PRI traditionally selects its candidates in closed
session.
   The son of the late President Lazaro Cardenas, one of Mexico's
most revered politicians, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas served as governor of
the west coast state of Michoacan.
</TEXT>
