<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Searing Temperatures, Summer Storms Sweep Nation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: The selected city temperatures have been delayed by the
source.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sweltering, triple-digit temperatures combined with summer
thunderstorms and showers today after breaking temperature records
in 15 states and unleashing tornadoes that skipped over eastern
Colorado.
   Temperatures were still in the 80s in the northern High Plains
early this morning following Sunday afternoon highs that ranged up
to 109 degrees at Glendive, Mont.
   The high of 94 degrees at International Falls, Minn., Sunday was
a record for the date, with the old record of 87 degrees set in
1976. Fifteen cities in the north-central United States reported
record highs Sunday. The mercury pushed to 108 degrees at Glasgow,
Mont., a record for the month of June.
   Tornadoes ripped through an area north of Denver Sunday
afternoon, tearing off part of the roof of one home, damaging others
and demolishing a trailer at a campground. There were no injuries
reported.
   The tornadoes were part of a wild afternoon of weather in the
Denver area that included heavy rain, hail and intense lightning.
   Meanwhile, thunderstorms whipped up severe weather in Florida and
Maine on Sunday afternoon but weakened during the evening.
   The Northeast had cloudy skies and scattered showers, along with
the northern and central Pacific coast to the northern Rockies.
   Clear skies prevailed across Nevada, the Mississippi Valley and
the Ohio Valley and the upper Great Lakes region.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms across the
eastern Gulf Coast and Florida; scattered showers and thundertorms
across the northern Rockies and northern Plateau region with
widespsread showers across the Pacific Northwest into northern
California; mostly sunny skies over the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 80s or 90s across much of
the nation; in the 50s across northern Washington, in the 60s and
70s from the Central Pacific coast region through much of Nevada;
also in the 60s and 70s from New England into the upper Ohio Valley
and eastern parts of the Great Lakes; from the mid 90s to near 100
degrees across the Arizona deserts through southern New Mexico into
the Rio Grande Valley and across the Northern Plains.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 37
degrees at Sexton Summit, Ore., to 85 degrees at Billings, Mont.
</TEXT>
