<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoCalWildfires     06-06 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SoCal Wildfires,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires Destroy Homes And Trigger Evacuations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A wildfire fanned by gusty winds burned out of control today in
Southern California, while firefighters mopped up two others that
destroyed six homes, triggered evacuations and charred more than
2,000 acres.
   The fire in the Coxey Meadow area of the San Bernardino National
Forest near Hesperia in San Bernardino County was 60 percent
contained at 2:30 a.m., but control was at the mercy of the weather,
said Gail Nerseth, an interagency dispatcher with the U.S. Forest
Service.
   The fire, 90 miles northeast of Los Angeles, had burned 220
acres, but destroyed only one small mining shack, she said. Several
mining cabins and some electronic sites were threatened, however,
she said.
   ``We've got hot and flashy fuels and gusty, erratic winds.
Control time is still a question depending on the weather,'' she
said.
   Six homes were destroyed, another was damaged and some
residential evacuations were ordered near the Riverside County
community of Desert Hot Springs when fire scorched 1,800 acres there
Sunday, said county Fire Department spokeswoman Joanne Evans.
   Erratic winds fanned the flank of the fire toward Desert Hot
Springs, which has a population of 6,000 in the desert 110 miles
east of Los Angeles, but by early this morning, firefighters
reported 95 percent containment, meaning the blaze wasn't expanding
beyond the fire perimeter, she said.
   More than 200 firefighters manned fire lines. California Highway
62 and several other roads in the area were closed.
   Authorities were unsure what caused the fires.
   In Orange County, firefighters contained a 170-acre blaze near
the El Toro Marine Corps Air Station, 45 miles southeast of Los
Angeles.
   Three boys were questioned about the fire, which witnesses said
started Sunday as the trio played with a toy hobby rocket, said
Patti Range, a spokeswoman for the Orange County Fire Department.
   No one was injured and no structures were damaged, Ms. Range said.
</TEXT>
