<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0465 06-06 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0465,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Go Back To School; Arabs Suspected of Arson Detained</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with Palestinians going back to school, Arabs
accused of setting fire to lands in northern Israel.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 36,000 Palestinian high school students
today returned to classes for the first time in four months and
police accused five Arabs of starting a fire that destroyed hundreds
of acres in northern Israel.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir left today for the United States to
meet Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze in a bid to further
improve relations between Israel and the Soviet Union.
   On Sunday, Israel's highest court upheld a deportation order
against Mubarak Awad, an Arab-American who advocates civil
disobedience against Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   He was given a week to leave.
   The army has been opening grade schools and junior high schools
in the occupied lands over the past two weeks, citing a recent
reduction in violence.
   In the West Bank city of Hebron, students burned tires and threw
stones at soldiers outside the Hussein School, an Arab reporter
said. He said the soldiers opened fire and one student was grazed by
a bullet.
   Several students and teachers in Ramallah, also in the West Bank,
said their return to school will not end demonstrations against
Israeli rule that have persisted for six months.
   ``It's good to be back in school because without being educated
we can't be liberated,'' said Ranna Bahu, a 17-year-old senior at
Friends Girls School. ``We can continue demonstrating after we take
our classes.''
   Police spokeswoman Edna Zigelshifer would not identify the five
Arabs arrested for setting a fire on Sunday that destroyed several
hundred acres of trees in northern Israel. She said only that they
were young men from villages about 80 miles north of Jerusalem.
   David Angel, a spokesman for an agency that manages most of
Israel's forest land, said Arabs were suspected of starting a series
of brush and forest fires that have destroyed 17,500 acres of woods
and pastures in the last five weeks.
   He said most of the fires appeared to be the work of Palestinians
acting in connection with the Arab uprising.
   Angel said he based his claim on the location of most of the
fires, many of which had been in fields bordering the West Bank.
   Last year, only 8,750 acres burned in Israel between May and
October, while this year's figure is already double, he said.
   In Jerusalem, the Supreme Court ruled that Awad ``harms the
security and public order'' and was illegally in Israel because he
did not have a valid residence permit. His lawyers argued that he
should be granted legal residence because he was born in Jerusalem.
   Awad's American-born wife, Nancy Nye, has denied government
charges her husband wrote leaflets encouraging the Arab uprising.
His ideas for civil disobedience have been adopted by underground
leaders of the uprising.
   Awad maintains a home in Wapakoneta, Ohio.
   Shamir announced his scheduled meeting with Shevardnadze at an
airport news conference before flying to a special U.N. session on
disarmament in New York.
   ``We have a lot to say to each other,'' he said. ``Our
discussions will focus on the attitude of the Soviet Union toward
regional issues, including Israel and the Middle East, the lack of
normal relations between us and the Soviet Union, and the problem of
Soviet Jews.''
   The scheduled meeting would be the latest in a series of talks
between Israeli and Soviet officials since Kremlin leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev came to power three years ago.
   The Soviet Union severed diplomatic relations with the Jewish
state after the 1967 Middle East war and has been a staunch
supporter of Syria, Israel's most implacable foe.
   A military spokesman said, meanwhile, that the army was
experimenting with a new aluminum bullet to replace regular
ammunition used to quell violent demonstrations.
   The Israeli newspaper Haaretz said the new bullet is lighter than
the steel bullet and is designed to travel slower and be less apt to
penetrate skin when fired from a distance.
   Two Israelis and 201 Palestinians have died since Dec. 8 as a
result of the uprisings in the lands Israel seized in the 1967
Middle East war.
   An Israeli soldier was sentenced Sunday to a year in prison for
the fatal shooting of a Palestinian in the Gaza Strip last October.
The soldier was identified as Yaacov Tamir, an Ethiopian immigrant.
</TEXT>
