<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Nuclear     06-06 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Nuclear,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Gives Final Approval To Anti-Nuclear Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The senate gave final approval today
to a bill banning nuclear weapons and nuclear-equipped warships from
the country in a move aimed at U.S. military bases in the
Philippines.
   Similar legislation is pending in the House of Representatives.
   Nineteen senators gave their approval to the bill on the third
and final reading. Three voted against the measure and one abstained.
   The bill, which received preliminary approval last month, sets
prison terms of up to 30 years for bringing nuclear weapons into the
country and up to 12 years imprisonment for importing nuclear
components.
   Supporters said the measure was aimed at the six American
military installations in the Philippines. As part of its defense
policy, the United States refuses to confirm or deny whether it has
deployed nuclear weapons in the Philippines.
   Senate President Jovito Salonga, a co-sponsor, hailed the measure
as a contribution to world disarmament.
   ``The Philippines should not be a promoter of the deadly arms
race,'' Salonga said. ``We should never be part of the problem. We
should be part of the solution.''
   Opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, a former defense minister,
said he supported the bill because ``the presence of nuclear weapons
in our territory is inconsistent with the national interest.''
   Enrile criticized President Corazon Aquino for allegedly failing
to enforce a provision in the new constitution which states that the
country opposes nuclear weapons ``consistent with the national
interest.''
   Legal experts are divided over whether the phrase ``consistent
with the national interest'' makes the provision less than an
unequivocal nuclear weapons ban.
   The three senators who opposed the bill _ John Osmena, Neptali
Gonzalez and Mamintal Tamano _ said the measure would raise problems
with the United States over the future of the bases.
   The current bases agreement expires in 1991, and the constitution
requires that any extension be provided for by a bilateral treaty
subject to approval by two-thirds of the senate.
   Last April, the U.S. and Philippine governments began a review of
the current agreement. A successful outcome is expected to influence
Manila's decision on whether to allow the bases to remain after 1991.
   Mrs. Aquino says she will honor the agreement but refuses to say
whether she will support an extension.
   Meanwhile, Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos told a House committee
today that the anti-nuclear bill was ``not completely satisfactory
to me.''
   Ramos called for unspecified amendments to give Mrs. Aquino
greater flexibility on the issue and in her dealings with the United
States.
   U.S. officials have said the measure would severely limit
American military operations, particularly those of the Navy at its
base at Subic Bay.
   Warships which are believed armed with nuclear weapons routinely
call at Subic Bay. Many are en route to the Persian Gulf to protect
commercial shipping from attacks related to the Iran-Iraq war.
   The senate bill bans the storage or transit of all nuclear
weapons as well as nuclear-equipped ships and aircraft. The original
measure also banned port calls by nuclear-powered ships.
   However, the bill was amended to allow nuclear-powered commercial
and research vessels to call at Philippine ports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
