<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Religion     06-06 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Religion,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Guests Help Start Orthodox Church Council</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZAGORSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church leaders from around the world
marched to the pealing of bells today into this 14th century Russian
Orthodox monastery for the opening session of a three-day conference
marking the church's 1,000 anniversary.
   Hundreds of Soviets watched the 45-minute procession of church
officials from under the shade of maple trees and ancient churches
on the grounds of the Trinity-St. Sergius Monastery.
   Guests included Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie;
representatives of Pope John Paul II; and officials of dozens of
other Eastern and Western faiths.
   ``We have a long-standing relationship,'' Runcie told reporters
before entering the conference hall. ``We have not lost contact
through the centuries. On the 900th anniversary, we were the only
Western church to send a message.''
   The celebration of the Russian Orthodox Church's 1,000
anniversary, being commemorated in Moscow before moving to Kiev,
Leningrad and Vladimir, east of Moscow, drew about 500
representatives from more than 100 countries.
   The conference of church leaders will canonize nine new saints,
including Russia's most famous icon painter, Andrei Rublev, and 14th
century nobleman Dmitri Donskoy, who helped defeat the Tatars
dominating Russia.
   According to church documents, the conference also was to
consider an administrative charter for the church and discuss its
activities on behalf of world peace.
   The Zagorsk monastery was founded in 1345 by Holy Sergei of
Radonezh, and still contains a monastery as well as one of the
country's main seminaries.
   Christianity was introduced to Russia by Prince Vladimir in
Kievan Rus _ the ancient name of what is now the northern Soviet
republic of the Ukraine _ with a baptism ceremony on the banks of
the Dnieper River in 988.
   Church officials began the celebration Sunday in Moscow with a
service in Epiphany Cathedral led by 77-year-old Russian Orthodox
Patriarch Pimen, and a wreath-laying ceremony at the Tomb of the
Unknown Soldier next to the Kremlin.
   Soviet television showed Pimen and other Orthodox clergymen
officiating at the ceremony as the strains of a male choir filled
the opulently furbished church, which has five domes and three
altars and dates from 1731.
   Pope John Paul II did not attend the ceremonies, although he has
often expressed the desire to visit the Soviet Union. But the
Vatican said earlier that the Russian Orthodox Church did not extend
an invitation to the pope. Russian Orthodox churchmen have said John
Paul was invited.
   The pontiff has said he would go to the Soviet Union only on
condition that he be allowed to visit the heavily-Catholic Soviet
republics. But John Paul has said he has been twice denied
permission to visit Lithuania, one of the country's Catholic
heartlands.
   In a rare show of cooperation between church and state, the state
Ministry of Religion participated in organizing events linked to the
millennium.
   The government gave Pimen and 14 other church officials awards
Friday in honor of the millennium, and on Saturday state and church
officials announced jointly that cathedrals in the oldest monastery
_ the Pechersky Monastery in Kiev _ would be returned to the church.
   Pimen met this spring with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in
the first such meeting since 1943 and pledged his support for the
Soviet leader's reform policies. Religious dissidents say such
cooperation is a sign of the church's subservience to the state,
which officially is athesitic.
   Dissidents planned their own services and seminars to give what
they said is a true picture of the situation of religious believers.
   A law that went into effect in 1929, the height of the Stalin-era
repression against the church, prohibits believers from organizing
charitable work, restricts religious education and requires
government registration of worshipers.
   Government officials now say that law is outdated, and will be
replaced by a new statute guaranteeing freedom of conscience. But
the law has not been published and neither church nor government
officials have revealed its contents.
</TEXT>
