<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     06-06 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Reportedly Under Way To Free German Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beirut newspapers said today ``energetic
negotiations'' were under way to release West German hostage Rudolf
Cordes.
   Several dailies quoted a Shiite Moslem news agency, the Daily
News, as saying the Bonn government was engaged in direct contacts
with the kidnappers holding Cordes in Beirut.
   ``These energetic negotiations might culminate in Cordes' release
within a few days in exchange for releasing Mohammed Ali and Abbas
Hamadi,'' the agency was quoted as saying. The Hamadis are Lebanese
brothers held in West Germany.
   Newspapers said the agency cited ``sources concerned with the
hostages' affair in Lebanon'' for its report.
   The agency is known to have close links with moderate Shiite
Moslem clerics in Lebanon, including Sheik Mohammed Mehdi
Shamsheddin, head of Lebanon's Supreme Shiite Council, and Sheik
Abdul-Amir Kabalan, the sect's senior religious judge.
   Cordes, a 53-year-old businessman, was kidnapped Jan. 17, 1987,
shortly after Mohammed Ali Hamadi was arrested in West Germany. A
group calling itself Holy Warriors for Freedom claimed June 8 it
abducted Cordes and said it would release him if the Hamadi brothers
were freed.
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi is to go on trial in July in Frankfurt on
charges of air piracy and murder in the June 1985 hijacking of a TWA
jetliner. In the hijacking, Shiite sky pirates held 39 Americans
captive for 17 days and killed a U.S. Navy diver.
   Abbas Hamadi, 29, is serving a 13-year prison term for
involvement in kidnapping Cordes and another West German, Alfred
Schmidt.
   Schmidt, 48, was abducted in west Beirut Jan. 20, 1987 and freed
Sept. 7.
   The group holding Cordes is believed to be headed by the Hamadis'
older brother, Abdul-Hadi Hamadi, chief of security for the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah.
   Hezbollah also is believed to be an umbrella for extremist
factions holding most of the 18 foreign hostages missing in Lebanon.
They include nine Americans.
</TEXT>
