<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PhonesAtLast     06-06 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phones At Last,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phones Up to Full Service in Chicago Suburb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HINSDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The phones finally are ringing again for
thousands of suburban residents cut off by a fire at a switching
station nearly a month ago.
   ``I see a lot of very tired people out there,'' Bell spokeswoman
Hilary Anderson said Sunday, after technicians from five states
completed restoring service to all 35,000 customers affected by the
May 8 fire at the Illinois Bell switching station here.
   The Great Phone Outage ended at 12:01 a.m. Sunday, when Bell
officials transferred the final 18,000 customers from a damaged,
jury-rigged switch to a new, state-of-the-art digital unit for
connecting local and long-distance calls.
   ``More than 250 people worked around the clock to meet the
deadline,'' Ms. Anderson said.
   ``Everyone was on at least 12-hour shifts, and some people were
working double shifts,'' Ms. Anderson said. ``We brought in
technicians from all the other Ameritech companies _ in Indiana,
Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin.''
   Company officials said the workers accomplished what normally
would have been a 50-week job in four weeks.
   ``It was a very good cutover, very uneventful,'' said Bell
spokesman Dick Hill.
   But, she added, ``I think I'm going to miss some of those times
when the phones weren't ringing off the hook.''
   About half of the phoneless customers were hooked up to the new
system on May 26, and the remainder were hooked up by Sunday.
   Although Illinois Bell has promised rebates, several businesses
have filed lawsuits accusing the utility of negligence. Illinois
Attorney General Neil Hartigan has filed a complaint with the
Illinois Commerce Commission seeking to have Bell pay for financial
losses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
