<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Jail 2ndLd-Writethru a0507 06-06 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Jail, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0507,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoners Riot After Ordered To Take Down Pin-Ups</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to update number of men captured. Picks up
3rd graf pvs ``No guards....''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 prisoners who were told to remove pin-ups
from newly painted walls rioted and burned down much of a
minimum-security prison on the northwest England coast, officials
said today.
   The Home Office, which runs the police and prisons, said 11
prisoners who escaped during Sunday night's rioting at Haverigg
Prison near Millon, 281 miles from London, were still on the run.
Five others were captured.
   No guards were injured but one prisoner was hospitalized with a
suspected broken jaw and 10 were given first aid for minor injuries,
the Home Office said.
   The search for the escaped prisoners, involving about 100 police
officers, was being hampered because prison records were destroyed
in the rioting, Cumbria police said.
   The Home Office said no demands were issued by the prisoners.
   Scores of police with dogs joined prison guards to encircle the
facility. Firefighters waited for several hours before going in
because of the possibility of attack. At about 9 a.m., police said
everything was under control, although there was a great deal of
damage.
   ``Nearly every part of the institution has been burned down,''
said David Evans, general secretary of the Prison Officers
Association, in an interview on British Broadcasting Corp. radio.
   He said the prison's kitchen, clothing exchange stores, education
departments and several of its wings had been gutted by the blaze.
   Evans said his association had been warning the prison system for
months that ``there are insufficient staff throughout the penal
system'' and noted that fewer than 20 prison officers were on duty
at the time of the riot.
   Evans said the riot proved that inmates needed hardly any excuse
to cause trouble: ``If it is over the pin-ups, it merely confirms
our view that you don't need an excuse if you are a prisoner to burn
down an institution.''
   The jail, with 490 inmates, is a former Royal Air Force camp used
for prisoners either nearing release or considered not dangerous by
parole boards. The 390 prisoners who gave themselves up were
sheltered in a workshop, police said.
</TEXT>
