<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-DrugCourier     06-06 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Drug Courier,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court To Consider Reinstating Conviction of Man Carrying Cocaine
at
Honolulu Airport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
reinstating the drug-possession conviction of a man who was carrying
1,000 grams of cocaine when stopped by authorities at a Honolulu
airport.
   The court said it will review a ruling that drug enforcement
agents lacked adequate evidence to suspect the man was engaged in a
crime when they stopped him.
   The Reagan administration said the appeals court ruling in Andrew
Sokolow's case is a major impediment in the fight against illegal
drug dealing.
   ``Many of the factors present in this case ... are ones on which
narcotics agents routinely rely when intercepting drug couriers,''
Justice Department lawyers told the high court.
   Sokolow was stopped by Drug Enforcement Administration agents
July 25, 1984, as he returned to Honolulu from a trip to Miami.
   Authorities said he aroused their suspicions three days earlier
when he and a female companion departed for Miami.
   They said Sokolow, who appeared to be in his mid-20s, bought his
plane tickets with $2,100 in cash taken from a roll of money that
appeared to contain more than $4,000. He was wearing a black
jumpsuit and a great deal of gold jewelry, appeared nervous, and he
and the woman carried four handbags on the plane without checking
any luggage.
   Agents also suspected Sokolow was using an alias because the name
he gave the ticket agent was not the same as the name listed for the
telephone number he gave the agent.
   Sokolow's behavior, dress and demeanor fit the profile of a drug
courier, narcotics agents said.
   Sokolow pled gulty to possession of cocaine with intent to
distribute and was sentenced to five years in prison. He appealed
the conviction on grounds the cocaine should not have been used as
evidence against him. He said the drug agents violated his right
against unlawful search and seizure when they stopped him.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeal threw out the conviction,
saying an officer's suspicion must ``be supported by evidence of
ongoing criminal activity.''
   ``Such behavior cannot be intuited from a hodgepodge assembly of
factors about individual character rather than criminal acts,'' the
appeals court said.
   The appeals court discounted the importance of Sokolow's
nervousness, stating: ``Nervousness would appear to be a normal
human reaction to air travel today, with a seemingly growing risk of
mid-air collision and the near certainty of delays that interrupt
the plans of travelers.''
   The Supreme Court, in a series of somewhat confusing rulings, has
upheld the use of so-called drug courier profiles by police.
   But the 9th Circuit court said while ``the vague and inchoate
profile presented here ... may generate good police work, absent
more it certaintly would generate bad law.''
   The case is U.S. vs. Sokolow, 87-1295.
</TEXT>
