<1ST_LINE>r p PM-WooCandidacy     06-06 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Woo Candidacy,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delaware Lt. Gov. Announces Senate Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo today
officially announced his bid to unseat five-term incumbent U.S. Sen.
William V. Roth Jr.
   Woo said Roth, a Republican, has provided valuable service to the
state, but said that does not mean he ``has been innovative or that
he is in tune with the times.''
   He faces fellow Democrat Samuel Beard, an investment banker and a
political activist who has state party backing, in a September
primary. However, he never mentioned Beard in his announcement;
later, he said he's targeting his efforts toward Roth.
   Woo admitted he is the underdog, but said he was in the same
position four years ago in his first bid for elected public office.
   In the 1984 elections, he won the lieutenant governor's seat by
only about 500 votes to become the highest-ranking Chinese-American
in an elected state position.
   Woo, 50, a physicist who was a professor at the University of
Delaware, said his expertise will help to develop high technology
jobs and higher pay.
   ``When elected, I want to help establish a federal technology
policy to make America the `king of technology' again. Why? So
American workers will again be the highest paid in the world,'' Woo
said.
</TEXT>
