<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     06-06 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Continues, But So Do Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three consecutive days of talks have failed to
end the 13-week-old scriptwriters strike against movie and
television producers, but another meeting was scheduled for today.
   Neither side claimed progress.
   ``It's just real sensitive,'' Cheryl Rhoden, spokeswoman for the
Writers Guild of America, said before the two sides recessed Sunday
evening.
   Negotiators also met Friday and Saturday and were scheduled to
resume talks this afternoon.
   Ms. Rhoden declined to comment on the issues discussed between
the guild and the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television
Producers and said only that negotiations were proceeding.
   On Friday the guild sent letters to owners and managers of 198
ABC-TV affiliates nationwide, urging them to press ABC to give
ground in negotiations to prevent further delays in the start of the
fall TV season.
   The writers walked out March 7 in a dispute that centers on
payments or residuals and reruns of one-hour television shows.
Demand for one-hour shows in rerun, or syndication, is declining,
and the producers want to tie payments to a show's success in the
rerun market.
   The two sides also have been at odds over writers' demands for
more say over changes made in scripts during filming and more credit
on and off screen for their work.
   The guild has signed full-term contracts with about 80
independent producers, but the alliance contends none of its large
members have signed and that the producers who did defect employ
only a fraction of the 3,000 active writers.
</TEXT>
