<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy Death, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0489,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Says School Lacked Formal Safety Rules</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with testimony resuming, picking
up at the 4th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A physician testified today that he saw an
ambulance crew properly administer resuscitation to a Navy recruit
who died after instructors forced him into a swimming pool during
lifesaver training.
   However, blood gas and chemistry tests indicated the
cardiopulmonary resuscitation efforts en route to and at the
Pensacola Naval Hospital had failed, Lt. Cmdr. Steven Marshall
testified at an investigative hearing.
   The emergency-room doctor led off the third day of testimony in
the hearing to determine whether five instructors and their
commanding officer should be court-martialed for the March 2 death
of Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis., at Pensacola
Naval Air Station.
   In testimony Saturday, an instructor said safety procedures were
informal at the Navy Rescue Swimmer School.
   And a doctor testified Saturday that Mirecki died of apparent
heart failure, most likely caused by fear. Several classmates
testified Mirecki appeared to be terrified before his death.
   ``He was very frightened and definitely scared to death,'' Petty
Officer 1st Class Joseph W. Yankawich, the student class leader,
testified Sunday.
   The instructors, all enlisted men, are charged with involuntary
manslaughter and conspiracy to commit battery. They are accused of
dragging Mirecki into the pool and holding his head under water
while struggling with him until his collapsed and died.
   Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, commander of the Navy Rescue Swimmer
School, is accused of dereliction of duty.
   There was no formal policy requiring one or more instructors to
stay out of the water as safety observers, but it was understood
that procedure should be followed, testified Petty Officer 2nd Class
Bennie T. Giles, an instructor who was present but not charged.
   None of the instructors were designated to observe, but they took
turns doing so during drills, Giles said.
   Questioned by Cmdr. Daniel J. D'Alesio, the investigating
officer, Giles said there was no release signal for students to give
if they were in trouble during practice rescue drills in which
instructors, playing the role of panicked drowning victims, grabbed
them in head holds.
   Another instructor not charged, Petty Officer 2nd Class Bobby
Powell, said it was policy to take a student to the deep end for
more training if he held on to the side of the pool.
   That's what happened to Mirecki, witnesses testified, but he
later climbed out. He said he wanted to quit the school and grabbed
an equipment rack, other students said.
   Petty Officer 1st Class Raymond W. Jablonowski, a safety
observer, said a group of instructors converged on Mirecki and
``more or less tossed'' him back into the pool.
   ``They put him back in the water,'' Giles said. ``He wasn't
thrown into the water. He was more or less slid into the water.''
   He said he could identify only one of the defendants, Petty
Officer 1st Class David J. Smith, as one of the instructors who
converged on Mirecki.
   Under questioning by lawyers for the defendants and government,
Giles denied that defendant Petty Officer 2nd Class John Zelenock
punched Mirecki and said he was unable to recall when other students
were told to turn away from the pool and sing the national anthem.
   Students had testified they were told to sing when Mirecki
allegedly was being forced, screaming for help, back into the pool.
</TEXT>
