<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DesertAliens     06-06 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Desert Aliens,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Found In Desert Returns To Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOGALES, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-six illegal immigrants were saved
from the blistering heat of the desert and returned to the Mexican
border to find their way home. But some of them said the parting
might not be permanent.
   Most members of the group were in generally good condition when
found Saturday afternoon, despite having gone without food and water
for nearly a day in 108-degree heat.
   They were fortunate. About 70 bodies have been found in the same
general area of the southern Arizona desert since 1980, according to
figures released last summer by the U.S. Border Patrol.
   On Sunday, authorities loaded the latest group onto a bus and
drove them to the border city of Nogales.
   Thirty-one walked silently through a revolving steel gate into
the Mexican state of Sonora; the other five followed after
videotaping interviews.
   ``We have to think it over,'' said Gilberto Perez, 28, of the
possibility he would try again to reach the agricultural belt
surrounding Phoenix.
   Authorities said all 36, including one woman, came from the state
of Oaxaca 1,500 miles to the south.
   Enrique Gonzalez, 50, said a field hand in Oaxaca usually earns
about 7,000 pesos, or $3, a day.
   ``In my land, what we earn is nothing,'' he said.
   ``What is that (7,000 pesos) when I have eight children?''
Gonzalez asked. ``We eat only tortillas and beans.''
   Others said the group started off with flour tortillas, white
bread, canned beans and water but ran out on Friday, the third day
of a trek northward.
   Late Saturday morning, they found water in a brackish pond
tainted by tailings from the Silverbell copper mine about 35 miles
northwest of Tucson.
   A few hours later, they were in custody because two men left the
group to ask for help at a ranch near Silverbell.
   Three members of the group received intravenous fluids for
dehydration at Northwest Hospital in Tucson, a nurse said.
   ``We're glad nobody died. That's why you get this kind of
response. With this soaring heat, we responded with everything we
had in an attempt to save lives,'' said Ronald Dowdy, chief patrol
agent for the Border Patrol's Tucson sector.
   The group crossed the U.S.-Mexico border apparently by jumping
the international fence about 60 miles southwest of Tucson, and
headed north into the searing heat of the desert.
   Although members of the group said they crossed the border in
groups of four, five or six people, Border Patrol officials said
they suspected that a ``coyote,'' or border smuggler, organized the
attempt.
</TEXT>
