<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-Paternity 1stLd-Writethru a0560 06-06 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Paternity, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0560,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Strikes Down Six-Year Deadline for Paternity Suits</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 6 new grafs after pvs 5th graf bgng, Today's decision,
on other Supreme Court actions; SUBS pvs 6th graf bgng, Congress
called, to reword for transition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today unanimously struck down
a former Pennsylvania deadline allowing mothers of illegitimate
children a maximum of six years to sue alleged fathers for child
support.
   ``Six years does not necessarily provide a reasonable opportunity
to assert a claim on behalf of an illegimate child,'' Justice Sandra
Day O'Connor wrote for the court, which held that the deadline once
imposed by Pennsylvania for paternity lawsuits was unconstitutional.
   The justices in 1982 unanimously struck down a state law's ban on
paternity suits not filed within one year of the child's birth. In
1983, the court unanimously struck down a two-year deadline for such
suits.
   That 1983 decision hinted that the court might frown on state
laws preventing mothers from suing on behalf of any minor child _ in
effect condoning an 18-year deadline for paternity suits.
   Today's decision again offered such hints but the court stopped
short of saying so explicitly.
   In other action today, the high court:
   _Ruled unanimously that states may not prohibit groups from
paying those who gather petition signatures necessary to place a
referendum on state ballots.
   _Decided unanimously in a case from Illinois that states may give
protection to workers beyond that provided by federal labor law so
long as it doesn't force courts to interpret collective bargaining
agreements.
   _Agreed to decide whether railroads may require all employees
involved in serious accidents to submit to drug testing.
   _Let stand the rape conviction of an Illinois man who wanted a
judge to examine privately the conversations his victim had with
rape crisis counselors.
   _Refused, 6-3, to order states to give refunds to businesses when
a state tax is invalidated as a violation of interstate commerce.
   On the issue of paternity suit deadlines, Congress called for
such 18-year deadlines in the Child Support Enforcement Amendments
of 1984, but the justices passed up the chance to rule whether the
1984 federal law is binding on the states.
   Instead, the court ruled that Pennsylvania's former six-year
deadline violated constitutional rights of equal protection under
the law because legitimate children may sue for parental support at
any time.
   The case involved in today's ruling stemmed from the 1973 birth
in Pittsburgh of Tiffany Clark.
   Tiffany's mother, Cherlyn Clark, sued Gene Jeter in 1983 after he
stopped making voluntary, intermittent contributions to Tiffany's
support.
   According to court documents, blood tests showed a 99.3 percent
probability that Jeter was Tiffany's father.
   Jeter, defending himself against the paternity suit, cited the
six-year statute of limitations then in effect for such suits.
   While the litigation was pending, Pennsylvania changed the
relevant statute of limitations to 18 years.
   A state appeals court upheld the six-year deadline, and the
Pennsylvania Supreme Court refused to hear Ms. Clark's appeal.
   Today, the high court provided Ms. Clark with a legal victory by
sending her case back to a state trial court.
   In her opinion, O'Connor noted that Pennsylvania law places no
time limit on lawsuits filed by illegitimate children who sue to
prove paternity for purposes of inheritance.
   She also noted that Pennsylvania does not impose any deadline for
lawsuits filed by men trying to prove paternity.
   ``It is questionable whether a state acts reasonably when it
requires most paternity and support actions to be brought within six
years of an illegitimate child's birth,'' O'Connor said.
   The case is Clark vs. Jeter, 87-5565.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Protest 5thLd-Writethru a0526 06-06 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Protest, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0526,0752</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: EDITS thruout to update with nine injured in attack on bus,
give number staying out of work, other details. NO PICKUP.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Explosions damaged commuter
railroads and Zulu officials said nine bus passengers were injured
by a fire bomb today as hundreds of thousands of black workers and
students joined a general strike.
   The scheduled three-day protest is the longest nationwide strike
called in several years. It takes place under new bans on political
activity by major anti-apartheid groups and black union federations,
which helped organize the strike.
   Mangosuthu Buthelezi, who heads the black homeland of KwaZulu and
an opponent of the protest, said four people were killed when a hand
grenade was thrown at a commuter bus. Later, an aide to Buthelezi
said the report had been incorrect and that nine passengers were
injured when a fire bomb was thrown at the vehicle.
   Police said five were hurt in the incident.
   No injuries were reported in bombing attacks on railway lines and
buses near Johannesburg and Pretoria or in the firebombing of the
Umgababa Station near Amanzimtoti, a black township outside Durban.
   Mining companies reported absentees only in some coal mines. Gold
and diamond mines, accounting for more than 60 percent of the
country's foreign currency earnings, operated normally.
   Black union leaders, who called for a national protest _ without
saying that it should be a general strike _ said they hoped to
pressure big business into demanding that the government ease its
crackdown on opponents of apartheid.
   Protest organizers called on workers to oppose a labor bill
before Parliament and restrictions on political activity, but
employers and union officials concede that the main purpose of the
strike is to test the strength of banned anti-apartheid groups.
   There was no official estimate of the number of people
participating in the protest. But based on the number of people who
normally use public transport, the absentees in major cities would
have totalled several hundred thousand.
   The government railroad service and private bus companies that
carry black workers from townships into city centers in Transvaal
and Natal provinces termed the general strike ``highly effective.''
   Absentee rates for black workers ranged from 30 percent in
Pretoria, to 95 percent in Durban and an estimated 80-90 percent in
Cape Town. Port Elizabeth, known as a center of political unrest,
had a near normal turnout.
   The Federated Chamber of Industries said the Johannesburg area
was the hardest hit by the strike, with a 90 percent absentee rate
among the black work force.
   The Johannesburg Stock Exchange reported an almost total strike
by its black workers, and the streets were empty and quiet.
   There were few milk or bakery deliveries, since most truck
drivers are black. Hospital supervisors in a Johannesburg medical
clinic had to wash floors and clean toilets, and whites operated
cash registers at many shops, which were empty of the usual crowds
of black customers.
   The South African automobile industry came to a standstill, with
all seven major assembly plants closing for three days.
   Many employers who normally institute a policy of ``no work _ no
pay'' during such illegal general strikes reacted more strongly this
time, obtaining court orders to prevent calls to strike and
threatening to dismiss absentees or cancel union contracts.
   The unions accused the managers of cooperating with alleged
government efforts to weaken the black labor movement.
   The national black chamber of commerce supported the protest and
agreed to close businesses through Wednesday.
   But in some townships near Cape Town, blacks were seen walking to
adjacent mixed-race communities to do their shopping and catch taxis
to work. Some cities reported more black worker turnout as the day
progressed.
   Scores of schools were empty in black townships around Soweto,
Cape Town and Durban, and three universities delayed final
examinations or canceled classes.
   Buses were stoned and there were reports of police gunfire in
Guguletu, a black township outside Cape Town. Journalists were
ordered from the area.
   Police and soldiers were reported patrolling in greater than
normal numbers in Cape Town and Johannesburg-area townships, and
standing guard at some train stations.
   Apartheid, by law and custom, establishes a racially segregated
society in which the nation's 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
