<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Zaire,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mobutu Sese Seko to Visit White House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zaire's President Mobutu Sese Seko, one of the
administration's staunchest African allies, will meet with President
Reagan this week, the White House announced today.
   Mobutu, who has been in power since 1965, last met with Reagan in
December 1986.
   The Zairean leader is also expected to meet with officials of the
World Bank, which last year granted his country an $80 million loan.
The funds were released after Mobutu undertook a reform program
including improvement of tax collection, promotion of private
enterprise and deregulation of prices.
   With nine neighbors and the second-largest land area in
sub-Saharan Africa, Zaire is regarded in Washington as one of
Africa's most strategically important countries. Mobutu pleased
American officials by sending troops to Chad to help it fight Libya.
   But Amnesty International and other human rights groups have
criticized Zaire for human rights abuses, including torture of
prisoners.
   Mobutu is also meeting with members of the congressional black
caucus to answer questions about allegations of human rights abuses
by his government, a congressional staffer said.
   The closed meeting on Wednesday will include discussion of the
cases of opposition leaders sent into internal exile, said the staff
member who asked not to be named.
   Last month 58 members of Congress wrote Mobutu to protest the
banishment of Tshisekedi wa Mulumba, a former minister of the
interior.
</TEXT>
