<HEAD>Israel's National Airline Turns Down Cargo Of Pigs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's national El Al Airlines has rejected a
deal worth tens of thousands of dollars to transport live pigs from
the United States to Europe to avoid offending Orthodox Jews, a
spokesman said.
   ``We don't feed our passengers un-kosher food, and we wouldn't
want to put pigs in the bellies of our planes,'' said El Al
spokesman Nachman Kleinman.
   Jewish dietary laws prohibit Jews from eating pork.
   Kleinman said in a telephone interview that the airline had
recently considered the offer to fly 12 tons of pigs to Europe for
breeding because it would have been worth ``tens of thousands of
dollars.''
   ``It's such a touchy subject, and some people would be offended
by it, so we decided against the deal,'' Kleinman added.
   The offer was by a North American company that Kleinman would not
identify.
</TEXT>
