<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-AncientFind     06-06 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Ancient Find,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4,000-Year-Old Musical Instrument Found in Grave on Crete</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It looks like a child's rattle, but it is
made of clay and was placed in a communal grave on the island of
Crete almost 4,000 years ago.
   The unique find from a Minoan cemetery outside the village of
Arkhanes is a sistrum, a percussion instrument used at religious
ceremonies in ancient times.
   In more than 100 years of digging on Crete, the home of Europe's
first high civilization in the Bronze Age, nobody had ever unearthed
a restorable musical instrument.
   ``It's the first time, we've recovered a sound created by the
Minoans...we've got a noise they heard,'' said Yiannis Sakellarakis,
the archaeologist who made the discovery last summer.
   ``It's a light sound that's hard to describe...clear and distinct
but an earthy sort of note,'' he said in a weekend interview.
   The Minoan civilization is named after King Minos, a legendary
ruler who kept a half-man, half-bull monster called the Minotaur
imprisoned in a labyrinth beneath his palace at Knossos.
   Arkhanes is 10 miles south of Knossos in a hilly but fertile
wine-growing district of central Crete that was densely populated in
Minoan times.
   The sistrum is a flat 4-inch diameter circle of unpainted clay
with a handle. The face had two parallel wooden slats across it, and
clay discs were slotted loosely between the slats.
   ``If you shook the instrument from side to side, you'd get a
light rythmic sound from the discs rattling against each other and
the clay frame,'' said Sakellarakis, a director of Greece's National
Archaeological Museum.
   ``It's a fantastic find. We know there was ritual drinking at
Minoan burials, and perhaps this indicates there was music and
singing or chanting as well,'' said Sandy McGillivray, an associate
professor of archaeology at Columbia University in New York.
   The sistrum was unearthed in a stone-walled burial chamber _ or
ossuary _ containing the skeletons and personal items of more than
150 Minoans. The grave offerings were mostly vases but included
carved ivory seals that probably belonged to the wealthier members
of a family clan.
   Sakellarakis said the sistrum apparently dates from around 1900
B.C. Some painted clay cups from that period were found next to the
instrument.
   ``We found the clay circle broken into two pieces. Then we
associated it with the three discs and realized we'd got a very
early sistrum,'' he said.
   Music and dancing were part of a sophisticated ancient lifestyle
on Crete, illustrated in wall-paintings, sealstones and carved stone
vases found in the sprawling Minoan palaces and country villas built
throughout the island.
   One vase made around 1500 B.C. shows a middle-aged man
brandishing a sistrum as he leads a group of singing worshipers.
   Sakellarakis said the sistrums found in Egypt ``were invariably
made of metal, not clay, and usually were associated with the cult
of Isis.'' Isis was worshipped in ancient Egypt as a goddess of
fertility who could also cure the sick.
   Sakellarakis and his wife, Effie, have excavated around Arkhanes
since the mid-1960s. In addition to the cemetery excavation, they
have unearthed part of a Minoan palace in Arkhanes and a shrine on
nearby Mount Iuktas, where it is believed the Minoans carried out a
human sacrifice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
