<HEAD>Tower of London Top Historic Attraction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tower of London was Britain's most visited
historic site in 1987, attracting 2.29 million tourists, up from
about 2 million in 1986, the British Tourist Authority said Monday.
   The runner-up was Edinburgh Castle in Scotland, up from 832,485
visitors in 1986 to 967,424 last year, according to statistics.
   The British Museum in London was the most popular museum, with
3.7 million visitors, compared with 3.59 million in 1986. It was
followed by the National Gallery in London with 3.567 million
visitors, up from 3.182 million.
   Kew Garden, also in London, was the top public garden, with 1.335
million visitors, up from 1.147 million.
   Blackpool Beach in northwest England was the biggest leisure
attraction of all, with 6.45 million visitors, down from 6.5 million
the year before.
  
