<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FTC-Advertising     06-06 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Advertising,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>False Ad Charges Can Cost Companies Millions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Being charged with false advertising can cost a
company millions of dollars, even if no fine is ever levied, the
Federal Trade Commission reported Monday.
   At the same time, the commission announced that the marketer of
Dream Away diet pills has agreed to set up a $1.1 million fund to
repay consumers in a false advertising case.
   When false advertising charges are brought against a company, the
market price of that company's stock declines, often significantly,
the commission said in its analysis of the effects of advertising
regulation.
   For a company with a value of $500 million, the drop in stock
prices could amount to $20 million in lost value, according to David
Scheffman, director of the FTC's bureau of economics.
   This decline is a measure of the market's estimate of the problem
the company will have in selling its products as a result of the
false advertising charges, Commission Chairman Daniel Oliver said.
   Thus, while the commission rarely levies fines against companies
in advertising cases, just bringing the accusation has a significant
effect, even if the charges eventually are dropped.
   Generally, when the FTC brings false advertising charges, the
case is settled with a consent agreement, in which the company,
while not admitting any wrongdoing, promises not to do it again.
Only if there is a subsequent violation of that promise are fines
likely.
   Such instances are rare, Oliver noted, the companies having
already suffered damage to reputation, costs of litigation and loss
of stock value and business.
   The study focused on 122 cases between 1962 and 1985 in which the
FTC brought false advertising charges. In 74 cases the companies
agreed to a consent order settling the case, while 48 contested the
case.
   In the cases settled by consent order, the companies' stock value
lost an average of 2.5 percent in the five days following the
announcement, the study found.
   The greatest effect was seen in cases in which a company
contested the FTC charges in court, but eventually lost. Abnormal
stock price losses averaged 1.2 percent at the time of the
complaint, 1.8 percent when the administrative law judge ruled and
1.9 percent on final commission action.
   Those cases generate considerably more negative publicity, Oliver
said, compared with ones in which they ``go quietly.''
   By comparison, the FTC study found little effect on businesses
from two other systems of advertising regulation: the National
Advertising Division of the Better Business Bureaus and the Lanham
Act, which allows businesses to sue one another for false
advertising.
   While involvement in any type of false advertising case can
damage a company's reputation, those generated by the FTC tend to
get widespread news media coverage, while the other two systems get
little media attention, the FTC said.
   In the Dream Away case, Nutri Marketing of Scottsdale, Ariz.,
agreed to set up the $1.1 million fund to reimburse buyers of its
Dream Away and Advances Dream Away products.
   Those products consisted of a 21-day supply of pills, sold for
$19.95, which were advertised as a means of losing weight while
sleeping. Dream Away does not cause weight loss without diet or
exercise and does not contribute to the loss effects of diet and
exercise, the commission said.
   Consumers who have purchased Dream Away and who want to determine
if they are eligible for a refund can write Nancy Warder, the
Federal Trade Commission, 6th Street and Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W.,
Washington, D.C., 20580.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0110 </DOCNO>
