<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham     06-06 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules on Notes By Campaign Aide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Handwritten notes by an Evan Mecham
campaign aide may be used as evidence in the former governor's
criminal trial on charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan, a
judge ruled today.
   However, the three pages of notes by former Mecham Finance
Committee member Vern Gasser may not be introduced as exhibits
unless the defense offers them, the judge said.
   Some contend that the notes, written in fall 1986 by Gasser,
appear to reflect a discussion on whether to disclose the $350,000
campaign loan from developer Barry Wolfson.
   The notes say ``Show Evan borrowed money'' and ``don't show
borrowed money.'
   Gasser testified Friday that he could not recall when the notes
were taken, who was present at the time, or what the notes meant.
   Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Michael Ryan ruled that he
would not allow the notes themselves to be introduced as exhibits
unless the defense requests it ``so the jurors will not place undue
emphasis on them.''
   Ryan noted they were made at meetings that ``dealt with intimate
campaign strategy and finances'' even though Gasser said he could no
longer remember what they meant.
   The prosecution wanted the notes introduced as evidence. But Joe
Keilp, attorney for Mecham's brother and co-defendant, Willard
Mecham, said Friday he was concerned they could be used to imply
that the statements might have been made by Willard Mecham or by
Evan Mecham's former chief of staff, Jim Colter.
   Mecham is charged with six felony counts of perjury, willful
concealment and filing false documents. He faces up to 22 years in
prison if convicted on all counts. Willard Mecham, who was his
brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faces three similar counts and up
to 9{ years in prison.
   The former governor has long contended that the $350,000 loan was
properly reported as part of a $465,000 lump sum that was listed on
financial reports as a contribution from Mecham.
   The prosecution said in opening statements last week that
Mecham's gubernatorial campaign badly needed the money but wanted to
conceal the fact that it came from a developer because Mecham
portrayed himself as being ``beholden to no one.''
   Mecham, a Republican, took office in January 1987. He was removed
from office April 4 when the Senate convicted him of two unrelated
impeachment counts.
   He also was impeached in connection with the $350,000 loan, but
the Senate decided not to hear that charge to avoid prejudicing his
criminal trial.
</TEXT>
