<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Election     06-06 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Election,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliamentary Race Pits Gandhi Ally Against Foe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Minister V.P. Singh
characterizes his campaign for Parliament in the June 16 elections
as a fight of ``money power versus people's power.''
   His main opponent for the seat from the central city of Allahabad
is singer and scriptwriter Sunil Shastri, who says the race is a
clash of political ideologies.
   Most people, however, see the Singh-Shastri race in Uttar Pardesh
state as a test of strength for Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's
governing Congress Party.
   It is one of seven by-elections for seats in the lower house of
Parliament. The election will also decide 10 state assembly seats.
   
   A defeat in Uttar Pradesh would signal further weakness for
Gandhi's party, which has fared badly in local contests _ it lost 10
of 14 state assembly elections in the past two years.
   Uttar Pardesh is India's most populous state and a bastion of the
Hindi-speaking population, which dominates India's politics in the
form of the Congress Party.
   Allahabad, a city of 700,000 people, is 350 miles southeast of
New Delhi.
   Sixty-eight other candidates are running for the seat, but the
Congress Party has thrown its weight behind Shastri, 38, the son of
the late popular Prime Minister Lal Bahadur Shastri.
   The major national opposition parties have endorsed the
56-year-old Singh, a former Gandhi ally who is now his opponent.
   As defense minister, Singh was one of the most powerful figures
in the Gandhi administration. He broke with the prime minister last
year over the government's hesitation to investigate his allegations
that kickbacks were paid for defense contracts. Some of the funds
were believed to have gone to Gandhi supporters.
   Singh told reporters last week that the central issue of his
campaign remains ``money power versus people's power.'' Singh _
nicknamed ``the raja,'' Hindi for ``the king'' _ is the son of the
late raja of eastern Uttar Pradesh.
   He says he demands a clean government, as well as improved
services such as pure drinking water, adequate electricity supply
and proper irrigation.
   ``I personally see (the race) as a fight between ideologies,''
Shastri said.
   In an interview published in the New Delhi-based Sunday Mail
newspaper, Shastri emphasized that the Congress Party _ through men
like his late father _ had earned the support of the people.
   ``We had great leaders who fought in the freedom struggle (from
Britain in 1947), leaders who took the country on the path of
progress after independence,'' he was quoted as saying.
   The Singh-Shastri contest has raised political emotions in the
state to the boiling point.
   Last Friday, Congress Party workers attacked a group of young
people loyal to Singh after they staged a walkout from a Congress
Party meeting. One of the youths was beaten unconscious, and he and
two others required hospitalization.
   The city of Allahabad was shut down by a strike on Saturday to
protest the violence.
</TEXT>
