<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Spoleto     06-06 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spoleto,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Festival Officials Call Festival Artistic Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizers of the Spoleto Festival U.S.A.
have declared this year's festival an artistic success although it
will be several weeks before the financial picture comes into focus.
   ``We've done well, but there's still work to be done,'' said
festival General Manager Nigel Redden. ``It happens every year. We
don't know what expenses are going to be exactly, and we will get
unpledged donations, too.''
   The festival closed Sunday night with an open-air symphony
concert of works by Russian composers followed by a fireworks
display at Middleton Place Plantation.
   About 5,000 people attended, some arriving early with picnic
baskets and coolers.
   This year's Spoleto, which critics have hailed as one of the most
ambitious in the festival's 12-year American history, featured more
than 100 performances of opera, music, dance and theater over 17
days.
   ``We're very happy with everything,'' said Charles Way, chairman
of Spoleto's board of directors. ``I have no doubt we'll end up this
year in the black.''
   Festival spokesman Scott Horton said Monday that ticket receipts
are not computerized and it will be several weeks before final
figures on ticket sales are in hand. The festival's fiscal year ends
in August.
   Redden and Way agreed the festival was an artistic success. Way
said the festival was more adventurous than in previous years,
including several premieres.
</TEXT>
