<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-06 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Twinkle, twinkle little star, how we wonder
where you are. Up above the lights you stare, but we can't see you
for their glare. Twinkle, twinkle star so fine, hidden by the city's
shine.''
   So might go the lament of amateur astronomers lobbying officials
to turn down the city lights so they can get a better view of the
heavens.
   The Amateur Astronomers Association of Pittsburgh is seeking
restrictions on street and building lighting to reduce what they
call ``light pollution.'' Artificial light interferes with their
ability to stargaze.
   ``I don't plan on giving up,'' Tom Reiland, association president
and an astronomer at Allegheny Observatory, said recently. ``I feel
this is a worthwhile effort.''
   The dramatic lighting of Fifth Avenue Place, a new skyscraper in
downtown Pittsburgh, was muted after the astronomers complained,
although Hillman Properties Vice President John Markey said the
change came as workers focused the lights, not because of the
astronomers' plea.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STRONG CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There were a few ``nay'' sayers amid the
worshipers, but that didn't fluster the preachers at the Flint Hills
Rodeo.
   After all, they were on horseback, too.
   Decked out in cowboy hats, boots and shirts, they led an
ecumenical service of hymn singing, scripture reading and
sermonizing Sunday morning for 400 rodeo participants, spectators
and area townsfolk, and, of course, their horses.
   Cheryl Lunday, pastor of the First Presbyterian Church in nearby
Cottonwood Falls, read the cowboy's prayer, asking God to guide
those present ``in the arena of life.''
   Bennie Holtsclaw sang ``One Day at a Time'' while sitting astride
his horse strumming a guitar.
   The congregants, many decked out in their Western best, kept
their hats on to ward off the hot sun. Church bells could be heard
ringing in the distance, and there was a collection at the gate.
   The real cowboys at the service included, Bruce Ford, 35, of
Kersey, Colo., a professional bull and bareback bronc rider for 18
years who has won an unprecedented five world championship titles
and four national championships in bareback bronc riding, and, Bart
McBeth, whose specialty is saddle bronc riding.
</TEXT>
