<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceShuttleTest     06-06 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle Test,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Schedules Key Space Shuttle Countdown Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A countdown test will be conducted
Tuesday in a major rehearsal for the first space shuttle launch
since the Challenger disaster.
   The launch team will assemble in the control center for the final
three hours of a simulated countdown, with a mock liftoff of shuttle
Discovery planned for 9:50 a.m. The exercise will be a realistic
preparation for the actual launch, set for Aug. 31.
   Following the countdown, mission control center in Houston will
assume control of a make-believe flight and will guide a shuttle
crew, operating in a Houston simulator, through an abort situation
in which the astronauts make an emergency landing at Kennedy Space
Center.
   The participating astronauts will be Loren Shriver, James
Wetherbee and Franklin Chang-Diaz. Observing will be the five-man
crew that will fly Discovery, commanded by astronaut Rick Hauck.
   The launch team here has held countdown rehearsals every month
for several months, but Tuesday's test will be the first to tie
together the Kennedy and Johnson space centers, the mission
management team and all the other elements that will be in place on
launch day.
   National Aeronautics and Space Administration spokeswoman Lisa
Malone said the practice ``will validate to the fullest extent
possible the complete launch process system.'' She said it will
exercise procedure and personnel changes that have occurred since
the Challenger exploded 73 seconds after liftoff on Jan. 28, 1986,
killing the crew of seven.
   Discovery is in a hangar at Kennedy Space Center, undergoing
final checks following a major overhaul of systems. Many of the
changes were the result of the investigation into the Challenger
accident, which was blamed on a faulty joint in a solid fuel booster
rocket.
   On June 16, Discovery is to be moved into an assembly building
for mating with its two solid fuel boosters and external fuel tank.
Transfer to the launch pad is planned for June 27.
   The spaceship's three main engines will be test-fired on the pad
in a critical test July 19.
   Officials said the current Aug. 31 launch target can be met if no
critical problems crop up during testing here and at the Morton
Thiokol plant in Utah, where two more full-scale tests are planned
of the redesigned booster rocket. The Utah tests are slated for June
14 and July 26.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica-Angola 1stLd-Writethru a0602 06-06 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0602,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army May Mobilize Units To Counter Cuban Buildup</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTs last graf to show the 97,000 soldiers are not part
of
the Citizen Force.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military said Monday it is
considering mobilizing special reserve units to help counter
deployment of Cuban forces in southern Angola.
   The brief statement from military headquarters in Pretoria
confirmed newspaper reports that a call-up was possible as a
precautionary measure in the event of escalated combat.
   The mobilization would involve units of the Citizen Force, which
includes men who have completed their obligatory two-year military
service but who participate in annual training camps and may be
mobilized.
   South African troops fighting in Angola support the rebels
fighting Angola's Marxist government. Angolan troops are backed by
an estimated 45,000 Cuban soldiers.
   South African officials have warned that the Cuban buildup _
confirmed by Cuban President Fidel Castro _ could jeopardize peace
negotiations aimed at resolving Angola's 13-year-old civil war.
   South Africa has said 9,000 to 15,000 new Cuban troops are
involved in the latest deployment.
   The peace talks also are aimed at bringing independence to
South-West Africa, the South African-ruled territory commonly known
as Namibia, which borders southern Angola.
   South Africa has complained that the Cubans, in some cases
accompanied by Namibian guerrillas, have moved to within 25 miles of
the Namibian border.
   South African military officials said Namibian guerrillas have
used the protection of the additional Cuban troops to move their
bases closer to the Angolan border and away from South African
troops on raids in Namibia.
   South Africa has 97,000 soldiers on active duty and about 175,000
reservists in the Citizen Force, according to the London-based
International Institute for Strategic Studies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
