<DOCNO> AP880606-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1457EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-LastPrimaryAds     06-06 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Primary Ads,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Primary Advertising Ends on a Quiet Note</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In sharp contrast to the media assaults of
February and March, the California airwaves are nearly devoid of
presidential advertising as the primary season draws to its
anticlimactic close
   With the Democratic and Republican nominees all but chosen, only
underdog Jesse Jackson waged a substantial television campaign in
the state with the largest number of convention delegates at stake.
He was hoping to spend $700,000 on TV by the time the polls closed
in California, one of four states with primaries on Tuesday.
   Republican Vice President George Bush, nearing the $27 million
ceiling on primary spending, didn't advertise at all. And
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the probable Democratic nominee,
expected to spend no more than $200,000 on television.
   ``Realistically, you have to spend far more than we anticipate
spending to maximize the impact of advertising,'' said Dukakis
strategist Tom Kiley. ``His own schedule of appearances was the
thing in which we were investing most heavily, the most important
element of the campaign.''
   Alixe Glen, a Bush spokeswoman, said Bush stayed off the air in
California ``in large part due to the fact that we have not had an
opponent for so long in the Republican Party.''
   Dukakis limited his television advertising to Los Angeles and San
Francisco. The idea, according to Kiley, was to catch the attention
of people already interested in the election and give them a little
extra information about Dukakis.
   ``That's a very modest goal,'' Kiley said. ``We don't pretend
that advertising is playing a major role in the campaign.''
   The early part of the primary season, with its multitude of GOP
and Democratic candidates, was rife with hard-hitting, often
negative television advertising. The TV campaign culminated on Super
Tuesday, March 8, when the presidential hopefuls competed in 20
far-flung contests in what, for many of them, was a do-or-die
proposition.
   By the time the final four primaries rolled around, the focus was
already on the general election in November.
   In one California ad, Dukakis says ``the chief executive can make
a difference in the war against drugs. I've done it in my state and
I want to do it for every state in this country.''
   In a companion ad, an announcer describes Dukakis' Massachusetts
program and quotes federal agents as calling it ``a model for the
nation. ... He did it with hard work. Integrity. Leadership. We
could use some of that in the White House.''
   Dukakis also was using a biographical spot and radio ads, some in
Spanish, aimed at the state's black and Hispanic voters.
   Jackson, his dream of a California upset all but dead, made a
last-minute pitch for money in a 30-second ad that started running
Saturday. And he bought a half-hour of television time across the
state Monday night to wind up his all-out drive in California.
   The program, part live and part pre-recorded, was meant to
highlight the significance and achievements of the Jackson campaign,
raise money and attract as many voters as possible. Actor Tony
Franciosa, who played the teacher ``Mr. Novak'' on television years
ago, signed on as the moderator.
   In the days preceding the primary, Jackson used an array of
30-second ads, some old and some new, on cable, independent and
network affiliate stations in Fresno, Los Angeles, El Centro,
Sacramento, Salinas, Redding, Santa Barbara, Bakersfield, Palm
Springs, San Jose, San Francisco, Eureka, Monterey, San Diego, and
Reno, Nev.
   One older ad touted Jackson's success in winning the release of
an American pilot shot down in the Middle East. Other spots featured
farmers saying they need Jackson and actress Eileen Brennan praising
the candidate's stands on women's issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1545EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--SpecialOlympics     06-06 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Special Olympics,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minneapolis-St. Paul To Host 1991 Special Olympics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The twin cities of Minneapolis and St. Paul,
Minn., have been selected to host the 1991 International Summer
Special Olympic Games _ an event organizers say will be that year's
largest sports event.
   ``These games will be historic in that there will be more people
with mental retardation competing and more countries sending
athletes than ever before,'' Eunice Kennedy Shriver, founder and
chairman of the Special Olympics International, said Monday.
   The budget for the 1991 games is estimated to be approximately $8
million, $3 million more than that of the 1987 international
competition held in South Bend, Ind.
   Budget expenditures include transportation, housing, food,
security, facility preparation, equipment, special events for the
athletes and opening and closing ceremonies.
   Mrs. Shriver said the committee, which has to raise the bulk of
the budget, expects the participation of more than 6,000 special
olympians from 91 nations.
   Founded in 1968, the Special Olympics International provides
year-round sports training and competition to 1 million disabled
athletes in more than 70 countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
