<DOCNO> AP880606-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TwinValedictorians     06-06 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Twin Valedictorians,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twins With Identical Averages Share Top Honor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Identical twins Jerlyn and Jeanine Jones
think alike _so much alike that they wound up with the same
grade-point average to share top-of-the-class honors on graduating
from eighth grade.
   The 14-year-olds each scored 1.16 under a grading system in which
an A is 1, a B is 2, etc., said Bush Elementary School Principal
Eddie Lewis. The lower the average, the better the grades.
   The two girls had identical class schedules, and expect to
continue sharing classes in high school and attend the same college
later on.
   And the similarity doesn't end with academics. Jeanine is student
council president, Jerlyn vice president, and they also participated
in the same sports.
   In discussing their lives, one twin often finishes a sentence
begun by the other, without interruption or hesitation.
   ``A lot of times we say the same thing at the same time,''
Jeanine said. ``And our friends get frustrated when we do that,''
her sister added.
   ``Our teachers can't tell us apart,'' Jerlyn said. ``They just
take a guess,'' Jeanine said.
   At their graduation Wednesday, one intends to talk about their
past education, the other about the future.
   As for how they achieved the honor, Jerlyn said, ``I just go to
my classes, stick to my work, study _ it just comes naturally.''
   ``Our mother makes sure we do our homework,'' Jeanine added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1549EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pollard-Appeal     06-06 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pollard-Appeal,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers For Anne Henderson-Pollard Ask For Sentence Reduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for the wife of convicted spy Jonathan
Jay Pollard filed a motion with the U.S. Court of Appeals on Monday
asking for reduction of her five-year prison sentence due to
deteriorating health.
   The brief seeks to overturn last December's ruling by District
Judge Aubrey Robinson, who rejected a request by Anne
Henderson-Pollard for a sentence reduction.
   Nathan Dershowitz, the attorney representing Mrs.
Henderson-Pollard, said he had asked the court either to reduce the
sentence to the time already served, to suspend her remaining
sentence or to grant her probation.
   Mrs. Henderson-Pollard was sentenced to five years imprisonment
for conspiring to receive embezzled government property and being an
accessory after the fact to possession of defense secrets. She began
serving her sentence on March 4, 1987, the same day her husband
began serving a life term.
   Pollard, a civilian intelligence analyst for the U.S. Navy, was
found guilty of selling secrets to Israel.
   Mrs. Henderson-Pollard suffers from a rare stomach ailment, and
friends and relatives say she has lost some 60 pounds in the past
two years. She is currently at the Federal Correctional Institution
in Rochester, Minnesota, to undergo testing at the nearby Mayo
Clinic.
   The court brief contends that Mrs. Henderson-Pollard is being
denied proper medical treatment at the Lexington, Ky. jail where she
is usually incarcerated.
   ``This barbarous withdrawal of treatment forced Mrs. Pollard to
endure excruciating pain, without even the limited relief afforded
by painkilling medication,'' the brief said.
   Her father, Bernard Henderson, visited Mrs. Pollard 10 days ago.
He said her condition was ``similar to survivors of death camps. She
is permanently hunched over in pain, cannot stand or sit erect, and
is little but skin and bones.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
