<DOCNO> AP880606-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Thompson-Veep 1stLd-Writethru a0599 06-06 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thompson-Veep, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0599,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Governor Could End Up Running Mate for Close Friend Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 8th graf to CORRECT winning margin to 5,074 to 5,047 bgng
``Also open...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Illinois Gov. James R. Thompson comes to
the nation's capital he often stays at the vice president's mansion,
the guest of his friend George Bush.
   This summer, Bush could offer Thompson a chance to become a
longer-term resident of the house on the Naval Observatory grounds.
   Now in his fourth term as governor, Thompson often is mentioned
as a potential choice to be the vice presidential nominee on a
Republican ticket headed by Bush.
   As governor of a major battleground state in the fall election _
one that offers 24 electoral votes _ Thompson's name would almost
certainly turn up on most short lists of GOP vice presidential
prospects. Another plus is his closeness to Bush.
   But Thompson, who was elected governor of Illinois in 1976 by the
largest margin in state history, has been on the lists of other
Republican presidential hopefuls and never has gotten beyond being
one of those mentioned.
   One reason is that he is one of the last of the liberal
Republicans, a dwindling band of politicians in the ideological mold
of the late Nelson A. Rockefeller, politicians left out in the cold
in the GOP of the Ronald Reagan era.
   Thompson earned the enmity of Reagan loyalists in 1980 when he
waited until May 4 to endorse the former California governor for the
GOP presidential nomination. His endorsement came six weeks after
the Illinois primary and after all chance of any other Republican
overtaking Reagan had been lost.
   Also open to question is whether Thompson could guarantee the
Republican ticket would carry Illinois. While the 52-year-old
governor's 1.4-million-vote victory margin in 1976 was the largest
in state history, he also squeeked through to re-election in 1982 by
5,074 votes _ the smallest edge ever.
   In that race, Democrat Adlai E. Stevenson III didn't concede
defeat until two months after Election Day, when the state Supreme
Court rejected his request for a statewide recount.
   Thompson was considered vulnerable as he squared off for a
rematch against Stevenson in 1986.
   Stevenson's chances suffered a fatal blow on primary day when a
follower of political extremist Lyndon LaRouche won nomination as
lieutenant governor. Stevenson resigned as the Democratic nominee
for governor and ran at the head of an independent slate. The
confusion effectively doomed his chances to mount another strong
challenge to Thompson.
   But even with the chaos on the Democratic side, Thompson was
re-elected by fewer than 400,000 votes out of 3.1 million.
   The 6-foot-6 Thompson served four years as U.S. attorney in the
early 1970s and earned a reputation as a crusader against corruption
and as a man intolerant of even the appearance of impropriety by
government officials.
   It was with that reputation that he swept into office in 1976 for
a two-year term. In 1978, he easily won re-election for the first
four-year term.
   A native of Chicago, Thompson is a graduate of Northwestern
University Law School. His wife Jayne also is a lawyer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Gurkhas     06-06 0126</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Gurkhas,0129</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ten Dead in Separatist Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 10 people have died in two days
of Gurkha separatist violence in the Darjeeling district of West
Bengal state, the Press Trust of India reported Monday.
   Darjeeling, a region in the Himalayas known for tourism and tea,
is about 185 miles north of Calcutta.
   The violence has been blamed on the Gurkha National Liberation
Front, which has been agitating for an independent state since April
1986.
   Gurkhas, who are Indians of Nepalese descent, say they are
ignored by the leftist government that controls West Bengal state
and that the federal government has not provided adequate education
and development aid.
   More than 275 deaths have been reported since the Gurkha
insurgency began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
