<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-US     06-06 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Medical Team Goes To Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-member U.S. team left Bangkok for
Hanoi on Monday for a four-day visit to discuss humanitarian
concerns with officials there, an American official said.
   Ross Petzing, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, said the
team included orthopedic specialist Dr. Bruce E. Van Damm of the
U.S. Army's Walter Reed Medical Center; Perry W. Stafford of
Bethesda Naval Hospital; Neil A. Holtzman of Johns Hopkins
University and Laurence Kerr, the Vietnam desk officer from the U.S.
State Department.
   The team returns to Bangkok on Thursday.
   Since last August, the U.S. government has dispatched medical
teams to Vietnam on four occasions to explore the needs of disabled
war veterans and others. Vietnam in turn pledged to speed up efforts
to account for Americans missing in the Vietnam War.
   Two American surgeons visited the communist nation from March
22-April 1 as part of an agreement between Hanoi's Maxillo-Facial
Institute and the private U.S. Committee for Scientific and
Technical Cooperation with Vietnam.
   The U.S. government has provided no direct humanitarian aid to
Vietnam but has allowed a private shipment of prosthetic devices.
The two countries have no diplomatic relations but over the past
year, the visits by U.S. officials have increased substantially.
</TEXT>
