<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1648EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MuseumExcavation     06-06 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Museum Excavation,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excavation Halted At Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $58 million construction project at the
Franklin Institute and Science Museum has been halted until
archaeologists can see if the excavation site holds any historical
artifacts, officials said Monday.
   Excavation was halted Sunday after cultural officials and
archaeologists criticized the Franklin Institute for not conducting
an archaeological survey before construction began.
   ``We'll try to get people over as soon as we can,'' said Donald
A. Cooke, the institute's vice president for marketing, fund-raising
and communication.
   Crews had been digging a block-long 12-foot-deep hole for a $58
million addition to the institute that will house a future's center,
which will look at science and technology that is shaping the 21st
century, said Cooke.
   Cooke said he didn't know how the excavation halt would affect
construction deadlines or how much money it would cost the museum.
``It certainly will cost us a little bit of time and a little bit of
money,'' he said. ``We think it's worth doing.''
   The excavation is in a small portion of a five-block area that
was once was the site of the Magdalen Society, a Quaker society for
reforming prostitutes that operated for more than 100 years.
   Cooke said excavation in the last 10 to 30 years by the institute
could have possibly already destroyed historical material. Among
other things, deep supports were built for a Boeing 707 it had on
display.
   However, John L. Cotter, formerly the chief archaeologist for the
National Park Service's eastern region, disagreed.
   ``Heavens, you can have all sorts of pillars and destroy half the
site, but the point is that you still have the areas where there are
no pillars and you have the other half of the site,'' Cotter said.
   Although the museum received $10 million in state money, state
officials said the usual requirement for an archaeological review
did not apply because the money was granted directly from the
Legislature, instead of through a state agency.
   Cooke said no one requested an archaeological review.
   Cooke said museum officials intend to meet with the Philadelphia
Historical Commission on Wednesday and hope to develop a plan to
review the site.
</TEXT>
