<DOCNO> AP880606-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1627EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0631 06-06 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0631,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Judge Says Conspiracy Charges Are Major Obstacle</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 14th graf pvs, bgng: At Monday's, with 5 grafs to UPDATE
with later developments from hearing. Picks up 15th graf pvs, `The
potential</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra case said Monday
the danger of exposing the nation's most sensitive secrets posed a
serious obstacle to pressing the conspiracy charges against Oliver
L. North and three co-defendants.
   This was the second time in the past two weeks that U.S. District
Judge Gerhard A. Gesell warned that unprecedented legal problems in
the case could curtail the rights of defendants to defend themselves
against the conspiracy charges.
   ``What's causing the trouble here is the conspiracy counts,
because they related to a wide course of conduct,'' Gesell told a
hearing in which the defense said the classified information
problems were insurmountable.
   Gesell, who did not decide whether to retain the conspiracy
charges, which allege the defendants defrauded the government, said
nonetheless that the exposure problem could inhibit defendants'
ability to show that they acted no differently than in other covert
operations.
   ``When a man is accused, he ought to be able to get on the stand
and tell his side of the story, if he wants to,'' the judge said.
   But that right could be restricted, Gesell said, if a defendant
wants to point to other secret operations and say, ``I've been doing
these things time and time again in other covert operations with the
approval of Cabinet officials.''
   The judge suggested that the prosecution might be better off
tying counts other than conspiracy, such as obstruction of Congress,
making false statements to Congress, obstruction of a presidential
inquiry, falsifying documents, conspiracy to pay illegal gratuities
and obstruction of justice.
   On another issue, Gesell rejected a defense pre-trial request for
top-secret documents. On Friday, the CIA's top lawyer filed a
statement contending that some of the documents are so sensitive,
that only President Reagan, the director of central intelligence and
his deputy are allowed to see them.
   On May 26, Gesell said a trial on the conspiracy charges could be
impossible because defendants might not have the usual trial
privilege of confronting each other on prior statements.
   Such questioning might be curtailed because three of the four
defendants testified before Congress under a grant of limited
immunity from prosecution _ testimony that the prosecution can't
use, and that might also be inadmissible under the defense case.
   The judge and lawyers for both sides agree that no prior case had
to deal with such extensive immunized testimony or up to 200,000
pages of classified documents.
   A federal grand jury last March handed down a 23-count indictment
against North, a former National Security Council staffer; his
onetime boss, former National Security Adviser John M. Poindexter;
and two businessmen, retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord
and Albert Hakim.
   The first count charges all four defendants with conspiracy to
defraud the government by using profits from a presidentially
approved sale of arms to Iran for personal gain, and to aid the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels when such assistance was banned by law.
   Gesell revealed at Monday's hearing that Secord, before he gave
congressional testimony, provided prosecutors with leads in the
case. Secord ended up meeting with the prosecution staff nearly a
dozen times before his indictment, Gesell said.
   The judge said he was surprised that none of the lawyers had
mentioned that Secord had helped the prosecution _ a fact Gesell
said he learned from a footnote in a legal brief.
   Secord's lawyer, Thomas Green, said the retired general acted out
of a ``sense of obligation and duty,'' and believed ``if he were to
tell the truth,'' prosecutors and members of Congress would
``ultimately agree'' he did nothing wrong.
   Gesell denied motions by Secord and Hakim to dismiss the
indictments against them. Both defendants charged that the
prosecution refused to allow the grand jury to hear North's and
Poindexter's immunized testimony _ which Secord and Hakim contended
would have proved that the money raised from the Iran arms sales
belonged to their business enterprise, not the government.
   North lawyer Barry Simon told Gesell the trial would have to stop
every time a witness was about to refer to classified information so
the court could decide how to proceed.
   ``The potential is absolutely endless,'' Simon said.
   But independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh argued, ``The
defendants are greatly exaggerating the problem,'' and called the
conspiracy count ``really vital as a unifying function in the
indictment.''
   He said much of the difficulty would be solved by substituting
letters and numbers for specific countries and individuals, a system
used at the congressional Iran-Contra hearings.
   Gesell said the prolem was broader, because of the potential need
to describe other covert operations.
   Testimony about these operations could be prohibited under the
Classified Information Procedures Act if U.S. intelligence agencies
were unwilling to expose the information in court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
