<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DredgeSpill     06-06 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dredge Spill,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Damage To Wildlife Reported From Dredge's Fuel Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leak of diesel fuel from a dredge
that sank in the St. Marys River channel slowed Monday, the Coast
Guard said, and no damage to wildlife had been reported.
   The Coast Guard was still working to reopen the channel to ships,
including Navy submarines based at nearby St. Marys, Ga. The dredge
sank in high wind and heavy seas Saturday.
   A bird expert said the leaking fuel threatened nearby marshes and
wetlands, including the Cumberland Island National Seashore. The
area has nesting sites of many species, some of which are now
raising their young.
   However, Coast Guard Cmdr. Henry Rohrs, executive officer of the
Marine Safety Office, said it appeared the fuel was not threatening
the sensitive areas.
   ``Less diesel is coming out than during the last few days,''
Rohrs said. ``It appears to be evaporating and blowing away. We did
a beach survey and found nothing, no pocketing of oil on the water
or sand, just a sheen.''
   Rohrs said the rate of leakage from the dredge Crest, which was
carrying 40,000 gallons of diesel fuel, had fallen from 500 gallons
an hour earlier to an estimated 100 gallons.
   Cindy Mosling, founder and director of Bird Emergency and Kare
Sanctuary, known as BEAKS, said she hasn't heard of any bird
injuries caused by the diesel fuel.
   But, she said, ``We have nesting birds in the marshes and this
could be very destructive. There are nesting colonies in very
critical areas. They use that whole area to dive and hunt for food.''
   Coast Guard officials said they wanted to set up a temporary
one-way-at-a-time boat channel around the dredge while divers
attempt to plug the leak.
   ``We are hoping to get private divers down there to plug the
vents, but the weather has not allowed them to do that,'' Rohrs
said. ``It's been too rough.''
   The closing of the channel has had ``no effect on commercial
traffic, since none was due in until (Tuesday),'' Rohrs said. ``Of
course, the Navy is very concerned.''
   Rohrs said officials were still investigating the sinking.
Because the dredge company took full responsibility for the cleanup,
the Coast Guard was only monitoring the situation and had not had to
spend any federal funds on removing oil, Rohrs said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
