<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FerryRefloating     06-06 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ferry Refloating,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic Ferry to be Refloated off Ellis Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Work begins Tuesday on refloating the ferry Ellis
Island, which carried 12 million immigrants to Manhattan and New
Jersey but now is a hazard.
   ``Our principal concern is that the structure is a navigational
hazard and we have to move it because of that,'' Edie Shean-Hammond,
a spokeswoman for the National Park Service, said Monday from her
office in Boston.
   Although the vessel has been a hazard since it sank in 1968, the
Park Service is opening a museum on Ellis Island next year and the
channel must be dredged for newer ferries, Mrs. Shean-Hammond said.
   The ferry, sitting in New York Harbor, also has historical
significance. Once raised, it will be taken to another part of the
island and studied, Mrs. Shean-Hammond said.
   ``It was the ride to freedom for them. It was their hope for the
future for them,'' she said.
   When the project was proposed, private contractors bidding for
the salvage offered costly estimates for what they said might be an
impossible job _ raising the vessel in one piece. But the U.S. Navy
is going to do the job free.
   On Tuesday, a Naval Reserve unit from Chicago will arrive and
begin setting up for an initial dive Wednesday. The divers will work
through June 16 removing silt and patching a few small holes in the
hull. Other reserve units will work through the summer.
   The double-decked ferry began service in 1904 for what was then
the Bureau of Immigration. The 160-foot long vessel could carry
1,000 immigrants in its hold and about 25 officials and New York
visitors on the top. It was outfitted with a 12-bed hospital.
   It made its last run in 1954 and was docked at Ellis Island until
it sank on Aug. 11, 1968, after years of sitting in the water
without attention.
</TEXT>
