<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PhoneSubscribership     06-06 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phone Subscribership,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assistance Program Signs Up Almost 14,000 New Phone Subscribers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assistance program designed to bring
telephone service to poor Americans signed up nearly 14,000 new
subscribers in four target areas in the first six months of the
program, though a government report shows phone subscribership in
three of those areas declined overall.
   The program, called ``Link Up America,'' is a combined initiative
of state and federal regulators, consumer groups and telephone
companies to bring phone service to the 5 million Americans who
don't have it.
   Since it was started last October, 30 states and the District of
Columbia have developed programs certified by the Federal
Communications Commission. Residents of those states become eligible
for benefits that include payment of up to half of their phone
installation and connection charges, up to $30.
   The District of Columbia and three states _ Arkansas, Texas and
West Virginia _ were selected as target states to be monitored
closely for six months so the FCC could assess the effectiveness of
various marketing strategies that could be used in other areas.
   Link Up America officials say the program signed up 5,358 new
subscribers in Arkansas, 455 in the District of Columbia, 5,153 in
Texas and 3,029 in West Virginia.
   A Census Bureau survey for the FCC shows that subscribership
declined from March 1987 to March 1988 in Arkansas, from 87 percent
to 83.6 percent of the population; in Texas, from 90.4 percent to
87.8 percent; and in West Virginia, from 88.7 percent to 87.9
percent. In Washington, D.C., subscribership rose from 91.2 percent
to 93.3 percent.
   FCC spokesman John Kamp said economic conditions in the three
states probably accounted for the overall decline in subscribership.
   ``These three states are economically in bad shape. That even
with this program the penetration would go down is not too
surprising to us,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1913EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TACAJet     06-06 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TACA Jet,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jet, Stranded Two Weeks, Finally Takes Off From Emergency Strip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUSTIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Central American airlines jet took off from
a World War II auxiliary landing strip Monday and completed the
final 12 miles of a trip cut short two weeks ago by engine failure
and an emergency landing in a thunderstorm.
   The Boeing 737 landed successfully without power May 24, without
injuries to the 41 people aboard.
   Monday's takeoff was normal ``in all respects,'' said Warren V.
Wandel, a safety inspector for the National Transportation Safety
Board.
   Actually, the fast, steep ascent would have been a bit
uncomfortable for passengers, had there been any aboard.
   The two Boeing test pilots who flew the plane from its emergency
landing strip to New Orleans International Airport practically stood
the plane on its tail, made a 15-degree turn to the right and
climbed quickly into low clouds lingering from two days of rain.
   The plane landed safely at New Orleans International about 15
minutes later.
   The narrow World War II airstrip is now used as a road from a
fuel tank assembly plant to a harbor on the Intracoastal Waterway, a
straight-line shortcut from the Gulf of Mexico to the port at New
Orleans.
   The May 24 emergency landing was made on a grassy strip parallel
to the road.
   The plane had lost power in both engines, and the right one,
which showed some damage from overheating, was replaced for takeoff.
Wandel said the left engine would be removed at New Orleans
International, and both engines would be taken apart next week and
inspected.
   Of all the possible causes of the loss of power, only fuel
contamination has been ruled out, Wandel said. It will be several
months before the NTSB announces its findings, he said.
   Getting approval to remove the plane from the insurers and all
the federal, state and local agencies involved was cumbersome. There
were discussions of taking the plane apart and trucking the pieces
away as well as putting it aboard a barge and floating it to an
airport.
   It is owned by TACA, a Central American airline based in El
Salvador with offices in New Orleans.
</TEXT>
