<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MortgageDelinquencies     06-06 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mortgage Delinquencies,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Late Payments on Mortgages Drop To Second Lowest Level of Decade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another sign of improving economic
conditions, the number of Americans late on their mortgage payments
fell to the second lowest level of this decade during the first
three months of the year, a trade group of lenders reported Monday.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association said the number of mortgage
payments late by 30 days or more dropped to 4.78 percent of total
mortgages in the first quarter, down from 4.95 percent in the last
three months of 1987.
   This was the second lowest late-payment level since 1979,
bettered only by a 4.71 percent deliquency rate in the third quarter
of 1987.
   The rate of foreclosures remained unchanged in the first quarter
at 0.27 percent of all mortgages, up slightly from the rate a year
ago.
   Warren Lasko, executive vice president of the association, said
``foreclosures remain a problem, especially in economically
depressed regions of the country.'' But he said the steady drop in
late payments should translate into lower foreclosures in quarters
ahead.
   All four regions of the country experienced lower late-payment
levels in the first quarter when compared with the same period a
year ago, when the overall late-payment rate was 5.17 percent.
   The largest decline was in the Northeast, where late payments
fell from 4.44 percent a year ago to 3.81 percent in the
January-March quarter, the lowest level of any region.
   The South, which has been hard hit by troubles in energy
producing states, saw the level of late payments fall from 5.72
percent down to 5.27 percent in the January-March quarter.
   The Midwest had a drop from 5.22 percent to 4.85 percent, while
the level of late payments in the West fell from 4.51 percent down
to 4.17 percent in the first quarter.
</TEXT>
