<HEAD>Four Senate Seats, One Governoship on Ballots</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS four to seven the number of local slow-growth issues,
in 4th graf bgng ``Locally, Sacramento''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Slow Growth, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Four New Mexico Republicans compete for a chance to challenge
Democratic Sen. Jeff Bingaman and former Montana Gov. Thomas Judge
puts his comeback hopes on the line Tuesday, as seven states hold
primaries for state and local office.
   Senate races also are on tap in California, New Jersey and
Montana, while voters in Actims, and proposals to ease state spending limits
and curb
campaign spending.
   Locally, Sacramento voters could decide to close the Rancho Seco
nuclear power plant; San Bernardino County voters could split the
nation's largest county into two; and voters in seven Southern
California communities could impose limits on growth or force
developers to pay for it.
   San Diego Mayor Maureen O'Connor, who won a special election two
years ago after Roger Hedgecock was convicted of a felony, is
seeking a full four-year term. She is expected to win a majority in
the non-partisan primary and thus avoid a runoff.
   In New Jersey, Democratic Rep. Peter Rodino is giving up his seat
after 20 terms amid growing sentiment that his Newark-area district
should be represented by the state's first black congressman. Two
black Newark city councilmen, Donald Payne and Ralph Grant, are
competing in the Democratic primary, with the winner expected to
defeat the GOP nominee, political newcomer Michael Webb, who also is
black.
   In New Mexico's GOP Senate race, state Sen. Bill Valentine led
the four-candidate field in a poll taken last week for the
Albuquerque Journal. The national Republican Party has targeted
Bingaman as vulnerable because he is a first-term liberal Democrat.
Bingaman has no primary opposition.
   The GOP also has designs on another first-term Democratic
senator, Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey, who faces two little-known
candidates in Tuesday's primary. The only Republican contender is
Peter Dawkins, a former star athlete, Rhodes scholar and Vietnam War
hero who moved to New Jersey last year from New York to run for
office.
   A third Democratic senator seeking re-election is John Melcher of
Montana. To win a third term he must overcome attorney Robert
Kelleher in the primary and Republican Conrad Burns, a Yellowstone
County commissioner, in November.
   California's GOP Sen. Pete Wilson has no primary opponent, and
will likely face Democratic Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy, who is running
against three political unknowns. Wilson has led in the polls, but
no one has been re-elected to his Senate seat for 30 years.
   In Montana's race for governor, Judge is one of six Democrats
seeking the nomination for the seat two-term Gov. Ted Schwinden is
relinquishing. Schwinden had defeated Judge in the 1980 Democratic
primary.
   A Montana Poll taken last week showed Judge was the choice of 28
percent of Democratic voters, but 35 percent were undecided.
   In the two-way Republican race, the poll showed a dead heat
between former state Sen. Stan Stephens and state Rep. Cal Winslow.
Republicans have not won the governorship in 20 years and the GOP
favorite, Secretary of State Jim Waltermire, was killed in a plane
crash in April.
</TEXT>
