<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1920EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Election     06-06 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Election,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abstentions, Withdrawals Important Second-Round Factors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key to any conservative success in this week's
runoff for the National Assembly is in the extreme-right National
Front after a surprisingly strong showing by the rightists in round
No. 1.
   After President Francois Mitterrand's re-election last month with
a hefty 54 percent of the vote, the polls, analysts and most
politicians expected a Socialist tidal wave in Sunday's voting for
the 577-seat National Assembly.
   But the right and center-right parties ran even with the
Socialists in popular vote.
   As the support is distributed, however, the Socialists have an
edge to win a majority of seats.
   But a foregone conclusion suddenly became a horse race, and on
Monday, the most sought after people in France were the 34.5 percent
of voters who didn't cast ballots Sunday.
   Some analysts said the voters indicated they wanted a balance of
power between the right and left, such as the ``cohabitation'' that
existed between the Socialist Mitterrand and the conservatives who
won control of the National Assembly in the 1986 elections.
   Two important factors affect the June 12 runoff. One is how many
of the registered voters who didn't go to the polls Sunday can be
persuaded to vote.
   Turnout in the first round was the lowest for any election in
post-war France.
   ``The level of abstentions has created suspense for the second
round and unexpectedly invigorated the campaign,'' wrote the leftist
daily Liberation. ``This will not exactly be the pleasure cruise
predicted by the polls.''
   The other factor is strategic withdrawal.
   In districts where no candidate won a majority, all those with
12.5 percent or more were eligible for the runoff which, depending
on the constituency, could involve several candidates.
   In the past, to set up a direct right-left confrontation, the
Communists and Socialists have agreed to back the best-placed
leftist candidate. The traditional rightist parties did the same.
   This time, while the Socialists and Communists will implement the
withdrawal strategy, the question remains about what the National
Front will do.
   The conservative Rally for the Republic and center-right Union
for French Democracy fielded a single candidate in each district. In
districts where the National Front candidate qualified for the
runoff along with the joint RPR-UDF candidate, he could split the
rightist vote and effectively elect a Socialist or Communist.
   National Front leader Jean-Marie Le Pen said he was ready to help
defeat the Socialists by withdrawing his candidates in favor of
leading RPR-UDF candidates, but only if the RPR and UDF did the same
in constituencies where National Front candidates were leading.
   Alain Juppe, former spokesman for the outgoing conservative
government, said the RPR-UDF coalition maintained its refusal to
deal with the National Front but would appeal directly to its voters
to help defeat the left.
   Strategy meetings were going on at major party headquarters all
over Paris on Monday.
   ``The French must confirm their will not to confide all power in
our country to a single party and, you and me, we must work toward
that this week,'' said former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing.
   Interior Minister Pierre Joxe said it was ``reasonable to think
that (Socialist Premier) Michel Rocard's government may be able to
count on a parliamentary majority.''
   In popular vote, the RPR-UDF candidates won 37.67 percent of the
vote, while the Socialists and their allies won 37.55. The
Communists scored 11.32 percent and the National Front 9.65 percent.
The rest went to minor parties.
   In actual seats, the RPR-UDF candidates won 76 seats in the first
round, the Socialists 40, minor rightists three, the Communists one
and the National Front none. But the Socialists were in better
position to win a majority of the 455 seats being decided in the
runoff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
