<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChildForSale     06-06 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child For Sale,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Guilty In Sale Of Daughter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose attempt to sell his young
daughter for $100,000 in a Giants Stadium parking lot sparked a
three-way custody battle pleaded guilty Monday to endangering the
child's welfare.
   Joseph Waltman, 24, of Alloway Township, faces a maximum of five
years in prison and a $75,000 fine after entering into a plea
agreement with prosecutors. He is to be sentenced July 13.
   ``I took the law into my own hands,'' Waltman said. He would not
comment about how he felt about his daughter or the family who won
custody.
   In exchange for his plea, charges of conspiracy and illegally
placing a child for adoption were dropped.
   The attempted sale of Waltman's daughter, Rachel Rauser, was
followed by a bitter custody dispute. The child, 5, now lives with
an uncle in Florida.
   Waltman was arrested March 19, 1987, in the parking lot at Giants
Stadium in East Rutherford on charges he tried to sell the girl to
her uncle, Gary Stern. Stern was cooperating with authorities and
undercover agents had been watching.
   A three-way dispute followed with Stern and his wife, Deborah,
the child's grandparents, and Waltman's estranged wife, Cynthia
Sullivan-Waltman, all wanting custody.
   Rachel's mother, Michal Rauser, had died in a fiery car accident
in 1984, and a judge awarded the girl a $3 million settlement. She
will receive a lump-sum payment when she reaches 18 and monthly
payments of $1,500 for life.
   The custody battle ended in December when the Sterns, of Sunrise,
Fla., were granted custody of Rachel. The judge said the ruling was
based on expert mental health reports, but he did not elaborate on
his decision.
   ``It's been a long time coming,'' Stern said when told of
Monday's plea. ``I'm going to tell my wife and family, and for the
first time in a long time we can sleep easy knowing justice
prevailed. If you wait long enough, it always does.''
   Waltman agreed to the plea bargain for peace of mind, said his
attorney, James Patuto.
   ``He was at the end of his rope. He had four years of custody
fights. He was out of money, his marriage was breaking up,'' said
Patuto.
</TEXT>
