<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     06-06 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Ready to Clinch Nomination, Reaches Out to Jackson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, a day away from sewing up the
Democratic presidential nomination, reached out to fellow Democrat
Jesse Jackson and jabbed at Republican George Bush on Monday.
   Expecting to win the delegates needed to assure him the
nomination in Tuesday's last round of primaries, Dukakis spoke of
party unity and said he believed Jackson would campaign for him in
the fall.
   ``I know how strongly he feels about the importance of a Democrat
in the White House in January,'' Dukakis said as he campaigned
around California on the eve of its primary.
   Dukakis telephoned Jackson after arriving in Los Angeles late
Sunday night. Dukakis senior adviser Paul Brountas said the two
``just chatted _ both were very tired.'' The Massachusetts governor
also took a call from defeated Democratic rival Paul Simon.
   Dukakis spoke to students outside Taft High School in Woodland
Hills, a section of Los Angeles, and later told reporters he hoped
he and Jackson would meet soon.
   ``We try our best to get together from time to time,'' Dukakis
said. ``I don't know whether we'll be able to do that in these next
couple of days, but if we can, we will.''
   Dukakis lacks only about 200 of the 2,081 delegates needed to win
the nomination, and his aides were clearly confident he would secure
what was needed from the 466 delegates up for grabs on Tuesday, 314
of them in California. Also holding primaries are New Jersey, New
Mexico and Montana.
   Dukakis said he expected Jackson to work for the Democratic
ticket.
   ``If the tables were reversed and he was on his way to the
nomination and I was the runner-up, I'd expect to be deeply
involved. ... I'd try to bring my people into this. I'd be as much
service to the ticket as I possibly could,'' Dukakis said.
   ``I'm cnfident he will be that kind of person.''
   Dukakis and his aides hope he can declare he has gone over the
top in the delegate race Tuesday night or Wednesday morning, before
flying back to Massachusetts.
   After Los Angeles, he flew to San Diego on Monday, for another
campaign appearance, and was traveling to San Jose before returning
to Los Angeles. He planned a morning appearance Tuesday before
awaiting the primary results in his Century City hotel.
   ``This has been a great 15 months,'' he said. ``I'm excited about
what has happened, and I'm looking forward if all goes well to a
decisive victory here in California, in New Jersey, in Montana and
in New Mexico, so we can lock up this nomination.''
   Asked about his conversation with Jackson and about bringing his
Democratic rival into the fall effort, Dukakis said: ``The process
has already begun. We're talking. Our staffs have been talking.''
   ``We'll be reaching out to supporters of Jesse, and the other
Democratic candidates, as we have already. The response has been
terrific,'' he said. ``I'm really overwhelmed by the good feeling,
the spirit, the confidence. A sense of victory is in the air.''
   Dukakis jabbed at Bush about off-shore oil drilling, an issue in
California, and Bush's apparent change of position Sunday. The vice
president, who has supported off-shore drilling, said he favored
delaying the lease sale of a tract off the northern California coast.
   ``I'm pleased he's coming around, but it's kind of late,''
Dukakis said. ``I'm not for delaying that sale _ I'm for canceling
it.
   ``It's easy to say, `We'll delay it until after the election,'''
Dukakis said. ``What does that mean? What does that mean?''
   Dukakis said he opposes off-shore drilling in ``environmentally
sensitive'' areas but stopped short of saying there should be a
moratorium on all drilling off shore.
</TEXT>
