<2ND_LINE>AM-White House Finances,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Took $429,000 When He Left Law Firm To Work for Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howard H. Baker Jr., chief of staff at the
White House, received $429,817 last year when he terminated his
partnerships in two law firms to go to work for President Reagan, it
was disclosed Monday.
   White House counsel Arthur Culvahouse Jr., who was a partner with
Baker at the Houston-based Vinson & Elkins law firm, received
$206,349 in partnership profits and as a refund for money
contributed to a retirement plan.
   The settlements were disclosed in annual financial disclosure
reports submitted to the Office of Government Ethics.
   Baker took over the top staff job at the White House in February
1987, when Donald T. Regan was ousted from the job.
   In returning to government, Baker, a former senator from
Tennessee, had to return $83,333 in consulting fees that had been
prepaid by Merrill Lynch for his services throughout 1987, the
disclosure form said.
   As chief of staff, Baker earns $89,500.
   His report said Baker received $262,275 from Vinson & Elkins in
undistributed profits from a partnership arrangement begun in 1985
after he left the Senate. Likewise, he received $167,542 from the
Knoxville, Tenn., law firm of Baker, Worthington, Crossley,
Stansberry & Woolf.
   He got $8,500 in director's fees from AT&T and $12,000 from MCA
Inc.
   Kenneth A. Duberstein, who was brought in as deputy chief of
staff in March 1987, not long after Baker's arrival, reported
$291,440 in settlement salary and compensation from Timmons and Co.,
a business consulting firm where he had worked previously.
   Duberstein also received $18,000 for work he did for HTB Inc. of
Oklahoma City, an architectural consulting firm, although Duberstein
also terminated his contract with that firm when he came to the
White House.
</TEXT>
