<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 2344EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-NigeriaLoans     06-06 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Nigeria Loans,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bank Resumes Lending to Nigeria</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's Export-Import Bank said Monday
it was resuming lending to Nigeria, Africa's most populous country,
after it cleared up overdue payments on $388 million in outstanding
loans.
   Nigeria is a major exporter of oil to this country.
   The bank, which makes loans to encourage U.S. exports, will lend
Nigerian borrowers as much as $10 million on each export agreement.
Repayment must be completed in five years. Loans for larger projects
will be considered if the money goes to different borrowers.
   The bank has been unwilling to lend to Nigeria since 1985. The
change was made possible by new policies that the government of Gen.
Ibrahim Babangida has undertaken, the bank said. But the bank still
is unwilling to make long-term loans, which also were cut off in
1985.
   Nigeria is one of the Third World's largest debtors, with about
$27 billion outstanding, according to the World Bank. Like big
debtors in Latin America and unlike most African countries, Nigeria
owes most of its debt _ about 55 percent _ to commercial banks
rather than to governments.
   ``We applaud the government of Nigeria's efforts to regain
economic balance and endorse their continuing movement toward
economic reform,'' bank President John A. Bohn Jr. said in
announcing its new policy.
   He said it would continue to watch Nigeria's economic progress
and that the U.S. loans will help Nigeria buy the machines and
services it needs to restore growth.
   Nigeria has been hard hit by the drop in the price of oil, its
major export. The World Bank calculates that the income of the
average Nigerian _ there are more than 103 million of them _ dropped
to $640 in 1986, from $820 the year before.
   Bohn praised the Nigerian government's efforts to work with the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund. On their advice,
Nigeria recently increased domestic prices of gasoline and diesel
fuel in an effort to reduce its $1.5 billion budget deficit.
   The increase touched off a two-week strike that paralyzed medical
and banking services and brought on demonstrations in which at least
six people were killed. The strike ended last month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
