<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0646 06-06 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0646,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Takes Peace Campaign to Syria</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede, DAMASCUS</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with Shultz in Egypt; picks
up
5th pvs: `We will...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George P. Shultz carried his faltering
campaign for Arab-Israeli peace to Syria and told reporters Monday
the United States and Soviet Union will continue discussions on a
Middle East settlement.
   The U.S. secretary of state spent about four hours in Damascus,
half of it in meetings with President Hafez Assad, who has taken a
hard line on peace with Israel.
   He then came Egypt, where he toured ancient Luxor and scheduled a
meeting Tuesday with President Hosni Mubarak before ending his
fourth Middle East mission of the year.
   Shultz briefed Assad on last week's U.S.-Soviet summit in Moscow
and, after a discussion of an increase in international terrorism,
offered to share information with him about the problem, a senior
U.S official said Monday.
   Shultz then flew to Luxor, at the site of the ancient Nile-side
Egyptian capital Thebes, 420 miles south of Cairo, and toured the
tombs of the pharaohs.
   Dressed in a blue golf cap and a green sports shirt, he seemed
relaxed after 3{ days of tough diplomacy with the leaders of Israel,
Jordan and Syria.
   The tombs and the majestic temple column of Karnak, the national
shrine of ancient Egypt, are reached by crossing the Nile by ferry.
Egyptian frogmen and armed partol boats kept watch over the
secretary and his delegation.
   Shultz's meeting with Assad reflected continuing improvement in
U.S relations with a country the State Department still lists as a
supporter of terrorism.
   Speaking to Arab reporters afterward, he said the United States
and Soviet Union have ``agreed to continue to address ourselves to
the Middle East issues.
   ``We will have some continuing discussions, probably before long,
on an intensive basis,'' Shultz said. ``It's not for the Soviet
Union and the United States to resolve the problems here. It's for
the countries in the region to resolve their problems.''
   He added, however, that the superpowers ``have a certain amount
of influence, and if we see some things in a parallel way it will
probably make an impact.''
   Washington has dropped its opposition to a Soviet role in a
Middle East peace conference but objects to an active part for
outside powers in negotiations between Israel and its Arab foes.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel opposes any Soviet role
but plans to meet the Soviet foreign minister, Eduard A.
Shevardnadze, at the United Nations. It will be the latest of
several recent contacts between the two countries, which do not have
formal diplomatic relations.
   Shultz has been unable to bridge the gap between Israel and the
Arabs over the U.S. peace proposals, which include an international
conference and trading Israeli-occupied land for peace.
   King Hussein of Jordan said Saturday that Israeli withdrawal from
occupied territories is a condition for talks. Shamir opposes
condition and has balked at Shultz's insistence on at least a
partial Israeli pullback.
   In comments to the Arab reporters, Shultz said both sides could
work with his proposal ``if people will cast aside their extreme
views, their illusions, and operate on the basis of reality.''
   The secretary said he considers the Arab demand for an
independent Palestinian nation ``unworkable'' and suggested ``a
confederation, or an attachment to another state.'' He said it could
be similar to an American state or a Swiss canton.
   About Lebanon, Shultz said he believed it ``important that
(presidential) elections go ahead'' as planned even if there is no
solution to the country's constitutional crisis.
   U.S. officials have welcomed Syria's military role in Lebanon's
Moslem areas and have worked with Syria in trying to win Christian
political concessions that might help calm the 13-year-old sectarian
civil war.
   There has been no sign, however, that the Lebanese Forces, the
main Christian militia, will accept any plan ending Christian
political dominance in a country that now has a Moslem majority.
</TEXT>
