<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Delegates     06-06 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Delegates,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Backers Threaten Convention Fight Over Delegates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some supporters of Jesse Jackson complained
Monday that the Democratic presidential contender will be denied his
fair share of delegates in New Jersey's primary election on Tuesday.
   ``We're fighting for, essentially, a moral principle,'' said
Frank Watkins, Jackson's national political director.
   Newark Mayor Sharpe James, Jackson's state campaign chairman,
said New Jersey's ``winner-take-all'' delegate apportionment will
leave Jackson with fewer delegates than he deserves.
   James and some others in the Jackson camp demanded that
Democratic party leaders give Jackson a large portion _ perhaps all
_ of the ``at-large'' New Jersey delegates. Those delegates are
expected to go mainly to Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis.
   James accused party leaders _ including Sen. Bill Bradley, a
Dukakis backer _ of refusing to return telephone calls to discuss
the dispute.
   The Jackson backers said if the matter isn't settled by Tuesday,
they would take their complaints to the party's national convention
next month in Atlanta.
   ``We're calling for fairness. We are prepared to go all the way
to Atlanta with this fight,'' said James.
   Under state party rules, voters will elect 71 pledged delegates
Tuesday from 20 specially created delegate districts. Then, party
leaders will meet June 26 to pick an additional 38 at-large
delegates, pledged in proportion to the elected delegates. The state
has nine ``super delegates,'' who are state members of the
Democratic National Committee.
   Jackson backers claim the delegate districts have been drawn
unfairly, diluting urban populations _ where Jackson is strong _
with suburbs, where he is weaker.
   The Jackson supporters also criticized the winner-take-all
system, whereby candidates will win all of district's delegates if
they win anything above 50 percent of the votes cast.
   James said Jackson could get 49 percent of the votes cast, and
yet end up with only a handful of delegates. He called the process
``unfair, constitutional.''
</TEXT>
