<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st item to correct allowable time for suing in
Pennsylvania rule</NOTE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Actions At A Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of Supreme
Court actions on Monday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PATERNITY SUITS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The high court unanimously struck down a former Pennsylvania
rule allowing mothers of illegitimate children a maximum of six
years to sue alleged fathers for child support. The court said such
a deadline was a violation of the Constitution's equal protection
clause because legitimate children may sue for parental support at
any time. The case is Clark vs. Jeter, 87-5565.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>STATE REFERENDA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The justices ruled unanimously that states permitting ballot
initiatives may not prohibit groups from paying those who gather the
petition signatures necessary to get a referendum on the ballot.
Such a ban in Colorado unconstitutionally limits the size of the
audience that referenda supporters can reach, the court said. The
case is Meyer vs. Grant, 87-920.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DRUG TESTING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The court agreed to decide whether railroads may require all
employees involved in serious accidents to submit to drug testing.
The court will review an appeals court decision that struck down as
an unconstitution invasion of privacy the federal regulations
requiring mandatory testing of railroad employees. The case is
Bunley vs. Railway Labor Executives Association, 87-1555.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRIVOLOUS SUITS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The high court ruled that the rights of convicted criminals are
not violated by requiring their court-appointed lawyers to state the
reasons they believe an appeal would be frivolous. By a 5-3 vote,
the justices thus upheld a Wisconsin rule that such lawyers must
explain why they want to withdraw from representing an indigent
defendant because they believe an appeal lacks merit. The case is
McCoy vs. Court of Appeals, 87-5002.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RAPE CASE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The high court let stand the rape conviction of an Illinois man
who wanted a judge to examine privately the conversations his victim
had with rape crisis counselors. Over two dissenting votes, it
refused to hear arguments that a state law granting absolute
confidentiality to statements made during rape crisis counseling
violated a rape defendant's rights. The case is Foggy vs. Illinois,
87-6763.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WORKERS' RIGHTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The justices ruled unanimously in an Illinois case that states
may give protection to workers beyond that provided by federal labor
law so long as it doesn't force courts to interpret collective
bargaining agreements. The case is Lingle vs. Norge, 87-259.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEATH PENALTY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _By a 5-4 vote, the court set aside the death sentence of a
convicted Maryland murderer on the ground it could not be sure he
received a fair sentence. It also ruled unanimously that a convicted
Oklahoma killer was wrongly sentenced to death based on an
unconstitutionally vague ground that he committed an ``especially
heinous, atrocious or cruel'' crime. The cases are Mills vs.
Maryland, 87-5367, and Maynard vs. Cartwright, 87-519.
</TEXT>
