<DOCNO> AP880606-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 2043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama     06-06 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Urges Latin Mediation In Panama Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders on Monday called on
Latin American leaders to mediate efforts to push Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega from power.
   Little indication emerged here, however, that Noriega is willing
to permit any kind of mediation that would ease him out of his
control of the military and government. He has survived internal
protests as well as substantial U.S. pressure.
   Opposition leaders told Morton Abramowitz, the deputy U.S.
secretary of state who met with them during the weekend, that they
favor mediation by ``current, not past, Latin American presidents.''
   Former presidents Carlos Andres Perez of Venezuela and Daniel
Oduber of Costa Rica met last week with Panamana's acting chief
executive, Manuel Solis Palma, but the government-controlled news
media said they discussed only ``the illegal sanctions against
Panama.''
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, head of the Christian Democratic Party,
said opposition leaders would like to see Latin American mediation
because ``it would change the focus of the negotiations from a
confrontation between Noriega and the U.S. government to the real
problem, which is the confrontation between Noriega and the
Panamanian people.''
   ``We would go along with this,'' said Alfredo Ramirez of the
Nationalist Republican Liberal Movement. ``If the mediation is done
by presidents now in office.''
   As chief of the 15,000-member Defense Forces, Noriega is de facto
leader of the country. He was indicted in Florida in February on
U.S. drug trafficking charges. Noriega denies the charges and has
resisted U.S. pressure aimed at making him give up power.
   Arias said Monday his party would welcome the efforts of
countries such as Guatemala, Venezuela, Costa Rica and Argentina to
try to resolve the impasse.
   ``The United States ran out of options _ other than military
intervention,'' said a leader of another political party, who
insisted on anonymity. ``Now they want to try something different.''
   The Reagan administration tried economic sanctions against
Panama, pressure on Noriega and then direct negotiations. It offered
to drop the drug indictments issued in Florida to induce the general
to leave, but Noriega has survived all pressure, aided by a core of
military and political loyalists.
   Arias said Abramowitz ``had absolutely nothing new to offer'' on
his mission here. ``He said he came to evaluate the situation
following the failure of the U.S. negotiations with Noriega,'' he
reported.
   Arias said the opposition here insists that any mediation must
lead to Noriega's departure, establishment of a new civil government
and submission of the military to civilian rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
