<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hutton-Libel     06-06 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hutton-Libel,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Hutton Manager Says He Was Not Authorized To Make Large
Overdrafts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman cited for alleged wrongdoing in
former Attorney General Griffin B. Bell's 1985 report about the E.F.
Hutton check kiting scheme conceded Monday he never was authorized
to make large overdrafts.
   John M. Pearce, who formerly managed two Hutton branches,
testified that he was routinely exhorted by his superiors at Hutton
to make more money on bank interest.
   Writing checks against non-existent funds was a device encouraged
by Hutton to maximize interest profits, Pearce testified at the U.S.
District Court trial of his lawsuit against Bell.
   Bell was hired by Hutton to conduct an internal investigation
after the company pleaded guilty to 2,000 mail and wire fraud
charges in 1985.
   ``That was the firm's policy,'' Pearce said. ``I think so long as
the banks weren't injured, it was a legitimate way to do business.''
   Pearce contends he and five other branch managers were wrongly
singled out for criticism in the report that Bell issued following
his three-month investigation.
   But under questioning by Bell's attorney, Earl J. Silbert, Pearce
conceded he never received written instructions to exceed the normal
overdrafting outlined in the Hutton ``drawn-down sheet'' _ a
procedure Bell concluded was not illegal.
   ``In retrospect, I should have been considerably more suspicious
of being told of things that were not followed up in writing. I
fault myself for that,'' Pearce said.
   Pearce also acknowledged he didn't follow the company's
guidelines when calculating how much money would be overdrawn from
branch accounts.
   ``I don't know if they became totally irrelevant but they became
generally so,'' Pearce testified.
   Bell's report exonerated top Hutton officials of wrongdoing but
recommended sanctions against Pierce, five other branch managers and
three regional executives. Bell, a partner in the Atlanta law firm
of King & Spalding, charged that some top Hutton executives had
failed to properly monitor the operations of branch and regional
offices.
   Pearce contends that Bell, who was President Carter's first
attorney general, negligently ignored evidence that top Hutton
officials condoned the practice of making large overdrafts on
company accounts.
   Government investigators determined that the company gave itself
interest-free loans up to $250 million at a time by writing checks
that were not covered by funds in the accounts.
   Under the elaborate scheme, Hutton would reimburse an overdrawn
account with money from another branch before the overdrafted check
was cleared by the bank.
   In many instances, the reimbursement check was overdrawn against
a second account, which _ in turn _ was replenished with a check
from yet another Hutton account.
   ``This was something that went on in Woodies window as it were,''
Pearce said, referring to a Washington-area department store.
``There was no effort to conceal it.''
   While managing a branch in Bethesda, Md., withdrawals from the
office account were sometimes 10 times to 30 times larger than
deposits, Pearce said. The company's guidelines specified that
withdrawals should only exceed an account balance by 50 percent.
   Pearce testified that he never personally benefited from the
overdrafting.
   Pearce, who also managed Hutton's St. Louis branch, said he was
making $135,000 when he left the company. Last year he made $21,000
as president of a fire safety equipment company he owns in Sarasota,
Fla., Pearce said.
   When Bell published his findings, Pearce said: ``I was held up as
a criminal, I was finished as a manager in the securities business.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
