<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wet Weather In Southeast, West Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms were scattered over parts of the South on Monday
and along parts of the parched West Coast, and warm weather spread
over the Great Lakes.
   Rain and occasional thunderstorms extended from the Mississippi
Delta across Florida during the afternoon.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 1.17 inches of rain fell
at Tampa, Fla., and 1.77 inches fell at West Palm Beach, Fla.
   Showers also were scattered along the northern half of the
Pacific Coast and thunderstorms brought winterlike temperatures,
rain and hail to the San Francisco Bay area.
   ``We keep looking at the calendar and it says June, but it's
really more like January weather,'' said National Weather Service
spokeswoman Cris Smith in Redwood City, outside San Francisco.
   The storm system extended to the Sierra Nevada, where the snow
level dropped to 5,000 feet, she said.
   Farther inland, a freeze advisory was issued overnight for
northern and central Nevada.
   Warm air with morning temperatures in the 70s and 80s moved as
far north as the upper Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley,
the Dakotas and eastern Montana, which had three days of record heat
over the weekend.
   Record highs for the date Monday included 95 at Alpena, Mich.; 93
at Flint, Mich.; 93 at Green Bay, Wis.; and 96 at Williston, N.D.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 36 at
Truckee, Calif., to 98 at Williston, N.D. The low for the day was 22
at Truckee.
   For Tuesday, showers were forecast over the Florida Peninsula,
and from the northern two-thirds of the Pacific Coast across eastern
Washington, and along the New England coast.
   High in the 50s and 60s were predicted over New England and
interior New York state, and from the Idaho Panhandle across
northern Nevada, from the northern third of California across
Washigton, and along the southern coast of California; in the upper
80s and the 90s over the Virginias, the Carolinas, the Ohio Valley,
the Tennessee Valley, much of the Mississippi Valley, and the
Plains; near 100 across the desert Southwest and southwestern Texas;
and in the 70s and 80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
