<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ABCPoll     06-06 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ABC Poll,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Poll Puts Dukakis Ahead of Jackson by 2-1 in California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis has stretched his advantage
over Jesse Jackson in the California Democratic primary to a 2-1
margin, an ABC News tracking poll indicated Monday.
   The survey had Dukakis with 61 percent support among likely
voters in the Tuesday contest and Jackson with 30 percent. That
represented a slight gain for Dukakis and a slight drop in Jackson's
support during the weekend.
   The results were based on 415 telephone interviews Saturday and
Sunday. Dukakis' support had been 56 percent in two-day poll
averages since Wednesday and Thursday; Jackson went from 36 percent
to 34, 32, then to 30 percent.
   Four percent backed former candidate Sen. Albert Gore Jr. in the
latest poll, 4 percent picked someone else and 2 percent were
undecided. The poll had a margin of sampling error of about 6
percentage points.
   ``It seems very stable. Two-thirds of whites plan to vote
Dukakis; only 21 percent of whites are for Jackson,'' said Jeff
Alderman, polling director for ABC. ``Dukakis leads Jackson in all
demographic groups except blacks.''
   Even among blacks, Dukakis appeared to be doing better than in
earlier races. He was supported by nearly a quarter of blacks in the
Saturday-Sunday poll, up from 15 percent in the earlier ABC averages
and considerably better than his showing among blacks in earlier
primaries, Alderman said.
   Because of the imprecision in tracking polls, it was not clear
whether that finding would hold, Alderman said. He noted that
Jackson's supporters, as usual, supported him more strongly than
Dukakis voters backed their man.
   Latinos, a sizable voting group in California, supported Dukakis
in the poll over Jackson by a 3-2 margin, Alderman said.
</TEXT>
