<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RocketFuel     06-06 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rocket Fuel,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon, NASA Officials OK Plan To Restore Production Capacity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department and NASA have approved a
plan to restore and actually expand private industry's capacity to
produce an important rocket fuel ingredient, government sources said
Monday.
   The plan involves a series of guarantees for annual purchases and
the payment of capital construction ``surcharges'' to the Kerr-McGee
Corp. and the Pacific Engineering Products of Nevada for the solid
fuel ingredient ammonium perchlorate, said the officials, who agreed
to discuss the matter only if not identified.
   The plan is aimed at allowing Pacific Engineering to rebuild its
production plant, which was completely leveled by a massive
explosion on May 4, and at encouraging Kerr-McGee to expand the
capacity of its existing plant by up to 50 percent, said the
officials.
   Ultimately, the plan might even be expanded to entice one or more
other companies to enter the business, they said.
   The main points of the plan were approved last Friday by Robert
B. Costello, undersecretary of defense for acquisition, and by top
officials at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, the
sources said.
   It was discussed with top leaders on Capitol Hill on Monday.
   The Pacific Engineering plant in Henderson, Nev., represented
about 50 percent of the nation's production capacity for ammonium
perchlorate, a rocket fuel oxidizer that is essential not only for
NASA's space shuttle but also for a variety of military missiles,
including the MX and Minuteman missiles.
   Government officials warned last month that if the lost capacity
is not quickly restored, both the Pentagon and NASA could face
slowdowns in their space-launching schedules.
   The sources refused Monday to provide any estimates of how much
the plan would cost the government, saying the Pentagon probably
would have more to say on the matter later this week.
   The officials did say, however, the plan avoids any commitment of
taxpayer money ``up front,'' instead committing the government to
pay a special surcharge over a five-to-seven-year period on its
ammonium perchlorate purchases. The surcharge would allow the two
companies to quickly recover plant construction costs, the sources
said.
   The plan envisions Pacific Engineering essentially restoring all
of its lost capacity by building a new plant that could produce
about 40 million pounds per year, the sources said.
   Kerr McGee would expand its existing plant, which can produce
about 40 million pounds per year, to allow production of another 20
million pounds, the officials continued.
   The government also would provide the two companies with
guarantees that it would purchase a minimum of 20 million pounds
from each of them each year, the sources said.
   The combination of authorized surcharges and a purchase guarantee
is expected to make it extremely easy for both companies _ but
particularly Pacific Engineering _ to line up the financing needed
to quickly build new facilities.
   The sources said the purchase guarantees of 20 million pounds per
year from each company is actually somewhat less than what the
government has been buying in recent years. Thus the significance of
that part of the plan is simply that a formal commitment would be
made to reassure lending institutions, said one official.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
