<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LottoWinners 1stLd-Writethru a0677 06-06 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lotto Winners, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0677,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aircraft Mechanic, Supermarket Clerk Share Grand Prize</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from winners,
details. Picks up 6th graf pvs ``The odds...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two blue-collar workers, one of whom
could find no one to share his bet, were catapulted to fame and
wealth Monday when they split North America's largest lottery
jackpot, $51.4 million.
   Aircraft mechanic Shelby Carroll, 53, of Vacaville, and
Sacramento supermarket clerk Randy Pennington, 26, will each receive
$25.7 million over 20 years, lottery officials said.
   At a news conference, the Lotto 6-49 winners said they both used
a feature of the lottery terminals that randomly selects ticket
numbers for the player. They said they have few immediate plans
except to quit their jobs and help family members in various ways.
   Both also told a crowd of reporters and cheering lottery workers
that they would be ready for an onslaught of strangers interested in
their windfalls from the Saturday drawing.
   Carroll, a mechanic at Travis Air Force Base, said he was
unsuccessful in finding someone to match $50 with his $50, then
split any winnings from the $100 in bets.
   ``I asked my boss...if he would like to share with me. I said,
`Give me $50 and we'll split the winnings.' At the time, it (the
jackpot) was around $40 million. He says, `No.' I asked a couple
more of the guys, and they said, `No.'''
   So Carroll bet $100 himself because, he said, ``I had a feeling.''
   How does he feel now about not finding a partner? ``I'm glad. I
feel sorry for them. But I'm glad.''
   Pennington said that after buying his tickets, ``I found a
heads-up penny. Every time I've ever found a heads up penny,
somethings always happened good to me. I'm superstitious, I guess.''
   Asked if he had been hoping to get the whole jackpot himself,
Pennington told the crowd of about 100: ``Honest to God, I was
hoping that somebody else hit it, too, because I didn't want all
this by myself.''
   Pennington said that with the money, he would have more time to
indulge his hobby of collecting antique toys.
   Being single, he was asked if he had any trouble getting dates.
Replied Pennington, ``No. But who wants dates now. I don't.''
   The odds of picking all six numbers out of 49 were about one in
14 million, said lottery officials. The winning numbers were 48, 42,
9, 14, 19, 31. Tickets cost $1 each.
   The $51.4 million jackpot was revised downward from the original
estimate of nearly $52.24 million, after lottery officials completed
the final tally of ticket sales.
   Each grand prize winner will get $1,028,000 annually, after
taxes, for 20 years.
   The winners' award culminated several days of frenzied lotto
playing, during which the bettors purchased up to $4 million worth
of tickets an hour.
   Saturday's sales alone totaled more than $33 million, a one-day
record, spokesman Bob Taylor said. Weekly sales normally average
about $23 million, officials said.
   The late rush pumped millions of extra dollars into the grand
prize pot before sales were halted at 7:45 p.m. Saturday, 13 minutes
before the drawing.
   A $46 million jackpot in Pennsylvania was awarded in October and
was the previous record for a North American lottery payoff. The
biggest previous California jackpot, $25.4 million, was split by two
players in October.
</TEXT>
