<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0754,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Students Return to Classes, Vow to Continue Uprising</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs graf after 7th graf, ``In Hebron...'' to
UPDATE with more violence; picks up 8th pvs: ``Meanwhile,
Richard...; edits throughout to tighten</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Media, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army reopened high
schools Monday for 36,000 students in the occupied West Bank and
freed more than 100 Palestinian teen-agers from jail so they could
attend classes.
   Military officials said opening the schools signaled a waning of
the rebellion that began Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million Palestinians
in the occupied lands. Schools had been closed since February.
   But students said they would continue to demonstrate against the
Israeli occupation.
   ``It's good to be back in school because without being educated
we can't be liberated,'' said Ranna Bahu, 17, a senior at Friends
Girls School in the West Bank city of Ramallah. `We can continue
demonstrating after we take our classes, but education has to also
be a priority.''
   Also Monday, a 9-month-old girl, Fidah Sharafi, was hit in the
left eye by a rubber bullet during a protest at the Jabaliya refugee
camp, officials at Shifa Hospital in Gaza City said. Israel radio
said the girl lost sight in the eye.
   Army spokesmen said soldiers treated a 9-month-old girl who was
injured when soldiers fired rubber bullets to disperse protesters in
Jabaliya. Arab reports said Suad Sharaf, 17, was struck in the mouth
by a bullet.
   In Hebron in the West Bank, students burned tires and threw
stones at troops outside Hussein High School, an Arab reporter said.
Hospital officials said a youth was grazed by a bullet fired by
soldiers.
   In the nearby Dheisheh refugee camp, a 16-year-old boy was
wounded when troops pursued stone-throwers, Israel radio reported.
Army sources said he was wounded when a soldier fired accidentally.
   The radio also reported that two firebombs were thrown at an
Israeli bus in the Arab east Jerusalem. No injuries were reported
but the bus was damaged.
   Meanwhile, Richard Schifter, U.S. assistant secretary of state
for human rights, and U.S. ambassador Thomas Pickering toured the
occupied territories Monday.
   They spent two hours with army commanders in the Gaza Strip,
discussing the army rules on detention, curfews and use of live
ammunition and allegations of brutality against soldiers, Israel
radio reported.
   ``We had a very useful talk here and we will be continuing the
talks,'' Pickering said on the radio.
   Pickering and Schifter also visited military administration
headquarters in the West Bank and discussed human rights policy with
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
   Yitzhak Artzi, a legislator with the left-leaning Labor Party,
said Rabin told him some of the 2,061 Palestinians jailed for six
months without trial or charges could be released.
   An Israeli officer, Lt. Giora Even-Tzur, was jailed for allegedly
pelting rocks May 18 at three Arabs placed handcuffed into stone
pits outside the West Bank village of Arura, the daily Yediot
Ahronot reported.
   The army was also investigating allegations against an Israeli
brigade commander accused of shooting an Arab shepherd to death
during a helicopter chase near the West Bank village of Bani Naim,
the newspaper said.
   The complaint, brought by left-wing legislator Matti Peled, was
based on information from troops who witnessed the April 4 incident,
Yediot said.
   Also, the daily Haaretz quoted a military spokesman as saying the
army was experimenting with a new aluminum bullet to replace steel
bullets used to quell violent protests. The newspaper said the new
bullet is less likely to cause serious injuries.
   Since the Arab uprising began Dec. 8, 201 Palestinians have been
killed, most of them by Israeli army gunfire. Two Israelis have died.
   In the first two months of demonstrations, schools were a major
center of protest. West Bank schools were closed, and schools in the
Gaza Strip had operated on-and-off.
   The army cited a reduction in violence when it reopened grade
schools and junior high schools over the past two weeks and resumed
high school classes Monday.
   ``We are very happy today. We had approximately 90 percent
attendance, nearly everybody was in class,'' said Olivier Rafowicz,
spokesman for the West Bank military government. ``It proves
everybody wants to go back to normal life.''
   But students and teachers said returning to school did not mean
demonstrations would cease in the territories Israel captured in the
1967 Middle East war.
   ``We're going to keep studying and demonstrating, both,'' said
Ghanam Abdul Khader Taha, 15, of Ramallah High School.
   ``It's not the Israelis who are responsible for the students
being back in school. If the PLO hadn't sanctioned it, they would
not be here,'' said Olga Hawid, a 12th-grade French and Arabic
teacher at the school.
</TEXT>
