<2ND_LINE>AM-Zero Tolerance,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs Commissioner Appoints Ombudsman to Help Innocent Victims
of
Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs Commissioner William von Raab
announced Monday the appointment of an ombudsman to advise innocent
people who become entangled in its ``zero tolerance'' anti-drug
program.
   Janet L. Labunda has been assigned to help boat owners and other
individuals avoid unnecessary legal expenses resulting from the
zero-tolerance program, he said.
   ``I want to emphasize that this appointment does not mean we are
backing off zero tolerance one bit,'' von Raab said in making the
announcement.
   ``We are concerned about the small number of innocent people who
are unfortunate to be unwittingly associated with criminal
activity,'' he added.
   Boat owners and civil libertarians last month angrily criticized
the policy when the owner of the $2.5 million yacht Ark Royal had to
pay $1,600 in fines and fees after the service seized the vessel
because a small amount of marijuana was found. The marijuana
allegedly was taken aboard by a crewman.
   The private yacht Monkey Business _ known widely as the boat on
which former Democratic presidential candidate Gary Hart and model
Donna Rice spent a weekend with friends _ was seized outside the
U.S. 12-mile territorial limit on May 14 when a marijuana cigarette
was found aboard. Eight ounces of the drug later were found on the
vessel.
   The government later refined its procedures to seize vessels
outside the 12-mile limit only when there was evidence that the boat
was being used for drug trafficking.
   Since the government instituted the zero-tolerance policy March
21, more than 1,000 arrests have been made and more than 1,500
vessels have been seized, Customs said.
</TEXT>
