<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Religion     06-06 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Religion,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Praises Church at Christian Millennium Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZAGORSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government praised the Russian
Orthodox Church on Monday in a message to religious leaders who met
here to mark 1,000 years of Christianity in what is now the Soviet
Union.
   Official Radio Moscow said the message ``describes the
introduction of Christianity as a major event in the nation's
history and in the development of Russia's statehood and culture.''
   In Moscow, meanwhile, more than 50 religious dissidents crowded
into an apartment for an alternate service to emphasize restrictions
the government and church place on their religious lives.
   The four-day Local Council conference in Zagorsk, a medieval
center 40 miles northeast of Moscow that includes a monastery and
seminary, will name nine new saints and consider internal church
business, church officials said.
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, spiritual head of the
Church of England, representatives of the Roman Catholic Church, and
dozens of officials from Eastern and Western churches entered
Trinity-St. Sergius accompanied by the pealing of bells.
   Hundreds of Soviet citizens crowded around iron fences under a
hot morning sun to watch the procession.
   Journalists were not allowed into the conference. According to
Radio Moscow, the government's message said ``The unity of people,
irrespective of their attitude to religion, is essential to further
progress toward a society of social justice.''
   It urged the church to continue working for peace and ``foster
the humanitarian and moral potential of the nation,'' Radio Moscow
said.
   Included among the saints to be canonized are Russia's most
famous icon painter, Andrei Rublev, and Dmitri Donskoy, a 14th
century nobleman who defeated the Tatars in two major battles.
   Church documents said the conference also would consider an
administrative charter for the church and discuss its activities on
behalf of world peace.
   At the apartment in south Moscow, seven Russian Orthodox priests
barred from serving in parishes conducted a service for people who
came from many areas of the Soviet Union, dissident Alexander
Ogorodnikov said.
   He said the purpose was to demonstrate that the priests ``are
part of the life of the church despite the view of authorities.''
   Pentecostalists and Baptists also attended the service, he said.
</TEXT>
