<HEAD>Actor's Daughter Pleads Guilty to Parole Violation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Victoria Sellers, the daughter of the late
actor Peter Sellers, on Monday admitted using cocaine in violation
of probation terms set in an earlier drug distribution case.
   Ms. Sellers, 23, admitted diluting urine samples by drinking lots
of fluids, failing to appear for tests and leaving the district
without probation approval, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Gary
Lincenberg. In a federal court hearing, she pleaded guilty to
probation violation, and will be sentenced June 27, the prosecutor
said.
   Ms. Sellers, of Los Angeles, had been ordered to undergo periodic
testing for drugs as a condition of her three-year probation. She
was sentenced in March 1987 after pleading guilty to concealing a
crime in a New Jersey drug conspiracy case.
   ``Right now she is being tested every day, according to the
probation officer,'' Lincenberg said.
   As part of a plea bargain, the former Playboy model and actress
testified against other defendants who allegedly ran a violent, Los
Angeles-based cocaine ring headed by Reed Wallace, her talent agent
and housemate.
   A Newark, N.J. judge also ordered her to perform 600 hours of
community service and fined her $500.
   The U.S. Probation Office has indicated it will recommend Ms.
Sellers be treated at a drug rehabilitation program, and ``we would
concur with that recommendation,'' Lincenberg said.
   Ms. Sellers, a British citizen and daughter of actress Britt
Ekland, already has spent time in a rehabilitation program at St.
John's Hospital in Santa Monica, Lincenberg said.
   ``It obviously didn't work,'' he said.
