<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SriLanka     06-06 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Troops Begin Withdrawing From Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India on Tuesday plans to begin
withdrawing some of the troops it sent to Sri Lanka to enforce a
peace accord that so far has failed to stop the 5-year-old Tamil
separatist war, military officials said.
   An Indian Embassy official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Monday that at least 3,000 of the 50,000 Indian soldiers in Sri
Lanka would be sent home on Tuesday.
   Sri Lankan officers, also speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the departing troops would take part in a farewell ceremony in
Trincomalee, an eastern port.
   Meanwhile, two men suspected of being Tamil militants shot the
Rev. Chandra Fernando to death in the eastern port of Batticaloa, an
associate of the Roman Catholic priest reported.
   Fernando was president of the Batticaloa Citizens Committee, a
volunteer group that charts human rights abuses in the war.
   India began sending peacekeeping forces on July 30, a day after
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and Junius R. Jayewardene, president of
Sri Lanka, signed a peace accord they hoped would end the war that
has cost more than 8,000 lives.
   Rebels were not involved in negotiating the treaty, which
required them to lay down their arms in return for more autonomy in
northern and eastern Sri Lanka, where ethnic Tamils predominate.
   The largest insurgent group, Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam,
rejected the treaty and has continued fighting. It wants an
independent Tamil homeland in the north and east to be called Eelam.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
most are Hindus, the main religion among India's 800 million people.
They claim discrimination by the majority Sinhalese, a predominantly
Buddhist ethnic group that controls the government and military.
   India became involved because it is the region's dominant power
and has about 60 million Tamils in its southern Tamil Nadu state.
   Its soldiers began an offensive in October against the Tigers on
the northern Jaffna Peninsula, their main stronghold, and drove them
from the region.
   For the past two weeks, the Indians have been sweeping jungles
around Mullaitivu, an eastern port, for more Tigers bases.
   Indian news reports have said most of the equipment being
withdrawn was used in the Jaffna offensive and is no longer needed
for the search-and-destroy operations now being conducted.
</TEXT>
