<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EthelKennedy     06-06 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethel Kennedy,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Difficult Time for Kennedy Widow</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Kennedy Remembrance, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the world remembers Robert F. Kennedy 20 years
after his death his widow says she is getting through this difficult
time by trying to focus on the ``wonderful part ... to remember what
he stood for.''
   In an interview broadcast Monday on ``NBC Nightly News,'' Ethel
Kennedy declined to speculate what Kennedy would think about today's
political climate, but she said anyone who had been around her
husband and knew how he felt would believe ``things could be a lot
better now.''
   Still, Mrs. Kennedy said in the interview taped Saturday at her
Virginia home, ``I think a lot of people have made some sacrifices
in their lives to make it a better world ... and in a lot of ways it
is.''
   While Kennedy was a passionate man with intense beliefs, Mrs.
Kennedy said he never preached to his children.
   ``Probably that's why he had such a tremendous influence on the
children. He never tried to impose his world view on them,'' she
said. `` He did it by example ... he brought us all along with his
enthusiasm ... his love of life ... his curiosity and he made
everybody feel a part of this battle, that we're going to do better,
that America can stand for something.''
   Kennedy, then a senator from New York, was fatally shot in Los
Angeles on June 5, 1968, while campaigning for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   Thousands of people were expected to attend a memorial ceremony
Monday night at the Kennedy grave in Arlington National Cemetery in
Arlington, Va.
</TEXT>
