<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 2147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ArabSummit     06-06 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arab Summit,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Leaders Gather For Extradorinary Summit On Palestinian
Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab leaders began arriving here Monday
for a summit that a PLO official said will help determine the
direction of the Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied
territories.
   Bassam Abu Sharif, spokesman for the Palestine Liberation
Organization, spoke to reporters following his arrival in Algiers
with PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat for the extraordinary three-day
summit that begins Tuesday.
   He said the meeting will be very important in determining the
course of the six-month-old Palestinian insurrection in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``The Americans are not recognizing the Palestinians' legitimate
rights to self-determination and the establishment of an independent
state,'' he said. ``This is why all the proposals put by America are
born dead.''
   Sharif said political support for the rioting should include a
unified stand against the latest U.S. peace initiative and a
reiteration of ``their endorsement of the PLO as the sole,
legitimate representative of the (5 million) Palestinian people,
inside and outside the occupied territories.''
   Arafat, wearing green fatigues and with a pistol on his hip, was
the first leader to arrive for the summit convened to back the
anti-Israeli riots and to unify positions on the U.S. Middle East
initiative.
   Underscoring Arafat's participation as a key player, President
Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria accorded him a warm, official welcome at
the airport, as if Arafat were a full-fledged chief of state. A
young Algerian girl gave Arafat a bouquet of flowers.
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia; King Hussein of Jordan; Sheik Zayed
Bin Sultan an-Nahyan, the president of the United Arab Emirates, and
President Sid Ahmen Ould Taya of Mauritania flew in after Arafat.
   The other arrivals were expected to continue into Tuesday.
   The summit of all 21 members of the Arab League was convened by
Bendjedid essentially to strengthen Arab support and financial
backing for the 1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, territories taken from Jordan and Egypt by Israel in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Attention was sure to be riveted on Fahd, leader of the richest
Arab nation, to see if he will substantially increase the Saudi
subsidy for the uprising.
   ``Ideally, we would like to see the intefadeh (uprising )
transformed into a (Mahatma) Gandhi-style civil disobedience
campaign,'' said a senior PLO official, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``But that means about $10 million a day to compensate
for loss of income and feed the people.''
   Yasser Abed Rabbo, a member of the PLO's 15-man executive
committee, said the main PLO goal at the summit was to draw a
``clear-cut, unequivocal stand toward the United States and (U.S.
Secretary of State George) Shultz's plan.''
   Shultz was in Damascus Monday on his fourth attempt to persuade
Syrian President Hafez Assad to support his plan, which calls for
limited Palestinian self-rule to be followed by an international
conference.
   The plan excludes PLO participation in the parley. It also makes
no mention of a Palestinian state, for which the Arabs have been
struggling.
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafy, whose personal participation was
still in doubt Monday night, has said he wants the summit to keep
strictly to the sole item on its agenda, the Palestinian uprising.
</TEXT>
