<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Vietnam     06-06 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Vietnam,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Would Withdraw Troops From Cambodia On Political Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach of Vietnam
told the General Assembly on Monday that his government will
withdraw all its soldiers from Cambodia before 1990 if a political
settlement can be reached.
   At a special session on disarmament, he repeated a government
statement that half of the troops, about 50,000 men, will be
withdrawn this year and by 1990 all soldiers will have left Cambodia.
   ``If a political solution on Kampuchea (Cambodia) can be
achieved, Vietnamese forces will withdraw totally from Kampuchea in
accordance with the provisions of the agreement signed,'' Co Thach
said in a speech that was regarded as one of moderation and
conciliation.
   Vietnam invaded neighboring Cambodia in late 1978 and maintained
about 140,000 troops there, but it has been withdrawing or rotating
troops since 1982. Both nations are communist.
   ``We wish for a speedy political solution to the Kampuchean
question,'' Co Thach said, ``On the basis of respect for the
Kampuchean people's right to self-determination, termination of all
foreign interference and definitive prevention of any possible
return of the genocidal and war-mongering Pol Pot regime.''
   Pol Pot led the pro-Chinese, Khmer Rouge communist government in
Cambodia. The present government in Phnom Penh, backed by Vietnam
and the Soviet Union, has been battling a three-party coalition that
includes the forces of former Cambodian leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, the Khmer Rouge, and the non-communist forces of former
Cambodian Prime Minister Son Sann.
   The General Assembly repeatedly has rejected the legitimacy of
the Vietnam-installed government in Cambodia and recognizes the
coalition as the legitimate government at the United Nations.
   Co Thach noted that the people of Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia have
been victims for 40 years of successive protracted wars which used
the largest amount of bombs and ammunition in history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
