<1ST_LINE>u a AM-KennedyRemembrance 4thLd-Writethru a0810 06-06 0976</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Remembrance, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0810,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend 20th Anniversary Mass At Gravesite</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS final graf to INCLUDE Douglas Kennedy</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 people joined the Kennedy
family Monday at the grave of Robert F. Kennedy for a sunset ``Mass
in joyful remembrance'' of the senator who was slain 20 years ago
while savoring victory in the California presidential primary.
   This was the first time since Kennedy's death that his family
opened to the public its annual memorial service at Arlington
National Cemetery. The graveside service was not far from where his
brother, John F. Kennedy, the 35th president, is buried.
   Ethel Kennedy, the senator's widow, and their 10 surviving
children took part in the service. One of those children, Rory
Elizabeth Kennedy, was not born until six months after her father
was assassinated at the age of 42.
   By the time the service began, the steep hillside under the
Custis-Lee Mansion was crowded with friends, former campaign aides
and tourists who happened to be in the cemetery. Lt. Col. Robert
Mirelson, deputy public affairs officer for the Military District of
Washington, estimated attendance at 5,000.
   As the service ended with the singing of the Battle Hymn of the
Republic, the people on the hillside lighted candles they had been
given on their way to the grave site, bathing the scene in a soft
glow.
   ``Robert Kennedy was always ready to stop and reach out to
others,'' said Joseph P. Kennedy II, the eldest son who is a
congressman from Massachusetts. ``Now, 20 years after his death, my
mother, my brothers and sisters, all of us in our family share with
countless others across America and abroad those precious moments of
his public life.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, Robert's younger brother, recited the
prayer of St. Francis: ``Lord, make me an instrument of your peace
... for it is in pardoning that we are forgiven.''
   Robert, a 34-year-old son who bears his father's name, asked the
crowd for a moment's prayer for a policeman who was struck by a
motorist as the Kennedy motorcade headed toward the service.
   Two bowls of white flowers graced the altar while a box in front
of the altar held 400 to 500 pink roses.
   Each of the Kennedy children and a few of Kennedy's grandchildren
recited during the service, some quoting from speeches their father
made, others from the Scripture.
   Matthew Kennedy welcomed the celebrants to the Mass on behalf of
his mother, sisters and brothers and said, ``I invite you to join us
in renewing the commitment that was his life, his spirit and his
hope.''
   Courtney Kennedy Ruhe quoted from a speech that the former
senator gave during the Oregon primary campaign in 1968 a week
before he was assassinated.
   ``Perhaps this world will always be a world in which children
suffer,'' she recited. ``But we can reduce the number of suffering
children and if you don't help us, who will?''
   And John F. Kennedy Jr., the only son of the president, recited
Shakespearean words Robert Kennedy liked to quote: ``When he shall
die, take him and cut him out in little stars, and he will make the
face of heaven so fine that all the world will be in love with
night, and pay no worship to the garish sun.''
   The gathering included some important names from the Kennedy era,
such as Ted Sorensen, a top aide and biographer to both Kennedy
brothers, and Byron White, a Supreme Court justice who was appointed
by John F. Kennedy. Neither Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis nor her
daughter, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, attended the service.
   The memorial Mass was in the evening, as was Robert Kennedy's
burial. The reason then was the large and grieving crowds that
slowed the train carrying his coffin from New York after a service
in St. Patrick's Cathedral. The funeral was four hours late and in
the darkness, children held lighted candles.
   Now the late hour was set to accommodate close friends and others
who wanted to share the memory with his family.
   Robert Kennedy, then a senator from New York and running for the
Democratic presidential nomination, was fatally shot in Los Angeles
shortly after midnight on June 5, 1968, following a brief speech at
a hotel to 2,000 campaign supporters who were celebrating his
California primary victory the previous evening. He died the
following day.
   His last words to those cheering supporters were ``it's on to
Chicago and let's win there.'' Chicago was the site of the 1968
Democratic National Convention.
   Sirhan Sirhan, the Jordanian-born assassin who insisted he did
not know how he was driven to his deed, still is in prison. He was
convicted of first degree murder, but his death sentence was lifted
when California abolished the death penalty.
   Kennedy's grave site is marked with a simple cross and a small
pool, a stark contrast to the more ornate grave of his brother.
There, an eternal flame burns that can be seen from Washington,
across the Potomac River, and the area is bordered by a wall
inscribed with quotations from John F. Kennedy's speeches.
   The fourth of the 11 Kennedy children, David Anthony Kennedy, was
found dead of a drug overdose in West Palm Beach, Fla., in April
1984.
   The others are Kathleen Townsend, 36, who heads a Maryland youth
corps program and was an unsuccessful candidate for Congress; Joe,
35; Robert Jr., 34, who teaches environmental law at Pace
University; Courtney Ruhe, 31, a fund-raiser for the RFK Foundation;
   Michael, 30, who heads Citizens Energy Corp. in Boston; Mary, 28,
who runs RFK Center for Human Rights in Boston; Christopher, 24,
works for the family-owned Merchandise mart in Chicago; Matthew, 23,
a senior at Harvard; Douglas, 21, a sophomore at Boston College, and
Rory, 19, a freshman at Brown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
