<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 2253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Contras     06-06 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Contras,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Rebels Are Coming to Canada on False Passports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels from Nicaragua are coming to Canada on false
passports, opposition members of Parliament complained Monday,
citing reports from Costa Rica.
   Immigration Minister Barbara McDougall told Parliament ``there is
a very large international problem of false documentation'' and said
the government was taking serious action to combat it.
   She noted that the Royal Canadian Mounted Police arrested two Sri
Lankan men in Montreal last weekend and seized material used to make
200 forged Canadian travel permits allowing foreigners lacking
genuine passports to enter Canada.
   The Toronto Globe and Mail said Monday that 300 to 600 Nicarguans
living in Costa Rica have used forged documents to enter Canada in
the past eight months.
   It said the operation was run by the U.S.-backed guerrillas,
known as Contras, who are fighting Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government.
   The report said Canadian officials in Costa Rica learned of the
forgeries in April but the racket continues.
   Since the beginning of last year, 1,335 Nicaraguans have claimed
refugee status at Canadian airports _ some of them holding genuine
passports.
   Sergio Marchi, immigration spokesman for the opposition Liberal
Party, said many Contras have ``horrible human rights violation
records'' and should be barred from Canada.
   Dan Heap, a member of Parliament from the opposition New
Democratic Party, complained that in Canada's official refugee
program, the government welcomed 1,177 Nicaraguans between January
1987 and March 1988, while taking only 568 Guatemalans where the
danger is far greater at the moment.
   Ms. McDougall responded that applicants are considered on a
case-by-case basis. She said that however an immigrant or refugee
enters Canada, war criminals and terrorists are unacceptable and the
system will eventually reject them.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Conservative government has
proposed legislation to toughen immigration and refugee laws, but
the opposition parties have delayed passage, contending that the
bills would penalize the genuinely needy as well as illegal aliens.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
