<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HarvardProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0768 06-06 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harvard Protest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0768,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nineteen Arrested After Harvard Students, Alumni Protest Apartheid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with 19 arrested to end
occupation; picks up 6th graf pvs, `It's clear...' SUBS 7th graf pvs
`Ropes & Gray...' to restore first reference for Casner. SUBS last
graf to UPDATE with O'Donnell comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 19 people Monday to end an
occupation of a law firm's office by a group of Harvard University
students and alumni protesting the firm's work for a company that
has a subsidiary in South Africa.
   A group of about 35 demonstrators walked into the office of Ropes
& Gray at 10 a.m. They chanted and sang songs while a group of
supporters marched outside the building chanting ``Hey, hey Ropes
and Gray, how much does apartheid pay?''
   Boston police entered the building around 7:45 p.m. and arrested
the 19 people remaining. They were charged with trespassing and
released on bail pending arraignment Tuesday in Boston Municipal
Court, said police Lt. John Boyle.
   ``We didn't feel we had any other choice than have them
removed,'' said Thomas O'Donnell, a managing partner at the firm and
a principal target of the protest. He said protesters had earlier
refused his request for a meeting with just a few of their
representatives.
   The protesters said they were concerned that the firm represents
at least one company doing business in South Africa, while O'Donnell
co-chairs a committee of Harvard's board of overseers that is
reviewing the university's investment in companies with operations
in South Africa.
   ``It's a clear conflict of interest,'' said Betsy Fishman, a
Harvard senior who was among about 40 people outside the building
housing the firm's office.
   Ropes & Gray represents the Gillette Corp., said Truman Casner, a
senior partner and member of the law firm's management board. A
Gillette spokeswoman confirmed that the company has a subsidiary in
South Africa.
   Officials at the firm were attempting to arrange a meeting
between a representative for the protesters and O'Donnell, said
Casner, who added that the firm conducted business as usual Monday.
   Bruce Marks, who identified himself as a member of the Harvard
Divestment Coalition, said one demonstrator, Eric Chester, planned
to press assault charges against Ropes & Gray lawyers for what Marks
described as a scuffle.
   Another demonstrator, Michael Wolf, was being examined by a
doctor for a possible broken collarbone sustained in an altercation
with lawyers and security guards, Marks said.
   O'Donnell said Ropes & Gray officials could not confirm whether
any protesters were injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
