<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100 Soviets Reported Killed In Fighting with Afghan Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy fighting raged in Afghanistan's
northeastern Baghland province and one report Monday said more than
100 Soviet soldiers were killed battling guerrillas.
   There was no independent confirmation.
   Baghland City, the provincial capital, has been under siege for
weeks. Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, chairman of the seven-party Moslem
guerrilla alliance, saids the city's collapse would be a coup for
his fighters.
   Agency Afghan Press, a private-run Pakistani news service,
claimed more than 100 Soviets and 15 guerrillas were killed on the
Salang Highway when the anti-Marxist guerrillas repulsed an attack
on their headquarters near the city on May 27.
   Departing Soviet troops travel the Salang Highway, the only road
out of Afghanistan's capital city of Kabul north to the Soviet Union.
   A strategic northern city would also give the U.S.-backed
guerrillas a stronghold should speculation prove true that Afghan
President Najib is eyeing the north as a possible refuge if Kabul is
overrun.
   Meanwhile, official Radio Kabul broadcasts have been playing up
guerrilla activities since May 15, the official start of the Soviet
withdrawal under a United Nations-sponsored peace accord. Prior
broadcasts virtually ignored guerrilla exploits.
   The radio, monitored in Islamabad, claimed late Sunday that
troops overran three guerrilla groups in southeastern Zabul and
Kandahar provinces and in northwestern Faryab province.
   Guerrilla commanders have been preparing for a major offensive on
the major city of Kandahar. According to Agency Afghan Press,
villages to the southwest of Kandahar City have been heavily bombed.
   Soviet forces invaded Afghanistan in 1979 and replaced one
Marxist government with another. It began withdrawing its more than
100,000 troops on May 15 after signing the April peace accord in
Geneva.
</TEXT>
