<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PoultryFire 1stLd-Writethru a0752 06-06 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poultry Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0752,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Seek Origin Of Fires That Left $7.5 Million In Damage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf ``We've got'' to CORRECT spelling to Levasseur
sted Lebasseur. Inserts one graf after 8th graf ``But officials'' to
UPDATE with Dayton selectmen deferring a decision on disposal
question.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN COSTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators examined the charred remains
of two egg farms Monday to try to determine what set off blazes that
killed 240,000 hens, destroyed thousands of eggs and caused $7.5
million in damage.
   The hens were killed at Co-Hen Egg Farms in this tiny southern
Maine town late Saturday in a fire that engulfed three barns before
firefighters arrived. Debris from the 480-foot-long buildings was
still smoldering two days later, and that and the stench of charred
birds hampered investigators.
   About 60 trailer loads of eggs were destroyed Sunday in a fire
that swept through the storage and packing facilities at DeCoster
Egg Farms, the nation's largest brown egg producer, in Turner, Fire
Chief Laurence Gagne said. No livestock died.
   Bruce E. Mullen, fire chief of Goodwins Mills, near Dayton,
estimated the loss at Co-Hen Farms at $2.5 million. Gagne said the
damage at DeCoster Farms, located 12 miles north of Auburn, was
about $5 million.
   Investigators from the state Fire Marshal's office said
determining the cause of both fires could take up to a week.
   ``We've got no idea,'' investigator Joseph A. Levasseur said,
surveying the smoldering ruins at Co-Hen Farms. ``We'll start at one
end and work our way to the other. I haven't ruled out anything at
this point.''
   State Department of Environmental Protection officials urged
Dayton town officials to quickly dispose of the charred chickens.
   But officials said neither the birds nor debris from the
buildings could be buried at the fire site because the ground is
sandy, gravely and susceptible to seepage, and a suitable burial
site had not yet been found, said Peter N. Mosher of the state
Department of Agriculture.
   The board discussed the disposal question at a Monday night
meeting but deferred a decision until Tuesday, Selectman Clement
Meserve Jr. said.
   Despite the loss of the hens, which produced nearly 200,000 eggs
per day, Co-Hen Farms remained in operation Monday with eight
surviving hen houses on that farm, said Dennis Babb, a supervisor at
Co-Hen.
   Co-Hen, which also owns other egg farms in Maine, has about
600,000 hens, making it one of Northern New England's largest egg
producers.
   Lost egg production will be made up through contracts with
smaller egg producers in the area, said Lois L. Hall, a secretary to
Co-Hen owner Maurice Cohen.
   This is not the first time fire has swept through the DeCoster
farm. On March 7, 1987, fire destroyed 25,000 hens.
</TEXT>
