<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Submarines     06-06 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Submarines,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Explodes Depth Bombs in Get-Tough Anti-Sub Hunt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The navy exploded a mine and depth
charges Monday night southeast of Stockholm as part of an
intensified effort to stop underwater intrusions by suspected
mini-submarines, officials said.
   The use of the weapons came after indications that a foreign
submarine operated between Orno and Uto islands. That is in the
vicinity of Sweden's main east coast naval base at Musko, 18{ miles
southeast of Stockholm.
   A mine was exploded in the same area a week ago and military
preparedness has been high since then. The navy would say only that
the search continued.
   The navy has exploded mines, depth charges and anti-sub grenades
on a half-dozen occasions during the past week, both on the east
coast and in the archipelago off Goteborg on the west coast.
   Numerous dead fish were the only tangible effects reported.
   Navy spokesmen on Monday denied news reports that a damaged
minisub was suspected to be hiding near Donso island off Goteborg.
   A military staff spokesman, Thomas Guer, said naval subhunters
are acting under new government directives which permit firing at
intruders without warning in the inner archipelago and sometimes in
waters farther out.
</TEXT>
