<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv12,0475</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, June 12, the 164th day of 1988. There are 202
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   Twenty-five years ago, on June 12, 1963, civil rights leader
Medgar Evers was shot to death in front of his home in Jackson,
Miss. He was 36.
   On this date:
   In 1665, the English installed their own form of municipal
government in what used to be the Dutch settlement of New Amsterdam
-- which the English renamed New York.
   In 1776, the state of Virginia adopted a Bill of Rights -- the
first colonial legislature to do so.
   In 1838, the Iowa Territory was organized.
   In 1898, Philippine nationalists declared their independence from
Spain.
   In 1917, the Secret Service extended its protection of the
President to his family as well.
   In 1937, the Soviet Union executed eight army leaders as a purge
under Josef Stalin continued.
   In 1939, the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum was
dedicated in Cooperstown, N.Y.
   In 1963, one of Hollywood's costliest failures, ``Cleopatra,''
starring Elizabeth Taylor, Richard Burton and Rex Harrison,
premiered in New York.
   In 1967, the U.S. Supreme Court unanimously struck down state
laws prohibiting interracial marriages.
   In 1971, Tricia Nixon and Edward F. Cox were married in a
ceremony in the White House Rose Garden.
   In 1977, ground-breaking ceremonies took place in Boston for a
library honoring the late President John F. Kennedy.
   In 1979, a 26-year-old cyclist, Bryan Allen, flew the man-powered
Gossamer Albatross across the English Channel.
   In 1982, an estimated three-quarters of a million anti-nuclear
demonstrators filled New York's Central Park.
   In 1986, South Africa declared a national state of emergency,
giving virtually unlimited power to security forces and severely
restricting news coverage of unrest.
   Ten years ago: David Berkowitz was sentenced in New York Supreme
Court in Brooklyn to 25 years to life in prison for each of the six
``Son of Sam'' .44-caliber killings that had terrified New Yorkers.
   Five years ago: Academy Award-winning actress Norma Shearer died
at a hospital in Woodland Hills, Calif., at age 80.
   One year ago: President Reagan publicly challenged Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev to ``tear down'' the Berlin Wall during a visit to
the western side of the Brandenburg Gate.
   Today's Birthdays: Banker David Rockefeller is 73. Movie producer
Irwin Allen is 72. Actress Uta Hagen is 69. Vice President George
Bush is 64. Singer Vic Damone is 60. Actor-singer Jim Nabors is 56.
Jazz musician Chick Corea is 47.
   Thought for Today: ``Think like a man of action, and act like a
man of thought.'' -- Henri Bergson, French philosopher (1859-1941).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
