<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--Classof'38 Adv19-2ndAdd   06-06 1013</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Class of '38, Adv 19-2nd Add,1043</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>CHAPEL HILL, N.C.: team Hiroshima...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I was as far away as I could get at Alamogordo. The sound was
just a rumble, but I've never forgotten the light, that tremendous
flash. We thought that anything that would end the war was
justified. I know we've been lucky, but maybe the bomb has had some
deterrence. Out here (Springfield, Mo.) it's just a fact of life.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Where do we...go from here?''
   _ From ``Mission Impossible,'' by Joe Paterson.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sanford Garelik: New Yorker, one of 979 non-Tar Heels at UNC ...
took New York City police exam on a bet ... rose to become highest
uniformed officer in department ... handled ``almost every'' riot
and demonstration in '60s ... walked down Wall Street with Soviet
Premier Kosygin ... two terms president New York City Council ...
   ``My first beat was on Willis Avenue in the South Bronx. Then the
cop on the corner was kind of a judge. You'd take bad boys home to
their moms, settle arguments. Today the South Bronx is a burned-out
war zone. In the '30s, we were a more homogenous nation. When you
have that, you have extended families. Today we look to government.
That's not bad, but it's not family. We've had an erosion of moral
values, respect for authority. Violence has almost achieved
respectability. Purse snatchers wear Reeboks. Democracy requires a
fairly educated public to work, and we don't have that. We've lost
some generations, and there's not much we can do about that. But how
do we save the next generations? We have to face the reality of what
government can and cannot do, and we're not doing that. As a result,
politicians cater to what people want to hear.
   ``The '60s demonstrators ripped the cover from injustice and
hypocrisy. But if you're going to tear down, you've got to build.
They didn't build.
   ``Society today expects a reward, needs a chemical stimulant to
cope with the problems of life. `This Bud's for You.' The enemy is
here _ It's Miller Time in America.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``We are a part of you...''
   _ From ``Go, Man, Go!,'' by Joe Patterson.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Marvin Chaikin: Another New Yorker ... WW II with Navy in North
Atlantic ... ate peanut butter to scrimp to buy communications
business he built into good life in Great Neck, N.Y., with yacht,
Tar Heel, nearby ... retirement unthinkable ... Jewish.
   ``I've tried all these years to de-sensitize myself. It's never
worked. I cannot change my concept of what the Germans stood for. It
was madness, the falling apart of man. But we gave our blood. We
backed up our promises. But we haven't continued to struggle, and
the struggle is never over. Our class had a particular hunger,
apprehensions for the future, how we were going to work it out. We
made it. The idea of living means putting things in balance. But the
United States has become complacent, spoiled. We overindulged our
children.''
   But overindulgence notwithstanding, the man who sold nickel
apples at football games is going to make sure his 15-year-old
granddaughter, Jody, whose mother is divorced and not affluent, goes
to college _ Chapel Hill.
   ``Jody is my best friend.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Fifty years of work and training,
   ``Fifty years of trying hard.''
   _ From ``Sixty-Nine,'' by Joe Patterson.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Edwin Jones Hamlin: Journalism major happy to get first newspaper
job at $6 a week ... acquired two weeklies: ``One week readers
thought I was a hero, the next a bum, so I decided to write what I
thought was right.'' Sold out in 1960s to work for state ...
retired, and then ...
   At age 71 Ed Hamlin wrote his first job resume. ``When I retired,
I decided I didn't want to play golf more than once or twice a week.
I had always wanted to be a lawyer, but with the Depression ...''
   So at age 68 Hamlin entered law school over in Greensboro, passed
the bar exam last year and landed a part-time job with a Raleigh
firm. Retirement, Ed?
   ``Well, I didn't do anything from spring of '82 to the fall of
'83 before I got into law school.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``The black man passed, eyes downcast.''
   _ From ``An Inside Look,'' by Joe Patterson.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   John McNeill Smith Jr.: Class cattle prod as editor Daily Tar
Heel ... put editorials on Page One ... when child, threw water on
playmates saying Hoover (a dry) was just as wet as Al Smith (a wet)
... defended Julius Scales against Communist charges in McCarthy
era: ``My grandfather belonged to a group that advocated overthrow
of the U.S. government, namely, the Confederate States of America.''
Headed Carolina's first civil rights commission 1959-63 ... National
Law Journal lists him among 100 most powerful attorneys in nation ...
   When the UNC cheerleaders, the Monogram Club, ousted Glen Davis
from the squad _ a job elected by the student body _ for not
rah-rahing with due enthusiasm, editor Smith put a photo of campus
leaders in the paper captioned, ``Who Will Be Next?'' He was
teaching a lesson not in the UNC syllabus: Trust not the claims of
an exclusive minority.
   Outside his Greensboro firm's new offices, so big they have exit
signs, is a historical marker on the sidewalk: ``SIT-INS@Launched
the national drive for integrated lunch counters Feb. 1, 1960 in
Woolworth's two blocks south.'' This particular day a black woman is
working behind the counter.
   ``The Supreme Court taught us a lot,'' said Smith. ``We've been
saved by the application of the Constitution.''
   Marv Chaikin had been shocked on arrival at UNC in 1934 when a
deferential black moved out into the unpaved street to leave him the
sidewalk. Did Smith ever conceive that 50 years after his graduation
a black student by the name of Jackson who had once tried to
integrate a movie house hard by his very office would get the
second-most delegates for the Democratic nomination for president?
</TEXT>
