<DOCNO> AP880606-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--SpyJet Adv19-1stAdd   06-06 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Spy Jet, Adv 19-1st Add,0724</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>SOMEWHERE OVER IDAHO: Air Force.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The recent training mission observed by the news crew began at
Beale, with the pilot and reconnaissance systems operator arriving
three hours before takeoff for physicals, breakfast, briefings, and
donning of $100,000 spacesuits that include toilet facilities.
   A van like those used to take astronauts to launch pads carried
the men to the SR-71.
   Fuel that is not particularly flammable dripped to the ground
from half-full tanks, which would fully seal only after the aircraft
expanded in the heat of flight.
   Equipment screamed as it ignited the SR-71's twin turbojets,
which belched greenish-blue flames and 100-foot streams of
shimmering heat just idling.
   Finally, the Blackbird blasted down the runway, then skyward, in
a crackling thunder that shook the ground.
   Some two hours later, those aboard the KC-135 Stratotanker again
saw the delta-winged Blackbird, this time over a practice refueling
corridor some 25,000 feet above southern Idaho's snowed-capped
mountains.
   The refueling boom operator laid in the belly of the tanker at
its tail, staring out the back through portals as he helped guide
the boom into the 107-foot-long Blackbird.
   Within minutes, the second half of the SR-71's fuel load _ too
heavy a burden for its liftoff _ was gushing between the coupled
planes, which were traveling at 500 mph.
   Explained tanker navigator, Lt. Phil Campbell: ``We're going as
fast as we can and he's going as slow as he can.''
   Aerial refueling provides the Blackbird its global range. A
mission can keep an SR-71 in the air for 12 hours, entering hostile
territory and leaving it to refuel perhaps four or five times, says
Orcutt, SR-71 squadron commander at Beale.
   Tanker crews are somewhat jealous of attention focused on the
Blackbird and its close-knit crews: ``Everything is always SR this,
SR that,'' griped one tanker crew member.
   But both tanker and Blackbird crews acknowledge a mutual respect:
``Tankers have gone the extra mile in many cases to reach an SR-71
in trouble,'' says wing commander Graham.
   Many of the Blackbird crew members are family men, with the
youngest in their early 30s. For most, it's their last active-duty
flying assignment.
   Judy Bozek, the 31-year-old wife of Maj. Blair Bozek, an SR-71
crewman, was aboard the tanker watching. ``I worry,'' she says,
``but you sort of get numb to the fear. Seeing him today made it
worse. I can visualize it now.''
   Orcutt, who has flown 80 Blackbird missions in five years, says
he experienced an in-flight emergency that could have led to an
explosion. Such dramas are doubly tense because pilots are flying
over hostile territory.
   Blackbird pilots say their background helps them survive. Crews
usually have a decade of flying experience before they can compete
for the program. If accepted, they train for another year.
   Even on the ground, dangers persist. Former airman Bruce Ott was
sent to prison in 1986 for passing an SR-71 unit personnel list to
FBI agents posing as Soviet spies.
   Indeed, the role of the SR-71 in world affairs apparently remains
significant. Department of Defense officials say aircraft are still
needed to gather intelligence because of the limits of satellite
surveillance, according to news reports.
   But SR-71s are becoming more scarce and the prototype photo
reconnaissance planes, the glider-like U-2s, are even older and less
capable. There are reportedly only nine of the 30 original SR-71s
still in operation. Some have crashed; others have simply worn out.
   Even so, the military plans cutbacks in the SR-71 squadron
operated by the Strategic Air Command out of Beale and its forward
fields at Mildenhall, a Royal Air Force installation in England, and
at Kadena Air Base on the Japanese island of Okinawa.
   Wing commander Graham says he has been told four Blackbirds will
be deactivated in fiscal 1989, which would reportedly save the Air
Force $300 millionannually. Congressional members are protesting the
cuts.
   As the era of the Blackbirds wanes, SR-71 pilots are looking to
the future.
   Asked if he'd like to fly the new stealth photo reconnaissance
jet, Orcutt quickly replies, ``I'd be the first one to raise my
hand.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
