<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1516EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--NewFace Adv19   06-06 0941</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--New Face, Adv 19,0971</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ A girl of 8, she was born with a black, hairy
blotch covering much of her face, a growth doctors describe as much
like ape skin. But thanks to a Denver plastic surgeon and an
organization called ``Friends of Man,'' Monica Tovar is being
transformed, a process that will take years to complete.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOE McGOWAN Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Monica Tovar, a young Mexico City girl born with a
disfiguring facial growth, has been given a ``new face'' by a Denver
plastic surgeon who donated his skills.
   The shy, 8-year-old has endured playmates' taunts, two operations
in Mexico, three in Denver and the prospect of others, during what
will be a 10-year project to remove completely scars and blemishes.
   ``When she is 16 or 17 and ready to date, I'll be finished,''
said her surgeon, Dr. Thomas Gargan, chief of plastic surgery at
Rose Medical Center.
   ``Monica is a unique child,'' he said as he showed slides
illustrating how Monica looked before and after the $10,000
procedure.
   ``This little girl with such beautiful hair has impressed me with
her courage. There is something that tears at your heartstrings when
you operate on a little girl like Monica.''
   Monica was born with a congenital hairy nevus, a black, hairy
blotch covering much of the left side of her face.
   Gargan said such a growth, occuring in fewer than 100,000 births,
is ``just like ape skin or chimpanzee skin. It is something like a
mole and as much as 8.5 percent of them develop into cancerous
melanomas.
   ``I've never seen one this bad,'' he said. ``Traditionally, you
cut out a growth such as Monica's and you put on a thick skin graft.
The problem is that it looks like a patch. The color doesn't match
and there is some contraction in the corners.''
   So Gargan undertook a relatively new procedure beginning in June
1986, when he inserted an inflatable bag under the skin of her neck,
along the jaw line.
   Using a valve placed behind Monica's ear, Gargan injected saline
solution into the bag once a week. As the bag expanded, it stretched
Monica's skin.
   ``Usually, kids don't tolerate the skin expander very well,'' the
doctor said. ``She cried a little at times, but she was so brave.
   ``Eventually, the skin became so thin you could almost see
through it. I felt I had gone as far as I could.''
   So, in September 1986, Gargan cut away the growth. The skin which
had been stretched, amounting to a large flap, was pulled up and
over the area where the nevus had been.
   The surgery was extensive on Monica's face, neck and chest,
involving hundreds of stitches.
   After the surgery, Monica had to wear a compression mask over her
head for one year, 23 hours a day. Made of a woven elastic material,
the mask had openings for her eyes, nose, mouth and ears, and was
kept tight by Velcro fasteners.
   ``The mask minimizes scarring and squeezes the swelling out of
the flap,'' Gargan explained. During that year, Monica's long, dark
hair had to be kept crew-cut short.
   After the year, Gargan performed a second graft under Monica's
bottom lip, and in time he will do a chin implant because ``her chin
flattened out a bit from the flap being pulled up.''
   Gargan says more work will be needed in the years ahead as Monica
matures and her adult facial features develop.
   Monica, speaking partly in Spanish and partly in English, says
she is happy the growth is gone and doesn't mind facing more surgery
because she knows it will make her look better.
   But Monica admits she would like to return to Mexico. ``I want to
go tomorrow. Our living is so different here,'' she said in the
cramped, three-room apartment she shares with her parents, brother
and two sisters.
   ``I miss Mexico and my friends,'' Monica says, but she admits she
likes American TV and amusement parks.
   Monica's parents, Francisco and Magda Tovar, are working at
menial jobs to support the family. In Mexico City, Francisco was an
administrative accountant and the family lived comfortably.
   ``Our standard of living is lower here,'' Mrs. Tovar said in
Spanish. ``But we are happy to do it for Monica. We will do
everything we can. We hope some day we can help other children.''
   In addition to Gargan's donated services, an organization called
``Friends of Man'' has helped with the medical costs. Monica's
parents are now at least partially covered by medical insurance.
   Monica completed the fourth grade this month and was looking
forward to ``a lot of swimming.''
   Her favorite class was art, she says, because ``I get to draw
with crayons, Magic Markers and so on. I really enjoy that.''
   Gargan last saw Monica in April when he re-contoured her chin. He
also ``revised the scar along the left side of the nose to bring it
in so it fit in with the crease formed by the nose and the cheek so
it is less noticable. The re-contouring was to help define the chin
more clearly.
   ``She is an extremely courageous little girl,'' he says. ``What
has impressed me so much is the courage she has shown despite
multiple, complex operations, wearing that `balloon' on her face for
so long and having such pain. She went through all of that like a
trooper.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
