<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv19   06-06 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 19,0940</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christopher Plummer is beginning to think that
Shakespeare's ``Macbeth'' is jinxed, as the old theater superstition
has it.
   He has a knee injury, a neck injury, a broken nose and some
missing teeth, all suffered since he signed on for his latest tour
as the Scottish king.
   Plummer, who is starring opposite Glenda Jackson in ``Macbeth''
on Broadway, for a limited run through July 3 at the Mark Hellinger
Theater, suffered his first mishap in Baltimore when he severed
cartilage and tore ligaments in his knee. He rehearsed on a new set
on crutches for days and performed in a cast.
   He lost a couple of teeth, yet to be replaced, in Toronto.
``Somebody banged into me in a blackout, going about 75 m.p.h.,'' he
says. ``I managed to continue the performance. They weren't the
essential teeth you need to speak.
   ``He banged into my head. My nose was broken for the third time.
Now I have a deviated septum as a result of that charming incident.
   ``And I developed that awful disintegrating disc on the neck. It
presses on the motor nerve and makes life miserable. I was in a neck
brace in Boston. I would take it off and I would be lopsided. I
found it difficult to stand straight. Now I'm much freer. I still go
to therapy.''
   Plummer says he'll ``go into the garage'' for repairs in July.
   Theater people have long considered ``Macbeth'' bad luck. No
actor ever has launched a career playing the title role. And
thespians are careful to say ``the Scottish play'' and never
``Macbeth'' anytime they're inside a theater.
   ``Maybe the play IS jinxed,'' Plummer laughs.
   Jinxed or not, this production of ``Macbeth'' has been drawing
good audiences.
   ``I think audiences want to hear good words spoken well and to
see good theater again,'' Plummer says. ``They've seen a lot of
mediocre stuff. It made us do extraordinarily well on the road _
Glenda, myself and Shakespeare.''
   Macbeth, who murders Scotland's king, Duncan, and becomes king
early in the play, is called by Plummer ``an intensely modern man.
Any ambitious young tycoon and anybody in the power-play game who
wants to rise can understand him. In every generation there are
Macbeths.
   ``Macbeth's conscience doesn't last very long. He consults his
evil psychiatrists _ the three witches _ who show him the easiest
way to power and to madness. Power-mad people can't stop once they
start because too many people know where all the bodies are buried.
   ``I think Macbeth is always aware; that is the tragedy. It would
be easy to play someone who is mad. It's more difficult to play
someone on the verge of madness.
   ``Macbeth is not as old as I am. When you're over 50, vaulting
ambition is no longer part of your psyche. Some of the youthful
anger you have when you're a young actor has vanished ... An actor
should be able to rustle it up at a moment's notice. That youthful
anger is very important to Macbeth.''
   One critic who saw Plummer in ``Macbeth'' in 1962 at the
Stratford Festival in his native Canada thought it was angrier and
better.
   ``I think he is generally wrong,'' Plummer says. ``Technically,
I'm much better equipped now. I understand the role much better. I
think I make it much clearer.
   ``It's difficult to make it clear, particularly in the beginning.
Scholars have said there are two major scenes missing. I take the
first part of the play much slower than most Macbeths do. I let the
audience come to me a bit and see what I'm thinking. In the first
soliloquy, he has received the news that he's to be king. I try and
take that as slowly and clearly as I possibly can. It does help.
   ``The unjust thing about the play is that the real Macbeth in the
12th century was a good king. He followed Duncan; he didn't kill
him.''
   This production of ``Macbeth'' had two set designers and three
directors. The first director, Kenneth Frankel, Plummer says,
``Obviously couldn't see it through. We were going to get into
artistic differences very soon. We opened rather shaky, with only
three-and-a-half weeks of rehearsal. `Macbeth' needs six weeks. What
audiences saw was us still rehearsing. At least he got it on.''
Robin Phillips, who could only give limited time, stepped in as
director and, Plummer says, ``Whipped up an exciting souffle on the
stage. But certain things he began so brilliantly were left in the
air. Zoe Caldwell came in and pushed the interpretation forward.
   ``Zoe is wonderful at bringing you back to the truth of the text.
After you've gone so many journeys out and around it as you have to
do with these great roles, you need someone to remind you of the
simplicity.''
   Once when he and Miss Jackson were vigorously discussing their
roles, Plummer says, somebody thought they were fighting and
informed the news media. ``We haven't said one lousy word to each
other since the beginning,'' he says. ``We get on very well. I asked
Glenda if she minded and she said, `No. It sells tickets.' I think
it did.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
