<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Economic Bloc Has Doubled In Size Since Founding</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-EEC-Unity, b0520-b0521</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the three decades since six West
European nations signed the Treaty of Rome creating the European
Economic Community, the organization has doubled in size.
   France, West Germany, Italy, Belgium, the Netherlands and
Luxembourg founded the organization in 1957.
   Britain, Ireland and Denmark joined in 1973, after having been
blackballed by the France of President Charles de Gaulle in 1961.
   Greece became the 10th member in 1981, and Spain and Portugal
joined in 1986.
   Last year Turkey submitted an application for membership but
negotiations have not yet begun, partly due to Greek opposition.
Morocco in North Africa also applied last year but was told it did
not qualify since it is not in Europe.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
