<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Iglesias Adv17-19   06-06 0964</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Iglesias, Adv 17-19,1007</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, June 17-19 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Julio Iglesias Craves Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Julio Iglesias sold out nine shows at the
6,000-seat Radio City Music Hall, and he signed autographs at a
nearby record store that had lines around the block.
   But as far as the international superstar is concerned, that
still doesn't make him feel like a success in the United States.
   The native of Madrid, Spain, says success will only be his in
America when he's listed in the pop sections of record stores
instead of being filed under ``foreign vocalists.''
   To this end, his new record for Columbia, ``Non Stop,'' is his
second done completely in English, and concerts on his current tour
include more singing in English.
   Another essential for success for Iglesias is that he feel goose
bumps of excitement at least once in a concert.
   ``If I don't get goose bumps, I get a very bad critique the next
day,'' he said.
   ``Sometimes on stage you don't reach people. You feel frustrated,
more than you can imagine. Sometimes they understand you. I prefer
goose bumps in the audience for two seconds more than 10 standing
ovations. Standing ovations can be provoked by three or four people
standing in front of the others. Goose bumps you feel, if you have
it, on your own.''
   His biggest hits in the United States have been duets: ``To All
the Girls I've Loved Before'' sung with Willie Nelson, and ``All of
Me'' with Diana Ross. Iglesias had intended not to do anymore, but
when Stevie Wonder wrote ``My Love'' for him, he couldn't resist
asking the composer to sing it with him.
   ``He came to my hotel room in Los Angeles with a little piano,''
said Iglesias, who had met Wonder at the Grammy Awards. ``He plays
this song without lyrics, in his own way, because he is a genius. I
said, `This is going to be difficult for me. I don't understand what
you're meaning in this song.'''
   Six months passed and Iglesias asked Wonder to play harmonica on
``Love Is on Our Side Again.'' Wonder also played ``My Love'' with
lyrics, and Iglesias started to work on it. ``It's not easy to sing.
The harmonies are even difficult for Stevie.
   ``The title `My Love' sounds superficial,'' he said. ``I think it
has the most beautiful words I ever sang. It's the first time I
think Stevie talks so directly about this disenfranchised situation.
He means people who are born without the opportunities of others.
   ``A Latino man and black man singing together _ it's a song to
put people together. We live in the moon sometimes; we need to get
back to reality.
   ``We're going to record it in Spanish, Italian and French. Stevie
has a musical sense of language. He can reach it phonetically, the
accent and everything.''
   Iglesias' 1988 tour, currently hitting 18 American cities,
already has taken him to South America, China, Japan, Australia, the
Philippines and Korea. On July 13, he goes to Europe and will return
to the United States on Sept. 14 for four additional concerts.
   In China, a two-hour TV concert was aired, the first there of a
Western performer.
   ``For me, it was one of the best experiences of my life, if not
the best one,'' Iglesias said.
   Iglesias is surprisingly unslick on stage, holding his microphone
in his left hand, reaching across himself with his right hand to tug
on his suit jacket, seeming hurt when shouts in Spanish request that
he cut the English. Women love him.
   ``I feel uncomfortable when they say sexy,'' Iglesias says. ``I
think after 20 years I proved my talent.''
   Though he is called the world's most popular singer, with
recordings in six languages and No. 1 hits in more than 90
countries, Iglesias said that two years ago he went to a
psychiatrist every day.
   ``I became crazier than I was,'' he said. ``I developed
depression and psychosomatic problems. But I went away from that.
Now I'm back. I don't need sleeping pills. I'm OK except I smoke too
much. I can't quit.''
   Learning English was difficult for the 44-year-old singer, who
started learning the language when he was 38. ``That's too old for
everything, I think, for a man,'' he said.
   ``When I go on stage now, I'm very happy. I think I can sing in
English, good or bad, like I sing in English all my life.
   ``Before, even when I used to do interviews, it took me seconds
to understand the question, translate it to Spanish, translate my
answer into English. At the end of the conversation, the writer was
also crazy.''
   Iglesias has been divorced since 1979 from Spanish journalist
Isabel Preysler, and has two sons and a daughter. Asked whether he
might marry again, he says, ``At my age it would have to be a
perfect combination between brains and feelings. To share a life in
an emotional way is not enough now. It doesn't mean I'm against
marriage. Maybe tomorrow I will get married.''
   His children have lived with him for the last three years, after
living with their mother.
   ``I'm a bad father,'' he said, because he has explained to his
children that singing comes first. ``They know there is nothing more
important in my life than my public. They have to understand I have
a life which is my work that would never take a second position in
my life.
   ``They know I care like crazy about them. I share with them as
much as I can physically, because I have a very busy life.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 17-19</NOTE>
