<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Panfish</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7^^</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the first day out on the bank with a cane
pole and wiggly worms to those days of ``serious'' fishing with
artificial bait and dreams of a wallhanger, sunfish provide
unequalled sport.
   They also are delicious!
   They can be caught on almost any kind of tackle, ranging from a
stick and string with hook and worm, to the most delicately balanced
fly rod and hand-tied flies.
   The most common of the sunfish family is the bluegill, or bream,
which is found all across the country. Other species include the
redear, or shellcracker; the warmouth; the rock bass; the green
sunfish; the redbreast; and the longear sunfish or pumpkinseed.
   The bluegill, which has a distinctive blue ear behind the
gillcover, is native to the Mississippi River drainage area, but it
has been introduced into virtually every lake, river and pond from
coast to coast and as far north as it can survive the winter.
   While bragging size 'gills are usually considered to be anything
hand size or bigger, and heavier than three-quarters of a pound, a
few get to be real wall-hangers. The world record is 4 pounds, 12
ounces, caught in 1950 in Alabama's Ketona Lake.
   Light tackle is best for bluegills, whether it is on a pole or
rod.
   Cane poles or light spinning gear are fine bluegill tackle. The
great little fighter is super sport on a fly rod.
   The best time for bluegills is the spring and early summer, when
they are on the beds. Males guard the eggs in nests which look like
plates in the sand in shallow water. They will attack almost
anything thrown to them.
   There may not be a ``best'' bait for bluegills, but crickets,
nightcrawlers and red wiggler worms all are excellent.
   Many first-time anglers make the mistake of running the hook the
length of the worm, or hooking the worm so many times it hangs in a
glob. The advantage to live bait is that it moves.
   Hook a worm through the body one to three times, leaving plenty
of the ends free to wiggle and attract fish.
   It's not necessary to hide the point of the hook.
   Crickets can be kept for days, possibly weeks, in a wire cage
with a piece of potato or fruit, or some water-soaked bread to
provide moisture.
   To hook the cricket so it will both attract fish, yet be
difficult for small fish to remove without being hooked, insert the
hook into the cricket's soft tail, up through the body and just
barely through the throat.
   The bluegill usually will take the cricket head first, and the
hook with it.
   Use 2-to-8-pound test line with a snall hook, such as a No. 8,
tied on. Don't use a swivel. Put a small split shot 6 inches to a
foot above the hook and attach a small bobber to your line high high
enough above the bait to keep it about six inches off the bottom.
Adjust the bobber position to find the right depth.
   The key is a small bobber the fish can pull under.
   For fly fishermen, the adage ``match the hatch'' still holds
true. Small popping bugs also are excellent lures.
   Find a tree along the bank where insects are congregated and
falling into the water. There you will find hungry bluegills that
will hit almost anything.
   Bluegills usually get into gear when the water temperature rises
above 80 degrees. In reasonably clear water, you can see the beds.
To find the big bluegills, look in 6 to 15 feet of water a few yards
away. The nests usually can't be seen in the deeper water, but a
depth finder will find the fish.
   Try fishing around moss beds, underwater humps, near lilypads or
in standing timber. Big bluegills on their beds will hit small
spinnerbaits dressed with grubs.
   In the summer, fish around docks, fallen trees or in standing
timber. Bluegills also are found off steep banks and just off the
rocky shoulders of dams.
   To keep your fish fresh for excellent eating, lay them on a bed
of ice in your cooler. Cook them any way you like and the fun of
fishing will be followed by a gastronomic delight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
