<DOCNO> AP880606-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0003EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:FlyFishing     06-06 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Fly Fishing,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Fly Fishing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY703</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSWELL, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe has been born again.
   My long-time bait-castin' buddy was standing hip deep in the
little rapids, whipping bits of fur and feather under the willow
branches overhanging a quiet pool.
   He's become a fly fisherman.
   Fly fishing long has been considered an elite level of angling.
It's highly effective, not only for trout, but for bass and a whole
assortment of panfish.
   Heavy-duty rigs also have been devised for ocean fish that tip
the scale in three figures.
   One caution. Fly fishing is not for everyone. If you get past the
beginner stage, it becomes addictive. If you catch a really good
fish on a fly rod, you never want to catch one any other way again,
Joe warned me.
   Knowing that, if you want to get started in fly fishing, there
are two ways: go to a school or teach yourself. There also is an
assortment of books and videos to help.
   There are some simple tips to start in fly fishing.
   Unlike baitcasting or spinfishing, where the lure carries the
line, flyfishing uses the line to carry an almost weightless fly.
   The fly is attached to a nearly invisible tippet, which the fish
can't see. The rig allows the bit of fluff to settle gently on the
water, as if it fell off a branch just above the bank.
   The line, which can be either a sinking or floating line, does
most of the work, whipping back and forth in a delicate arc, carying
the fly to the fish.
   So buy a good line!
   An average rod can cast a good line, but the best of rods won't
cast a cheap line properly.
   Lines are measured by weight, based on the weight in grains for
the first 30 feet of line after the front taper. Weights range from
No. 2 to No. 13.
   Lines and rods should match each other to assure proper casting.
   Start with an 8-foot, 5- or 6-weight rod from a reputable maker.
You can get a good quality graphite rod for $50 or less. Fiberglass
rods cost about half that.
   The ultimate rod is hand-made of split bamboo, but don't worry
about one of those until you are good enough to really appreciate it.
   As you get started, a moderately priced reel is sufficient. Its
sole function early in the learning process is to store line not in
use.
   Read your books, study your videos and practice, practice,
practice.
   Remember, you're not whipping a team of horses. Learn the basic
movement of bringing the rod hand forward from the back cast before
you break your wrist in the power stroke.
   When you're ready to try your skill on fish, go to a tackle shop
that caters to fly fishermen for advice on flies. The adage in fly
fishing is ``match the hatch.'' Pick flies which resemble whatever
insects are flitting around and falling into the water, or hatching
from the bottom of the area you plan to fish.
   Finally, begin your fly fishing career where you have some room.
Flies tangle in branches just as easily as crankbaits hang up in
bushes. Pick a stream that's wadeable in hip boots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Fishhooks     06-06 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Fishhooks,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Fishhooks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY704</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Professional anglers will tell you, sharp hooks
are critical to catching fish.
   There are several ways to sharpen hooks, but they basically are
variables on two themes _ a tapered point and a designed point. You
can go either way, but sharpen every hook one way or the other.
   There are mechanical sharpeners which will produce needle points
that are needle sharp.
   ``The needle is the natural shape in nature. If it weren't the
best way to puncture, animals wouldn't have evolved needle-shaped
incisor teeth,'' according to Doug Hannon, who recommends the Hook
Hone, a battery operated sharpener.
   It puts a needle-sharp point on any hook in seconds.
   John Juranitch, president of Razor Edge Systems, edge consultants
from Ely, Minn., recommends the designed hook, with three cutting
edges which cut into the bone of a fish's jaw. A three-sided point,
with a flat face on the stem side of the point, ``attacks any
surface it touches,'' he said.
   He recommends sharpening the three faces to create the three
sharp cutting edges.
   In addition, Juranitch said, it is critical that the point of the
hook face the direction of travel. The point should be in line with
the shank of the hook, not curved in toward it, or pointed to a side.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0003EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Houstons     06-06 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Houstons,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Houstons</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sherri Houston-Combs grew up in a bass boat and now, as a
professional angler, she is trying to outgrow the shadows of her
parents, two of the nation's top bass fishing pros.
   ``I'm just extremely proud of her,'' said her mother, Chris
Houston, six-time Bass'n Gal Angler of the Year and a member of the
National Fishing Hall of Fame.
   ``Chris is definitely a better fisherman than I am, and I'm not
so sure Sherri isn't too,'' said her father, Jimmy Houston, two-time
Bass Anglers Sportsman Society Angler of the Year and host of the
nationally syndicated ``Jimmy Houston Outdoor'' televsion show.
   Last year was the first time Chris and Sherri faced each other in
the Bass'n Gal Classic, the championship of women's bass fishing.
Chris finished fifth and Sherri 17th.
   ``We're competing against each other, but yet we're not. We're
always pulling for each other, helping each other out,'' Sherri
said. ``We spent one whole morning fishing around and around the
same hole. She was catching keepers. Mine, I had to throw back.''
   Sherri has finished ahead of her mother ``five, maybe six
times,'' in 3{ seasons on the Bass'n Gal trail, but the two never
have battled it out for one place in the standings.
   ``It seems we're far enough apart, either she's ahead, or I'm
ahead, that we can work together,'' Chris said. ``I don't think
we've ever fished one place in front of the other. We've always been
four or five places apart''
   That allows cooperation without confrontation, with the help
going to the one who has the best chance to finish high.
   ``We team up to help the leader,'' Chris said. ``We had one
tournament a few years back where she had just a slim chance to make
the Classic. I had one little bank where I had caught my fish. I let
her have that bank the next day, hoping she would catch something.
   ``We do stuff like that quite frequently. She shares with me and
I share with her. In practice, we can combine information. We can
cover a lot more water that way.''
   Sherri, 24, said she started fishing because ``I've grown up with
it. Dad started fishing professionally when I was 4 or 5 years old.''
   ``Mom and dad have not really pushed a lot on me. When I was a
kid, I'd take coloring books or comics or read or sleep or
whatever,'' while her parents fished. ``If I'd concentraced more on
fishing then, I might know a lot more now. I'm sure there's a lot of
newcomers to Bass'n Gal who know a lot more than I do.''
   ``I fished my first tournament a month after I turned 16. You
have to be 16 to fish Bass'n Gal,'' she said. In the following
years, fishing competed with college, marriage and, in 1986, son
Jeremy.
   She qualified for the Classic for the first time in 1987.
   She said she doesn't feel any resentment from other anglers on
the trail because of her family name.
   ``Most of them sort of treat me like another daughter. I've been
around Bass'n Gal from the very beginning,'' she said.
   A lot of the others team up in practice just the way she and her
mother do, so that's not a particular advantage, she said.
   The one advantage, she said, is the family name has helped her
accumulate sponsors, a vital part of professional fishing.
``Sometimes we work a package deal,'' Sherri said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
