<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Martin     06-06 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Martin,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Martin</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY705</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roland Martin danced a spinnerbait to the top of
the bass fishing world, but the professional angler said the key to
catching fish, and winning tournaments, is confidence in your
fishing pattern.
   ``You've got to believe in your patterns. Once you've set up your
patterns, water temperature, water clarity, that you're dealing
with, whatever the pH or sun condition might be, you have to believe
in the pattern and not deviate,'' he said. ``In a big lake, there's
maybe 100 pattern combinations.''
   Martin makes his living on Lake Okeechobee, the largest lake in
Florida.
   ``Once you catch a fish on a spinnerbait, you've got to examine
everything, because the next one will be in that exact set of
conditions,'' he said in an interview.
   Those conditions include everything from water condition to type
of cover, water depth and relationship to deep water.
   Martin said the key to fishing, particularly in the spring, is
water temperature. He used Lake Lanier, a big reservoir northeast of
Atlanta where he won a Bass Anglers Sportsman Society tournament in
March 1984, as an example.
   ``In bigger lakes, there can be a tremendous variance in water
temperature,'' he said. ``You can have up to 15 degree differences
from a warm, shallow, muddy cove to a deep clear cove by the dam.''
   ``The one tournament I won at Lanier was in March and it was
basically won in the warmest water I could find,'' Martin said.
   He won it by taking an opportunity, changing his place, not his
pattern.
   ``The easiest tip that I have in spinnerbait fishing is to be an
opportunist,'' Martin said. ``Take the best opportunity. Go for the
warmest water you can find. It is generally the best opportunity.''
   Look north for warm water.
   ``In this hemisphere, normally the high-pressure winds blow from
the south, good nice winds, and that normally pushes the warm water
up the northern creek fingers'' of a lake.
   ``The little creeks that run to the north are usually five to 10
degrees warmer than the creeks just across the cove with the
southern exposure because that water is being pushed out of there
and being replaced by the colder, deeper water,'' Martin said. ``In
just a quarter of a mile, you can find five or 10 degrees difference
in water temperature.''
   The pattern that won Martin his Lanier tournament was ``trees and
logs in fairly dingy water. When it got down to the last afternoon,
everywhere I wanted to go there was a boat. I had to make one
supreme gamble.''
   The gamble was to go to one of several spots that fit the pattern.
   ``I had seen three pockets I had never fished that had boat
docks, had stumps, had the right temperature of water because I'd
already checked them out,'' he said.
   ``I had 10 minutes left. I needed one more good fish, three or
four pounds,'' Martin said. ``I motored into a little pocket. There
was a log and an old Christmas tree laying there in the back of a
pocket by the boat dock in this little warm spot, about 65 degrees.
   ``I took the jig and I sailed it over there and the jig settled
about a foot and the water blew out and I hit the big old fish, and
he's towing this Christmas tree all over the cove.
   ``I had to pull the whole Christmas tree in. I reached down in
the water and grabbed him. He weighed 8 pounds, 5 ounces, and I won
the tournament by 6 pounds.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
