<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:DuckHunting     06-06 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Duck Hunting,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Duck Hunting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlook for ducks is dismal.
   There is a real possibility there may be major cuts in the duck
season this fall.
   While the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service is not making any
predictions about summer breeding success and fall hunting
regulations yet, conditions on the Canadian prairies are near
disastrous.
   ``I guess the real story is (the Canadian provinces of) Alberta,
Saskatchewan and Manitoba are drier than any of our field people
have ever seen them,'' said Rollin Sparrow, chief of the FWS Office
of Migratory Bird Management.
   He commented in a telephone interview after making a personal
tour of the Canadian prairies in late May.
   ``We have got to face the possibility it will be worse then '85
when some North American duck populations went lower than we'd ever
seen before,'' Sparrow said.
   Ducks must have water to breed and rear their young. Ever since
the last ice age, the prairie potholes of the Upper Midwest and the
Canadian prairie provinces have been the primary duck factories of
North America.
   As farming has become increasingly big business, more and more of
the potholes have been drained. The continent is in a drought cycle
that has run through most of the '80s, drying up still more potholes.
   The plows which had to stay out of the water, and the muddy land
around it, have chewed through the now dry weeds and brush.
   ``We have seen the situation deterioriating since last year,''
Sparrow said. ``After a good eight years of on-again, off-again
drought, and some slight improvements in populations in 1986 and
1987, it looks like breeding conditions have taken a turn for the
worse.''
   Last fall, ``farmers were telling us of dry conditions they
hadn't seen in their lifetimes,'' he said.
   Then came an extremely dry winter.
   Then came the spring surveys of the breeding grounds.
   ``It's already apparent, although we're not through the surveys,
we're finding a very dramatic deterioriation from last year,
although last year was well below normal,'' Sparrow said.
   ``There are quite a few transects that have virtually zeroed out,
no ducks to be seen in these spring surveys.''
   Ground crews double-checking aerial surveys confirmed the
results. ``One area that last year had 66 wetlands had seven. Last
year it had 145 ducks. This year it had 10. Generally the reports
from all across the prairie are of deterioriation of this
magnitude,'' Sparrow said.
   Many ducks apparently have continued on north, to some areas in
the extreme northern prairies that have some water.
   ``They're concentrated in abnormally large concentrations,''
Sparrow said. ``We don't know whether they're going to breed. We
just didn't find many mallards and very few pintails in the prairie
transects.''
   Mallards and pintails are the most common and most sought-after
duck species.
   Normally those species disperse across the prairies to breed.
When they are concentrated they either don't try to breed or the
survival rate for the young is very low.
   Either way, it means a very small number of ducks flying south to
the United States for the winter.
   Even though the focus is on the drought, Sparrow said, the real
story is the destruction of the breeding habitat.
   ``It's really astounding how much the natural wetlands have been
modified; first the borders around the ponds then, if the ponds stay
dry long enough, the farmers are able to plow through the whole
wetland basin,'' he said.
   Those wetlands don't recover in just one wet year.
   ``In one wet year, you just have a dish full of water, you don't
have habitat,'' Sparrow said. ``Ducks can't utilize a pond in the
middle of a plowed field, with no vegetation, no cover, no food.''
   Without cover, brush and weeds, nests are food on the table for
predators.
   It takes several wet years for a dry pothole to recover enough to
produce broods of ducks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
