<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Sharpening     06-06 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Sharpening,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Sharpening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAINBRIDGE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lot more people are cut with dull knives
than with sharp ones.
   That's because people tend to force dull knives through the
material they are cutting and that leads to slips and trips to a
hospital.
   John Juranitch, president of Razor Edge Systems Inc., Ely, Minn.,
has been studying cutting edges for years. To demonstrate his
techniques, he will sharpen his double-bladed ax and shave with it.
   To him, sharpening a knife is a two-step process _ tapering the
blade and then sharpening the edge.
   At an old table under a live oak tree, Juranitch taught an
impromptu course in knife sharpening, passing along expertise
learned from years of working with industry, including the meat
processing industry where razor-sharp knives are vital.
   Start with the abrasive, the stone, or hone.
   ``You are going to need an abrasive that will cut quickly to
remove all that unnecessary scrap iron'' on the edge of most knives,
he said. ``Use a truly coarse man-made stone, not a `coarse' natural
stone because the natural stone isn't coarse enough.
   ``Keep the greasy kid stuff off it, as it is just another old
wives tale,'' he said. ``If your stone is already oil logged, clean
it with hot water and detergent.''
   Hold your knife an angle just a few degrees of the coarse hone
and work it in a circular motion.
   Notice the grind marks where the hone is grinding on the blade.
``When these furrows reach the edge, they'll form a burr. When
you've got the burr, turn the knife over and repeat the process on
the other side,'' Juranitch said.
   The grind marks can be worked out with a natural ``coarse''
stone, but it's not necessary.
   That tapers the blade.
   Now the knife is ready to sharpen.
   The critical thing in sharpening the knife is precise angle.
   ``It doesn't matter what precise angle you use, although you
can't sharpen at 90 degrees and get an edge. But it must be
something like 25 degrees to get a decent cutting edge. Your better
edge will come with less pitch.
   ``It doesn't matter, just so the knife is held exactly at that
angle on each stroke,'' he said.
   Stroke the blade down the coarse hone, like you were slicing a
thin sliver off the stone, until you get a light burr. Turn to the
other side and repeat the process.
   ``Then go to the fine hone, stroke toward the cutting edge with
your edge approximately perpendicular to the line of stroke, then
you get an acceptable edge,'' Juranitch said.
   Keep working until the edge is as sharp as you want it. Then
refine the edge.
   Reset your knife a little deeper into the holder, increasing the
angle between knife and hone slightly, and make several more slicing
strokes down the fine hone on each side of the blade.
   ``If you want to increase the value of the edge more than that,
then you go to a very fine steel,'' Juranitch said.
   ``Using just the weight of the knife itself, run it down the
steel once on one side and once on the other with an angle just
slightly sharper than you had on the fine hone.
   ``Once you have this edge, you can skin out a deer or bear and if
you have a proper steel with you, and use it once in a while, your
edge should be as razor sharp at the end of the day as when you
started.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Backyard     06-06 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Backyard,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Backyard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You don't have to go into the woods to enjoy
viewing wildlife. You can attract a wide variety of wildlife to your
yard with a little planning and planting.
   All animals need food, water and shelter. Trees are a good place
to start. Pick varieties that produce fruits, berries or nuts and
plant different varieties that produce those foods at different
times of the year.
   The U.S. Forest Service suggests the following varieties by
region:
   South _ live oak, black gum, American holly and flowering dogwood.
   Southwest _ pinyon pine, live oak, box elder and mesquite.
   West Coast _ dogwood, hawthorne, serviceberry, black oak, Douglas
fir and Ponderosa pine.
   Your local nursery, the Forest Service or your county
agricultural extension agent all can help select varieties for your
yard.
   Birds are either fruit and seed eaters or meat-eaters.
   Orioles, vireos, warblers, chickadees, nuthatches and woodpeckers
like mature trees with large insect populations. The robin needs a
lawn with plenty of worms.
   To encourage robins and other ground feeders, water your lawn
regularly. Many species of birds love to bathe in the spray and a
well-watered lawn helps provide a good supply of both worms and
insects. It also provides mud for robins and eaves swallows to build
nests.
   If possible, let one corner of the yard grow wild with weeds and
bushes. You also can pile brush or old Christmas trees in a back
corner to create cover for both birds and small mammals, including
rabbits and ground squirrels.
   If you have alders, birches, pines, oaks, dogwoods or other
seed-producing trees, you can bet you will have squirrels.
   Seed-eating birds and flower-seeking birds often need help to
survive in the city.
   Princessfeather, asters, rockpurslanes, blessed thistle,
California poppies, cosmos, marigold, sunflowers, tarweed,
forget-me-not, portucala, silene, zinnas and varieties of sorghum
grow large quantiites of seeds and won't become yard pests.
   Fruit-bearing trees and shrubs are popular with birds and
squirrels.
   More than 100 species of birds will throng to raspberry,
blackberry and elderberry bushes. Other popular species are juniper,
red cedar, bayberry, mulberry, pokeberry, strawberry, sumack,
grapevines and blueberry. They will bring woodpeckers, waxwings,
cardinals, bluebirds, orioles, warblers, robins, flickers and
finches.
   Hummingbirds are the best-known flower seekers.
   They are very fond of cultivated flowers, particularly those with
red, orange or purple petals. Varieties include daylilies, lilies,
canas, morning-glories, petunias, honeysuckles, jewelweed and
trumpetcreeper.
   In summer, the best way to bring birds and other animals is to
provide water. In dry weather, it can mean life or death.
   A bird bath a few inches deep with the bottom sloping gradually
upward toward the edge is one of the best bets. Make sure the bottom
and the edge are rough to provide good footing. Change the water
regularly.
   Make sure it is elevated because a bird bath on the ground can be
a happy hunting ground for the local feline population.
   In winter, food is a magnet.
   A feeder can be as simple as a Christmas tree, decorated with
popcorn or cranberries. It's best to offer several birdfeeders with
different delicacies in each.
   Place the feeders near trees or shrubs, particularly evergreens.
Many species will stay hungry rather than fly from cover to a bare
post in the middle of the yard.
   Different species prefer different foods. Cardinals and blue jays
like sunflower seeds. Goldfinches like thistles. Sparrows and
juncoes like cracked corn. All the insect eaters, such as
woodpeckers, nuthatches and chickadees, love suet, the waste fat
from beef.
   Avoid bagged, mixed bird seed. Many brands, particularly cheaper
ones, contain varieties songbirds don't eat. Often it is cheaper to
buy one large bag each of several varieties of seed and put each
seed in a different feeder.
   Keep an area under an eave or overhanging tree branch clear of
show and scatter seed for groundfeeders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Wildlife     06-06 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Wildlife,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Wildlife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   American hunters and fishermen pay the majority of the cost of
wildlife conservation in the United States, according to recent
figures.
   This year, for example, a record $265 million in taxes paid by
hunters, fishermen and boaters will be made available to help
finance state fish and wildlife restoration programs.
   ``Once again, hunters and fishermen have made record
contributions to state fish and wildlife restoration efforts through
the federal excise taxes they pay on hunting and fishing eqipment,''
said Secretary of the Interior Don Hodel.
   Those restoration efforts provide and protect habitat _ for
nongame animals as well as the game animals sportsmen pursue. For
example, whooping cranes, the most endangered of the world's 15
species of cranes, winter on national wildlife refuges financed by
waterfowl huters.
   ``This investment by hunters, fishermen and supporting industries
results in many wildlife enhancement activities that will benefit
all Americans,'' said Frank Dunkle, director of the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service.
   The two major federal program are the Pittman-Robertson program,
which is financed by an 11 percent excise tax on sporting arms and
ammunition and certain archery equipment, and a 10 percent tax on
handguns.
   Fisheries and boating projects are financed by the
Dingell-Johnson, Wallop-Breaux programs, which place a 10 percent
tax on most fishing tackle and other taxes on other gear used to go
fishing.
   In addition the ``duck stamp'' which must be purchased by hunters
seeking migratory waterfowl, brings in millions of dollars each year
to finance the National Wildlife Refuge System.
   A study by the Wildlife Conservation Fund of America found
hunters, fishermen and trappers paid $1.1 million in license fees in
1986 _ or 53.4 percent of the revenue collected by state wildlife
and fisheries agencies. Federal payments to these agencies _ the
return of sportsmen's excise taxes _ contributed another 17.1
percent.
   ``Other revenue'' accounted for 13.4 percent of the wildife
agencies budgets. That included voluntary contributions by
individual sportsmen as well as the large sums raised by
conservation groups, such as Ducks Unlimited, the Foundation for
North American Wild Sheep, the National Wild Turkey Federation, the
Ruffed Grouse Society and scores of others.
   General fund revenue was 14.2 percent and the rest was interest
income.
   But, the study noted, sportsmen directly pay a percentage of the
general fund revenue as part of their hunting and fishing
activities. A large portion of state revenues is generated by the
sales tax and sportsmen pay sales tax on every rod, reel, boat,
rifle, shotgun and piece of outdoor gear they buy for hunting or
fishing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Hunting-Glasses     06-06 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Hunting-Glasses,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Hunting-Glasses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hunters who wear glasses may need a little extra help from their
optometrist when it comes to keeping their vision on target.
   According to the American Optometric Association, regular
eyeglasses may do more harm than good for hunters because the
prescription may not be set high enough in the lens for sighting the
gun.
   Also, the association says, glasses with small lenses or thick
frames and wide temple pieces can hamper side vision, which is used
to detect motion.
   However, it adds, hunters who tell their optometrist about their
sport can get frames and lenses specially suited for hunting and may
also pick up a few tips that will not only help them see game better
against the brush, grass or sky but help them safely aim and hit
that game.
   For example, hunters are advised to consider yellow-tinted lenses
because dim sunlight reduces contrast between the game and its
surroundings due to the amount of blue light in the spectrum _ and
yellow lenses filter out blue light and increase contrast.
   Other suggestions include:
   _ Use a telescopic sight after 40. (With a regular gun sight,
hunters must focus from the back sight to the front sight to the
target in a fraction of a second. But hunters who are over 40 find
it increasingly difficult to focus on the back sight. The telescopic
sight helps by providing a close, clear look at the target.)
   _ Protect the eyes from powder burns, spent shell casings,
branches, flying shot and other debris by wearing safety goggles, or
use prescription safety eyeglasses, which can better withstand such
an impact.
   _ Wear hunter orange, because just as important as seeing is
being seen for safe hunting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:FishContest     06-06 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Fish Contest,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Fish Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMM, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court has fined two organizers of a
fishing contest about $700 each for cruelty to animals, ruling that
fish feel pain when hooked and pulled from the water.
   The April 18 decision grew out of a suit filed by an animal
rights group against a local angling club that staged a fishing
contest two years ago.
   The object of the contest was to see which fisherman could catch
the most pounds of fish in two days. After the fish were pulled in
and weighed, they were returned to the water.
   Civil court Judge Horst Brinkmann based his decision on testimony
of experts called in to determine whether or not fish feel pain when
hooked, and if they suffered during the time they were out of the
water.
   Four wildlife experts testified that an increased heart rate and
labored breathing of the fish after they were pulled from the water
indicated that they feel pain.
   Brinkmann ruled that fishing was permissible if fish were quickly
killed, and if they were caught for useful purposes. But he added
that simply catching the fish to weigh and determine which angler
was more skilled subjected the creatures to unusually cruel
treatment.
   ``Fishing contests serve no further purpose than to determine who
has won,'' Brinkmann ruled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:Travel     06-06 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: Travel,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: Travel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A travel group has predicted that Americans
will set new records in travel this summer, with the majority taking
a car, truck or camper to a vacation spot less than 250 miles from
home.
   The U.S. Travel Data Center, in its annual projection of summer
vacations, said the Southeast will remain the most popular
destination, while the Midwest and Great Lakes regions, which are in
the midst of an economic recovery, will generate the biggest
increase in vacation travelers.
   Cities, the data center said, will edge out oceans and beaches
this year as the preferred destination.
   Suzanne Cook, director of the data center, said the traditional
summer vacation _ ``where the parents take the kids on a three-week
summer vacation'' _ is no longer the model for many American
households, where more women work and have less time to take long
trips.
   ``We're finding that people are taking more shorter trips
throughout the year and not just one long summer vacation,'' Cook
said.
   It estimated that Americans will take 136 million vacation trips
during June, July and August, up 3 percent from the 132 million
trips last summer. Cook said the 1987 travel rate was a record.
   The travel data center, a private, non-profit group that promotes
travel, developed its forecast from the results of monthly telephone
interviews of 1,500 adults. Cook said the margin of error in the
survey is plus or minus 2 percentage points.
   The center found that nearly a third of those responding to its
survey _ 31 percent _ said they planned to visit a city, while 26
percent said they would go to an ocean or beach. That is exactly the
opposite of the results for the 1987 survey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Outdoors:RVs     06-06 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Outdoors: RVs,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>OUTDOORS: RVs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY700</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The sliding dollar, a plentiful gas supply and the ``graying of
America'' all may be contributing a new look to the nation's travel
patterns, according to tourism officials.
   With travel abroad generally becoming more expensive, indications
are that many Americans plan driving trips in the United States for
their summer vacations, taking shorter but more frequent vacations.
   ``Today's predominantly dual-income families often have more
disposable income, but they have less time for extended travel
because of conflicting schedules,'' explains David Humphreys,
president of the Recreation Vehicle Industry Association.
   Large inventories of crude oil are expected to keep supplies high
and prices at or below last year's levels, according to the American
Automobile Association, which reports an increase in requests for
tour books and maps, indicating an expanding interest in domestic
destinations.
   Overnight visits to national parks _ 40 percent of which are by
RVs _ were up 7 percent in 1987, and officials predict overall
visits will continue to climb this year.
   ``Following two years of strong showings, the National Park
Service is again expecting increased visitations,'' notes tourism
director Priscilla Baker.
   ``We're anticipating more domestic travelers primarily because of
Americans' renewed appreciation of the outdoors as well as the high
cost of European travel.''
   Early reservations for RV rentals by foreign visitors to the
United States are reported up 100 percent over 1987 by Cruise
America, a Miami-based RV rental firm. At the same time, domestic
reservations are up 50 percent, says Bob Caldarone, the company's
marketing director.
   ``The obvious lure to European travelers is the weakened dollar
because it's making U.S. vacations especially affordable,'' he says.
``But efforts of travel and tourism organizations to make travelers
more aware of RV rental options are really paying off, too.''
   Some industry observers note the ``graying of America'' _ an
increase in the retiree population _ is helping boost RV sales
because older people have the greatest amount of time and
discretionary income to spend on such vehicles, and they enjoy
camping out.
   Humphreys, of the industry association, estimates that the RV
industry directly contributes $7 billion to $8 billion annually to
the U.S. economy through retail sales of new units, plus another
$6.5 billion generated through the used and rental markets and the
sales of parts, accessories and services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
