during May on the strength of new orders, according to a survey of
purchasing managers.
   The National Association of Purchasing Managers, a trade group
with about 30,000 members, said Sunday its index of economic
activity rose to 55.1 percent last month from 54.9 percent in April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment increased for the first time this
year to 5.6 percent in May, the Labor Department said. But both
government officials and private economists cautioned Friday the job
figures for last month are too unreliable to suggest that the
economy is losing steam.
   The 0.2 percentage point increase from April's 14-year-low
civilian jobless rate of 5.4 percent reflected a seasonally adjusted
shrinking of the U.S. labor force by 363,000 people, with 536,000
fewer Americans at work.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestic cars and trucks picked up in
late May despite lower incentive offers and rose 14.8 percent over
the same period a year ago, auto companies said.
   The automakers reported Friday that for the month of May, U.S.
sales of all cars and light trucks _ imported and domestic _ were up
10.8 percent from May 1987. Domestic vehicle sales improved 15.8
percent, while import sales fell 3.1 percent from a year ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Carl C. Icahn's multibillion-dollar bid
for Texaco Inc. has failed to gain ground, with Wall Street
remaining unmoved by his latest attempt to drum up support from
investors.
   In an analysts' meeting late Thursday, Icahn, Texaco's largest
shareholder, gave the first details of how he would finance the
proposed acquisition and said he was certain he would have no
trouble getting the money.
   But the oil giant's stock stayed around the $50 level Friday _ or
$10 below Icahn's offer _ where it had hovered since the bid was
announced.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Electronic Data Systems Corp. criticized its
founder, H. Ross Perot, for luring eight executives away just one
day after a moratorium against such recruiting expired.
   ``We're just disappointed he did it,'' Bill Wright, a spokesman
for EDS, which is now a subsidiary of General Motors Corp, said
Friday.
   Perot announced the formation of a new company, Perot Systems
Corp., which included three EDS corporate officers and five of the
company's divisional managers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The broadest measure of Japan's trade surplus shrank
12.7 percent in April from its level of a year earlier as imports
climbed 30 percent to record levels, according to government figures.
   The current account, which covers trade in merchandise as well as
services and investment income, posted a $7.12 billion surplus, down
from $8.15 billion surplus a year earlier and an $8.12 billion
surplus in March, the Finance Ministry said Friday.
</TEXT>
