<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-06 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar and Gold Fall in Early European Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against all major currencies in
early European trading today on West German opposition to a higher
dollar and a growing belief that a rise in U.S. interest rates is
improbable.
   Gold prices were also lower.
   Traders in Milan said declining fears of a rise in U.S. inflation
had made the prospect of an increase in U.S. interest rates less
likely.
   ``Much of the dollar's strength last week was based on the
expectation of the Federal Reserve increasing interest rates,'' said
one Milan trader.
   Karl Otto Poehl, president of the West German Bundesbank, said
Sunday in a radio interview the central bank had sold dollars last
week to show it wasn't interested in a higher dollar and a lower
mark.
   But another trader in Milan said sentiment remained strong for
the dollar.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.04 yen to a closing 126.07 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 126.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.7184 West German marks, down from 1.7248; 1.4360
Swiss francs, down from 1.4363; 5.8160 French francs, down from
5.8293; 1.9298 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9355; 1,278.75 Italian
lire, down from 1,282.00; 1.2305 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2311.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8005, unchanged
from Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $464.40 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $464.10. Both were down from late Friday's bid
of $464.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $463.80, down from $465.50 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose to $464.39 from Saturday's
$463.71.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $7.26 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $7.31.
</TEXT>
