<HEAD>Stocks Reach Record High, Dollar Dips In Active Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices climbed almost across the board in
active trading today, driving the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main
barometer momentarily above the 28,000-mark for the first time. The
dollar declined slightly against the Japanese yen.
   After passing 28,000, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues then declined slightly, closing the day up 89.76 points, or
0.32 percent, for a record 27,996.24.
   When investors saw the Nikkei index top 28,000, said one trader,
they may have thought ``this is a good time to take profits.''
   However, traders said market sentiment remained bullish in heavy
trading. Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 1.6
billion shares.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 126.07
yen, down 0.04 yen from Friday's close. Spot volume totaled $5.67
billion.
   The dollar opened at 126.32 yen and ranged between 126.00 yen and
126.38 yen during the day.
   An official of the Bank of Tokyo, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said there was little market-affecting news.
