<HEAD>London Stocks Marginally Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were marginally higher Monday,
affected little by a half-point increase in the commercial banks'
base lending rate to 8.5 percent.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was up 2
points, or 0.1 percent, at 1,821.2 at midday.
   Volume was a slim 192.5 million shares at midday, compared with
359.6 million at the same time Friday.
   The equities market was little affected by the rate increase
because it had been expecting such a hike.
   The commercial banks, heeding a signal from the Bank of England,
raised their base lending rate effective immediately.
   It was the second increase in the benchmark rate in less than a
week.
   Last Thursday, the central bank signaled a rise in the base rate
to 8 percent from 7.5 percent after the pound dropped sharply on
foreign exchange markets. The base rate increase that followed was
effective Friday.
</TEXT>
