<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ChipsDispute     06-06 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chips Dispute,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Chip Makers Might Ask For New Sanctions Against Japanese</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. makers of semiconductors might ask the
Reagan administration for new sanctions against Japan following the
collapse of talks on foreign access to Japan's chip market,
according to a report published today.
   Chip makers said it is too early to determine what effect the
collapse will have. But Alan Wolff, a lawyer for the Semiconductor
Industry Association, said the group could demand an increase in the
existing $165 million in punitive tariffs if Japan does not import
more chips, the Wall Street Journal reported.
   Talks broke down Friday over a disagreement about how to measure
whether Japan has sufficiently opened its market to foreign-made
chips.
   The Semiconductor Industry Association says Japan should be
buying about 12.5 percent of its chips from the United States. The
actual proportion has declined slightly and is about 10 percent.
   Japanese negotiators say they will not promise a certain share of
the market in advance.
   ``We can't accept the premise that there should be increased
market share. Market share is a result of effort,'' Tohri Sato,
executive managing director of Hitachi Ltd. and co-chairman of the
Japanese delegation, said in a weekend news conference, the Journal
reported.
</TEXT>
