<DOCNO> AP880606-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Brazil     06-06 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Brazil,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks Said Close To Agreement On New Loan To Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consortium of creditor banks from Japan, the
United States and Europe soon will reach agreement with Brazil on a
new loan totaling $5.2 billion, Japanese banking officials said
Monday.
   ``The new loan package (to Brazil) is shaping up in concrete
terms'' in negotiations under way in New York between Brazil and the
Bankers' Advisers Committee, an organization representing Western
and Japanese creditor banks discussing ways to help solve Brazil's
debt problem, said a Bank of Tokyo official involved in the talks.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the new
loan agreement will be ``officially agreed upon in the near future''
by the Brazilian government and committee representatives from 16
leading Western and Japanese banks.
   He declined to provide other details, but the Japanese national
newspaper Sankei Shimbun and Kyodo News Service reported the new
loan would be repayable in 12 years, including a five-year grace
period. The new loan would be used to help Brazil carry out economic
reforms, the news reports said.
   Brazil, the biggest debtor country in the Third World, has been
negotiating with a group of creditor banks, led by Citicorp of the
United States, since it announced in January its readiness to accept
an economic rehabilitation plan offered by the International
Monetary Fund.
   Brazil's current external debts are estimated at more than $109
billion, including about $60 billion owed to Western and Japanese
private banks.
</TEXT>
