<HEAD>Tate & Lyle Sells Off Staley Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tate & Lyle PLC said today it has signed an
agreement to sell off the food service subsidiary of Staley
Continental Inc. to Sysco Corp., a U.S. food distributor, for $700
million in cash.
   Tate & Lyle's $1.5 billion takeover of Staley is expected to be
completed by Tuesday.
   The London-based company had announced its plan to sell Staley's
food-service distribution and manufacturing subsidiary, CFS
Continental, when it launched its takeover bid for Staley on April 8.
   Tate & Lyle officials said today its agreement to sell CFS
Continental to the Houston-based Sysco is subject to normal closing
conditions.
   The $700 million in cash is to be paid on closing day, which is
expected in midsummer, Tate & Lyle said. The cash payment also will
be adjusted to reflect changes in CFS Continental's working capital
and fixed assets since April 30.
   On May 13, Tate & Lyle and Staley signed an agreement to merge
Staley with a wholly owned subisidary of Tate & Lyle. Both companies
are leading producers of sugar.
</TEXT>
