<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 0946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-VDTStudy     06-06 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-VDT Study,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Suggests Relationship Between Terminal Use and Miscarriage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of 1,583 pregnant women in northern
California showed that almost twice as many miscarriages occurred
among those who worked at video display terminals more than 20 hours
a week in the first three months of pregnancy.
   The study, conducted by the Kaiser-Permanente Medical Care
Program of Oakland, Calif., and described over the weekend in the
New York Times, said the findings did not necessarily mean VDTs
caused miscarriages. Working conditions and job-related stress were
among factors not measured in the study.
   Some experts have suggested low-level radiation from VDTs may
alter or disrupt cell development.
   The study called the figures on miscarriages statistically
significant.
   It also said pregnant VDT users were more likely to have children
with birth defects, but not in statistically significant numbers.
   Increased risk of miscarrying was found during both the first
three months and middle three months among woman who worked at VDTs
more than 20 hours a week, the study said. Women who worked at VDTs
less than 20 hours a week had no statistically significant greater
risk.
   The researchers reported their findings in the June issue of the
American Journal of Industrial Medicine and suggested more elaborate
studies were needed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
