   The stock market turned downward today as traders
cashed in some of last week's gains.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 10.84 to 2,060.46
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 10 to 9 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 452 up, 509 down and
448 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 26.11 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Interest rates rose slightly in the government bond market this
morning, reversing last week's sharp decline.
   Analysts said that provided stock traders with an incentive to
sell issues that bounced upward in the market's recent surprise
rally.
   In addition, they said, many investors continued to view the
upswing in share prices skeptically, questioning its prospective
staying power.
   There have been no noteworthy developments of late, the doubters
maintain, to erase the inflation worries and uncertainties about the
election outlook that had been depressing the market until last week.
   MacMillan Inc. climbed 2[ to 73|. The Robert M. Bass Group raised
its takeover bid for the company from $64 a share to $73 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
