<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TimberStrike     06-06 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Timber Strike,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Strike 18 Paper Mills in Pacific Northwest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 4,500 workers in three states were
off the job today in the first major labor action this year against
the timber industry in the Pacific Northwest.
   The strike began at midnight Sunday at 18 mills in Oregon,
Washington and Montana, said Bill Hubbell, president of the
International Woodworkers of America-U.S.
   The strike by the IWA and the Western Council of Industrial
Workers affected 1,300 workers at 10 Willamette Industries Inc.
mills; 2,400 at six Champion International Corp. plants; and 800 at
two mills of DAW Forest Products Co.
   ``We are at a complete negotiating impasse with these companies,
and they refuse to even consider our initial industry settlement,''
said Mike Draper, executive officer with the Western Council.
   Draper referred to a tentative long-term agreement that his union
and the IWA reached last week with Bohemia Lumber Co. in Eugene,
affecting more than 800 workers. The agreement was the first
settlement in the 1988 bargaining year, and the unions planned to
use it as a foundation for future negotiations.
   Bill Latimer, Willamette Industries division manager, declined to
comment on the unions' strike plans Sunday, saying only, ``We'll
just wait and see what happens.''
   Attempts to reach officials at Champion headquarters in
Cincinnati and DAW in Oregon were unsuccessful late Sunday.
   Pickets first began appearing Sunday evening at Champion mills in
Missoula and Bonner, Mont., where 900 union members are employed.
   In Oregon, union negotations with Willamette Industries and DAW
stalled last week with no further talks scheduled.
   The IWA membership voted in April to let their leaders call a
strike if negotations broke down after the contract expired June 1.
   Top journeymen now are paid about $11.50 an hour, although the
average basic wage rate is as low as $9 an hour.
   The company offered a three-year contract with bonuses, according
to Willamette spokeswoman Cathy Baldwin, but unions rejected it.
   Draper said the Bohemia contract the unions have adopted as a
model in their talks restores and in some cases exceeds wages that
were cut in 1986.
   Details of the Bohemia pact will not be made public until after
the ratification vote this week. Sources close to the industry have
described it as a four-year agreement that gives wage increases of 5
percent the first year and 4 percent in each following year.
   Jim Bradbury, director of labor planning for Weyerhaeuser Co.,
based in Tacoma, Wash., said his company would reject provisions of
the Bohemia contract.
   ``We must be competitive with the low-cost independent producers
that are now our primary competition in Western Washington and
Oregon,'' Bradbury said. ``Increases in base pay rates are not
comptatible with this competition and cannot be recovered through
price increases.''
   Negotiations are continuing with Weyerhaeuser and and several
other companies, including Boise Cascade Corp., Simpson Timber Co.
and Pope & Talbot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880606-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Teamsters-Coors     06-06 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters-Coors,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Declares Impasse in Teamsters-Coors Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Teamsters Union has declared an impasse
with the Adolph Coors Co. and will hold an election at the brewery
here in a few weeks, the union's brewery chief said.
   Charles Klare, head of the Teamster's brewery division, said this
weekend the decision followed months of secret talks with Coors
during which the union tried unsuccessfully to get the brewer to
shrink its bargaining unit.
   Employees will vote on whether to be represented by the
Teamsters. In order to call for an election, the union must have
authorization cards signed by at least 30 percent of the workers.
   Klare said the union has had more than enough cards for some
time, but has not scheduled the vote because the size of the
bargaining group is undetermined.
   The unit's size is critical to the success of the vote because
many of the workers Coors may put into the unit never have been
unionized, and may reject joining a union.
   Coors considers the bargaining unit to be about 3,500 employees
who work in the brewery, two can plants, a bottle plant and a
corrugated cardboard plant.
   The union wants the unit to contain only the 1,500 brewery
workers, consistent with its bargaining units at other plants.
   The Teamsters wants to organize all Coors workers eventually, but
it does not want non-brewery employees included in its initial
contract.
   ``People who brew beer have one kind of job, and people who blow
glass have another,'' Klare said. ``The work weeks are different,
the problems are differnt, and there are diffent skills.''
   Coors, however, has considered its brewery and packaging workers
as one operating unit for nine years, officials said.
   ``They are together in terms of compensation, internal promotions
and other things, said John Meadows, Coors community relations
director.
   The unionization effort at Coors began in August after the
AFL-CIO ended its 10-year boycott in exchange for Coors agreeing not
to interfere with an organizing drive.
   The drive began as the Teamsters and the International
Association of Machinists competed for the right to represent Coors
workers. In March, the AFL-CIO gave the Teamsters the right to the
workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
