<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Scotus-Merger     06-06 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Merger,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Study Fraud Damage Awards in Georgia Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to hear an
appeal,stemming from a 19-year-old business merger, that could
affect the size of damage awards in some fraud cases.
   The court said it will review a ruling in a Georgia case that
limited the ability of purported fraud victims to sue an accounting
firm.
   The case arises out of the 1969 merger of Cavalier Bag Co. and
E.T. Barwick Industries Inc.
   The owners of Cavalier Bag _ Myles, Guy-Kenneth and Robert
Osterneck _ charged in a 1975 lawsuit that the financial health of
Barwick Industries had been overstated.
   The Osternecks sued Barwick officials and Ernst & Whinney, the
accounting firm that prepared the allegedly inflated financial
statements.
   After nearly a decade of pre-trial maneuvering, the case went to
trial in 1984 and the Barwick company and its officials were ordered
to pay the Osternecks more than $2.6 million in damages plus
$946,000 in interest.
   But the Osternecks lost their case against Ernst & Whinney.
   They then sought to appeal, seeking additional damages from the
accounting firm.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that their bid for
more damages must be treated as a motion to amend the original
judgment that the Osternecks had won.
   The appeals court, therefore, barred the Osternecks from pursuing
their related appeal to bring Ernst & Whinney back into the case.
   ``The rules of appellate procedure are designed to prevent
precisely what has occurred in this case _ the piecemeal appeal of
non-final substantive judgments rendered'' by federal judges, the
appeals court said.
   The case is Osterneck vs. Ernst & Whinney, 87-1201.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
