<HEAD>Help-Wanted Advertising Held Steady In April, Survey Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Conference Board said Monday its Help Wanted
Advertising Index held steady at 158 in April, compared to its
performance in March.
   The index measures the volume of classified advertising in 51
major newspapers across the nation and is sensitive to changes in
demand for labor, according to the business-supported research group.
   ``Labor market trends have become perplexing,'' Kenneth
Goldstein, a Conference Board economist, said in a news release.
   He noted that employment has continued to rise since last
November in spite of no significant strengthening in help-wanted
advertising volume.
