<HEAD>Trio Launches Investment Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two top executives of Metromedia Co. and a former
director of PaineWebber Group Inc. have joined forces to set up a $1
billion investment boutique specializing in leveraged buyouts.
   The partnership, to be called Kluge Subotnick Perkowski & Co.,
expected to invest in friendly buyouts in a variety of industries
both in the United States and abroad, according to a statement
issued Monday.
   The general partners are Metromedia Chairman John W. Kluge,
Metromedia Executive Vice President Stuart Subotnick, and John F.
Perkowski, a 15-year veteran of PaineWebber, where he served as
director of the investment banking division.
   Subotnick and Kluge will contribute $100 million for initial
capitalization, but the parternship expects to raise another $900
million from limited partners.
   Metromedia is a privately held partnership with interests in
telecommunications, robotic painting and computer software. The
company recently acquire Ponderosa Restaurants and a majority
interest in Orion Pictures.
   It previously owned and operated the largest independent
television broadcasting company in the nation, among other
businesses.
