<DOCNO> AP880606-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1942EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OhioTakeover     06-06 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ohio Takeover,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lower Court Told to Review Ohio Takeover Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Monday ordered a lower
court to re-examine its 1986 ruling that an Ohio law regulating
corporate takeovers is unconstitutional.
   A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled 2-1 that U.S. District Judge John Holschuh of Columbus should
review whether his 1986 ruling is still valid.
   Although the 6th Circuit court upheld Holschuh's ruling later
that year, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned it in 1987 and sent it
back to the 6th Circuit for reconsideration.
   Lawyers representing Ohio contend that Holschuh's decision still
leaves in question whether the state's takeover law is valid.
   On Monday, a majority of the 6th Circuit court's three-judge
panel decided Holschuh's court is the proper forum for the review.
In a minority dissent, appeals Judge Cornelia Kennedy said she would
have upheld Holschuh's ruling that Ohio's law, enacted in 1982,
illegally conflicts with provisions of the Williams Act, a federal
law governing tender offers.
   The Ohio law, known formally as the Ohio Control Share
Acquisition Act, forbids a suitor from acquiring more than 20
percent of a company's stock without the approval of its
shareholders.
   Holschuh's 1986 ruling came in a lawsuit brought by Fleet
Aerospace Corp., a Canadian aerospace company that used its
challenge of the Ohio law to successfully take over Aeronca Inc. of
Charlotte, N.C., a commercial and military subcontractor that
operates an aerospace division based in Middletown, Ohio.
   Aeronca initially fought the takeover but ultimately agreed to an
improved bid and now operates as a subsidiary of Fleet Aerospace.
   Lawyers for Fleet Aerospace now argue that the case is moot
because the takeover has been completed and is successful. But
lawyers for Ohio, which appealed Holschuh's ruling, want the case
kept alive. They argue that Ohio has a legitimate interest in seeing
that its laws are constitutional and that it be allowed to enforce
them.
   Ohio's lawyers say the law is a legitimate way of letting the
state regulate potential takeovers of Ohio corporations and also
protect Ohio shareholders who buy stock in out-of-state companies
that become takeover targets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
