<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted a modest gain today,
overcoming some early selling to extend last week's strong rally.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had jumped a
record 114.86 points last week, rose another 3.91 to 2,075.21.
   The average was down more than 13 points at its midsession low.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
854 up, 641 down and 476 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came 152.46 million shares,
against 189.60 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 176.71 million shares.
   Interest rates rose in the government bond market early Monday,
reversing last week's sharp decline.
   Analysts said that provided stock traders with an incentive to
sell issues that bounced upward in the market's recent surprise
rally.
   In addition, they said, many investors continued to view the
upswing in share prices skeptically, questioning its prospective
staying power.
   But as the session neared its close, bond prices recovered to
finish mixed. Selling pressure on stocks never developed much
intensity, and once it became clear that the market was holding its
ground buyers stepped in again.
   Macmillan Inc. climbed 3{ to 75. The Robert M. Bass Group raised
its takeover bid for the company from $64 a share to $73 a share.
   Avon Products fell { to 23[ in active trading. The company said
late last week it plans to sell its health-care operations and cut
its annual dividend from $2 a share to $1 a share.
   On Monday, however, it said its second-quarter earnings were
running ``well ahead of plan.''
   Among the blue-chip industrials, Ford Motor rose 1\ to 50{;
American Express } to 27; International Paper | to 43~;
International Business Machines 1[ to 114], and DuPont } to 86[.
   Texaco gained ~ to 50~. The company announced an agreement to
sell its West German operation to a German concern for more than
$1.2 billion, marking the first step in a planned restructuring.
   Ducommun Inc., traded on the American Stock Exchange, picked up ]
to 3|. A group that includes members of the Ducommun family said it
had increased its stake in the company to 9.5 percent of the shares
outstanding.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $5.84 billion, or 0.22
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.24 to 150.55.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose .99 to 308.57, and S&P's
500-stock composite index was up .60 at 267.05.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
advanced 2.48 to 379.34. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 301.94, up 1.06.
