<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly against most major
currencies Monday in response to indications that West Germany was
trying to stall the U.S. currency's recent advance.
   Gold also fell in price. Republic National Bank of New York said
gold was bid at $463.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from
$464 an ounce late Friday.
   A report by West Germany's central bank Monday surprised traders
by indicating the bank had quietly sold at least $2 billion in the
last week of May. Such a move lowered its huge dollar reserves and
helped slow the dollar's recent rise.
   Karl Otto Poehl, president of the Bundesbank, said over the
weekend that the central bank was not interested in a higher dollar
and a lower mark. A lower mark could increase West German inflation.
   After falling against the mark, the dollar lost ground against
other major currencies except the Canadian dollar.
   Keiichi Udagawa, chief currency trader of the Bank of Tokyo, said
he considered the dollar's decline a brief ``correction'' in an
upward trend, but said he joined in selling dollars Monday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.04 yen to a closing 126.07 yen. Later in London,
it was quoted higher at 126.22 yen. At the end of the trading day in
New York the dollar fell to 125.76 yen from 125.97 late Friday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.8025 from late Friday's
$1.8005. Later in New York, sterling rose to $1.8006 from $1.7970
late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.7134 West German marks, down from 1.7266; 1.4279
Swiss francs, down from 1.4391; 1.2321 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2314; 5.8015 French francs, down from 5.8333; and 1,273.88 Italian
lire, down from 1,283.75.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.7190 West German marks, down from 1.7248; 1.4357
Swiss francs, down from 1.4363; 5.8122 French francs, down from
5.8293; 1.9303 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9355; 1,277.65 Italian
lire, down from 1,282.00, and 1.2324 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2311.
   Traders said the Bank of England's increase in a key money market
intervention rate failed to support the pound because it had been
predicted and acted upon in advance.
   In Hong Kong, gold bullion rose to $464.39 a troy ounce from
Saturday's $463.71 an ounce.
   European gold trading was dull, as attention in metal markets
focused on silver. The late bid price in London for gold was $463.50
a troy ounce, down from late Friday's bid of $464.75.
   In Zurich, the late bid price was $464.50, down from $465.50 late
Friday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $462.90 a troy ounce from $464.80 an ounce.
   Silver was quoted in London late Monday at a bid price of $7.34 a
troy ounce, up from Friday's $7.31. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $7.270 a troy ounce from $7.225.
</TEXT>
