<HEAD>Joint Venture Would Combine Two Truck Leasing Outits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GE Capital and Penske Corp. announced
Monday they have reached an agreement in principle to form a joint
venture that would combine Penske's Hertz Penske truck-leasing unit
with GE Capital's Gelco truck-leasing business.
   The new joint venture will create a leading national full service
truck-leasing and rental company with more than 56,000 vehicles and
more than 400 service and maintenance facilities, the companies said
in a statement.
   The venture, to be owned jointly by Penske and GE Capital, will
have combind ssets of $1.5 billion and revenues of about $750
million, the companies said. It will employ 5,500 people.
   Roger S. Penske, chairman of Penske Corp., will be named chairman
and chief executive officer of the new company, and Brian Hard,
Hertz Penske executive vice president, will serve as president and
chief operating officer.
   Hertz Penske Truck Leasing Inc., which Penske formed in 1982 as a
joint venture with the Hertz Corp., is based in Reading, Pa.
   The company is a subsidiary of New Jersey-based Penske Corp., a
privately-held transportation service company. Penske will exercise
its option to purchase Hertz' interest in Hertz Penske prior to
entering into the joint venture with GE Capital.
   Gelco Truck Leasing, which was purchased by GE Capital in October
1987, along with other protions of Gelco Corp., provides
full-service truck leasing, rental and a variety of motor freight
transportation services to commerical clients nationwide.
   GE Capital, with net earning assets in excess of $36 billion, is
one of the nation's largest diversified financial services companies.
</TEXT>
