<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LTVModernization     06-06 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LTV Modernization,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LTV Steel Proposes $1 Billion Modernization In Cleveland Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Steel Co. on Monday unveiled a $1.13 billion
modernization proposal that is contingent on the approval of tax
abatements in Cleveland and Cuyahoga Heights.
   The company, a subsidiary of Dallas-based LTV Corp., would invest
the money at its Cleveland Works, which employs more than 6,000
people, LTV Steel said in a news release. LTV Corp. is reorganizing
under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code.
   ``The Cleveland Works is the largest flat rolled steel complex in
North America and has a reputation for superior quality, but without
these investments in new technology and equipment, it will quickly
fall behind in the competitive race we are running with the top
steelmakers in the U.S., Japan, Korea and Europe,'' said David H.
Hoag, LTV Steel's president and chief executive officer.
   The proposed, seven-year modernization would include construction
of a facility to produce ultra-low carbon steels and the renovation
of coke and by-products operations, the company said. It also
includes the renovation of three blast furnaces and improvements to
the 84-inch rolling complex.
   LTV Steel said legislation would be introduced in Cleveland and
Cuyahoga Heights to secure abatements on tangible personal property
taxes. The legislation wouldn't apply to $442 million worth of
capital improvements, which are not eligible under enterprise zone
criteria and would produce $6.8 million in taxes a year, LTV said.
</TEXT>
