<DOCNO> AP880606-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Brazil-Debt     06-06 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Debt ,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Finance Ministry Announces End Of Debt Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Finance Ministry said Monday Brazil
had closed a $4 billion agreement for new loans with international
bankers in New York after lengthy negotiations on the country's $121
billion foreign debt.
   In New York, a spokesman for the 14-member bank committee said it
had a rule of not commenting on the negotiations and issued no
statement on the announcement by Brazilian Finance Minister Mailson
da Nobrega. But knowledgeable bank sources who requested anonymity
said that some pending issues remained unresolved and that
negotiations were continuing Monday with Brazilian representatives
in New York.
   Da Nobrega, at a news conference in Brasilia, said the new
agreement was not linked with an accord with the International
Monetary Fund.
   Brazil's two main debt negotiators cut off talks two weeks ago
over the issue of whether or not the IMF had to give the green light
before creditors would sign an agreement with Brazil.
   Da Nobrega said the committee of 14 banks in New York
representing Brazil's 700 creditors found the agreement acceptable.
   ``Together we are finding a solution to the debt,'' da Nobrega
said.
   Under the agreement, he said, Brazil will receive $4 billion in
new bank loans now, plus $600 million later in 1988 and another $600
million in 1989, for a total of $5.2 billion.
   He said the 1989 payment was subject to Brazil meeting the goals
set by the country's IMF-approved economic program. Da Nobrega said,
however, that this accord has not yet been signed because of legal
details.
   In February 1987 Brazil suspended its $1 billion monthly debt
payments, saying the country was broke. Inflation was running at a
1,000 percent annual rate, the trade surplus had tumbled from $1
billion to $1 million a month, and currency reserves had dipped
below $4 billion.
   In January of this year, Brazil resumed payments but said it
would only officially suspend the moratorium after an agreement with
creditors.
   A sticking point in negotiations between Brazil and creditors
since 1986 has been IMF approval of the country's economic programs.
Brazil argues that the IMF policies are recessionary and impinge
upon its national sovereignty.
   Since early this year, however, Brazil has eased its criticisms
of the IMF and agreed to monitoring by that institution. For
political reasons, Brazil does not want an IMF go-ahead linked to
new loans, political analysts have said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
