<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MergerRescind     06-06 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Merger Rescind,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Seeks Rescission Of Corn Mill Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission announced Monday
that it is moving to require the merger of two major dry corn mills
to be rescinded.
   Illinois Cereal Mills Inc.'s acquisition of Lincoln Grain Co.
from Elders Grain Inc. could substantially reduce competition in the
production of dry corn products in the United States, the FTC said.
   The commission said it has directed its staff to seek a federal
court injunction blocking the move or requiring it to be rescinded.
The merger, which had been planned to be completed Tuesday, was
moved up to last Sunday, the commission noted.
   Dry corn mill products include flaking grits, used for corn
flakes; brewer's grits, used in beer, and corn meal, used in a
variety of foods.
   Illinois Cereal is based in Paris, Ill. Elders is a subsidiary of
Elders IXL Ltd., one of Australia's largest companies. Lincoln Grain
Co. is based in Atchison, Kan.
</TEXT>
