<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1945EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoTalks 1stLd-Writethru   06-06 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0510</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with further comment from Bieber, Greenwald;
further details of contract; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers union and
Chrysler Corp. made their new two-year labor pact official Monday,
signing the agreement covering 66,000 workers.
   Chrysler Motors Chairman Gerald Greenwald and UAW President Owen
Bieber traded lighthearted barbs during the signing ceremony. Top
negotiators and bargaining team members signed the settlement
agreements covering production, maintenance, parts, office,
technical and clerical workers.
   ``It's a good contract, one that we're extremely happy with, one
that provides some benefits and protection from a job security
standpoint,'' Bieber said. ``And I think the fact that we were able
to put it together early ought to speak well for future
negotiations.''
   Greenwald said, ``We had had a bit of a bumpy ride preceding
these national contract negotiations.''
   ``Nevertheless, between the union and Chrysler, we have been able
to achieve an early contract agreement which means that all of us
... are now able to concentrate on our equal goals of quality and
productivity without any concern of work interruption that would
have otherwise taken place under a September deadline,'' the auto
executive said.
   The contract has been in effect since May 16, when it replaced a
three-year agreement that would have expired Sept. 14.
   The new contract expires in September 1990, the same time as
agreements between the UAW and General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor
Co. GM and Ford reached agreements with the UAW last fall.
   The contract guarantees a set number of jobs at each Chrysler
plant, warehouse or office except in cases of cuts in production
volume brought on by slow sales.
   Workers received a $1,000 signing bonus and will have profit
sharing in future years. UAW Chrysler Vice President Mark Stepp said
one of the chief gains of the bargaining was Chrysler's unsolicited
promise to withhold executive bonuses in years when workers fail to
qualify for profit-sharing.
   ``We got a foot in the door with this agreement. ... The kind of
antagonism and the kind of ill feeling against excessive
compensation will fade in the future,'' Stepp said.
   The No. 3 automaker and the UAW began early negotiations April 18
as a way to cool rising tensions brought on by Chrysler's
consideration of a $2 billion offer for its 28,000-worker Acustar
Inc. parts subsidiary and the company's decision to close a
5,500-worker assembly plant in Kenosha, Wis.
   The tentative agreement was reached May 4 and eliminated the
possibility of a strike in September, which some felt was likely
because of the anger of rank-and-file workers over the proposed
Acustar sale and the Kenosha closing.
   Bieber said he was unconcerned by the relatively small margin by
which the contract was approved. He said the turmoil during
negotiations and the fact that 50 percent of the rank-and-file
failed to cast votes during the ratification process contributed to
the 54 percent approval.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
