<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Tate-StaleySale     06-06 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tate-Staley Sale,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tate & Lyle Sells Off Staley Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tate & Lyle PLC announced Monday it has
signed an agreement to sell off the food-service subsidiary of
Staley Continental Inc. to Sysco Corp., a Texas-based food
distributor, for $700 million in cash.
   The takeover of Staley by the London-based Tate & Lyle also was
completed Monday.
   The British company had announced its plan to sell Staley's
food-service distribution and manufacturing subsidiary, CFS
Continental, when it launched its takeover of Staley on April 8.
   Tate & Lyle officials said Monday its agreement to sell CFS
Continental to the Houston-based Sysco is subject to normal closing
conditions.
   The $700 million in cash is to be paid on closing day, which is
expected in midsummer, Tate & Lyle said. The cash payment also will
be adjusted to reflect changes in CFS Continental's working capital
and fixed assets since April 30.
   ``We are very pleased to have reached an agreement so quickly for
the sale of CFS Continental as a unit and to a company that will be
able to take advantage of its potential,'' said Neil M. Shaw,
chairman and chief executive of Tate & Lyle.
   ``With this behind us, we are eager to move forward with
returning Staley's headquarters to Decatur and to proceed with
running Staley's corn refining business, thereby building on the
company's strengths in the U.S. sweetener industry,'' Shaw said in a
statement.
   On May 13, Tate & Lyle and Staley signed an agreement to merge
Staley with RP Acquisition Corp., a wholly owned subisidary of Tate
& Lyle.
   Sysco is a leading distributor of food and related products to
the food service industry, serving restuarants, educational
institutions, nursing homes and hotel and motel chains.
   It also distributes frozen foods to supermarkets in several major
metropolitian areas, and has about 83 distribution facilities and
cash and carry outlets in 30 states.
   In 1987, Sysco reported a profit of $61.8 million on sales of
$3.66 billion.
</TEXT>
