<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 2154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Gillette-Coniston     06-06 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gillette-Coniston,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coniston Says Gillette Misled Stockholders About Potential Suitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. had discussions with at least two
potential suitors this year and one in 1987, even though it told
stockholders during a proxy fight that no one was interested in
buying the company, a New York-based investment firm charged in
court documents made public Monday.
   Coniston Group, which has been involved in a long and bitter
battle to gain control of Gillette, also accused the personal care
giant of paying greenmail to avoid a hostile 1986 takeover bid by
Revlon Group Inc.
   Gillette admitted in court documents that it held discussions
with one company in September 1987 and others this year but denied
they involved talk of a possible takeover.
   The allegations were made in a countersuit filed by Coniston in
federal court in April charging Gillette with misrepresenting facts
in legal action and in material sent to stockholders before a proxy
vote that month.
   Gillette sued Coniston for allegedly failing to disclose all its
financial backers before the proxy vote in April, in which
shareholders rejected Coniston's attempt to gain control of
one-third of Gillette's board of directors.
   U.S. District Judge Rya Zobel placed the countersuit and other
documents under seal but made them public Monday after she reviewed
them. The trial in the lawsuits is scheduled to start next Monday.
   In its countersuit, Coniston charges that Gillette:
   _Signed confidentiality agreements in November 1986 with nine
potential ``white knights'' interested in buying the company. In the
agreements, Gillette gave the companies access to confidential
information in exchange for a promise not to buy Gillette securities
without company approval for two years.
   _Paid greenmail when it bought Revlon's more than 9 million
shares of Gillette stock in November 1986 at $59.50 a share, or
$3.125 a share above market price, to avoid a hostile takeover.
   _Paid $9 million to Revlon's investment banker, Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., in exchange for a promise not to arrange or provide
financing for purchase of Gillette securities for three years.
   _Hired a private investigator to research Coniston members
dealings around the world.
   _Presented to stockholders misleadingly favorable earnings
projections.
   In its 31-page point-by-point response, Gillette charges that
Coniston's claim is ``repetitive and irrelevant'' and ``a tool in
the Coniston Group's public relations campaign against Gillette.''
   Gillette called the agreements with the nine companies ``standard
procedure,'' denied they were suitors, denied paying greenmail to
Revlon and charged that Coniston painted the dealings ``in a
blatantly false and miseleading manner in attempt to mislead
stockholders.''
   Coniston ``mischaracterizes totally the nature of the
communications,'' Gillette spokesman David Fausch said. ``Gillette
was approached by certain parties who were merely inquiring whether
the company had any interest in discussing certain types of
transactions.
   ``The interests were not attractive to Gillette ... and the
inquiries were not sufficiently concrete or detailed to warrant
action,'' he said.
   At its April 21 annual meeting, Gillette shareholders rejected by
52 percent to 48 percent Coniston's slate of four candidates for the
12-member Gillette board.
   Coniston, which controls about 5.8 percent of Gillette shares,
launched a proxy battle in February and pledged to convince the
other eight directors to sell Boston-based Gillette if its
candidates were elected.
   The countersuit, filed by two Coniston subsidiaries, RB
Associates of New Jersey and Bahamas-based RB Partners, seeks
dismissal of Gillette's suit and ``some equitable relief.'' Zobel is
to consider the countersuit first.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
