<FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 2204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TimberStrike     06-06 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Timber Strike,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walkout in Northwest Over Restoration of Lost Wages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. CRUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 4,500 union workers walked off their
jobs Monday at lumber mills and plywood plants in the Pacific
Northwest in a showdown over efforts to restore wages and benefits
lost two years ago.
   The strike shut down 18 wood products operations in Oregon,
Washington and Montana. Willamette Industries Inc. of Portland,
Champion International Corp. of Stamford, Conn., and DAW Forest
Products Co. of Lake Oswego were affected by the walkout.
   The surprise walkout followed the collapse last week of talks
between the three companies and two unions _ the International
Woodworkers of America-U.S. and the Western Council of Industrial
Workers, both based in Portland.
   The unions have vowed to win restoration of wages and benefits
lost in 1986 after a series of unsuccessful strikes.
   The first step toward restoration was taken last week when the
unions announced a tentative agreement with Bohemia Inc. of Eugene.
Union officials said the four-year pact largely restored wages lost
two years ago.
   The unions want to use the Bohemia agreement as an industry
standard, but other companies so far have rejected it.
   Dennis Elder, a spokesman for Champion in Milltown, Mont., said
his company did not think the Bohemia agreement ``represents a
standard for the wood products industry.''
   Talks broke down Friday after Champion made a counter-proposal,
but Elder said the company was ready to go back to the bargaining
table.
   ``This is a strike that did not have to happen,'' he said.
   Talks with Willamette also broke down after the company's
counter-proposal was rejected, said spokeswoman Cathy Baldwin.
   ``We've expressed a willingness to meet any time they're willing
to meet and bargain and compromise,'' she said.
   The two unions represent about 1,300 workers at five lumber
mills, four plywood mills, two wood products plants, a machine shop
and a logging shop operated by Willamette in Lebanon, Sweet Home,
Dallas and Albany, Ore.
   The IWA bargains for 450 workers at Champion's Roseburg, Ore.,
plywood plant. The WCIW represents about 200 Champion workers at a
Klickitat, Wash., sawmill, and 1,800 Champion workers at sawmills
and plywood plants at Missoula, Bonner and Libby, Mont.
   Contracts at Klickitat and Libby expire later this summer, but
workers stayed out Monday, honoring picket lines set up by workers
from other mills.
   Members of both unions voted overwhelmingly a month ago to
authorize their negotiators to call strikes if necessary.
   Elder and Baldwin said their companies had no immediate plans to
reopen their operations.
   Baldwin said Willamette's three-year offer included bonuses the
first two years and a 3.5 percent wage increase the third year.
   The average plywood worker, making $9.77 per hour, would gross an
additional $2,777 over the life of the contract, she said.
   Elder declined to discuss Champion's last offer.
   Union leaders oppose bonuses because the base wage rate remains
the same, although annual wages are boosted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
